The book was widely acclaimed on its release and remains so; it is regarded as one of the premier adventure novels and one of Verne's greatest works, along with Around the World in Eighty Days and Journey to the Center of the Earth.

Kenneth Charles Williams ( 22 February 1926 – 15 April 1988 ) was an English actor . He was best known for his comedic roles in the British "Carry On" film series and as a panelist on the popular BBC radio game show "Just a Minute." Throughout his four-decade career, Williams captivated audiences with his wit, signature nasal voice, and exceptional comedic timing. Aside from his film and radio work, Williams was also a notable stage actor, appearing in numerous West End productions, as well as being a TV personality, frequently guest-starring in talk shows and variety programs.

(All Women Do It, or The School for Lovers), K. 588, is an opera buffa in two acts by Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart. It was first performed on 26 January 1790 at the Burgtheater in Vienna, Austria. The libretto was written by Lorenzo Da Ponte who also wrote Le nozze di Figaro and Don Giovanni.Although it is commonly held that  was written and composed at the suggestion of the Emperor Joseph II, recent research does not support this idea. There is evidence that Mozart's contemporary Antonio Salieri tried to set the libretto but left it unfinished.

A pegmatite is an igneous rock showing a very coarse texture , with large interlocking crystals usually greater in size than 2.5 centimeters. They are formed from highly viscous silicate-rich magma during the slow cooling process, which promotes the growth of large mineral crystals. Pegmatites can be found worldwide and contain important deposits of various valuable minerals such as lithium, rare earth elements, beryl, and gemstones like tourmaline, topaz, and aquamarine. Intrusions of pegmatites in other rock types are common in orogenic belts where metamorphism occurs due to intense heat and pressure. This can create striking rock patterns and open cavities where exquisite crystal formations develop.

The United Nations Foundation is a charitable organization headquartered in Washington , DC , that supports the United Nations and its various initiatives. Established in 1998, the Foundation is committed to promoting global peace, security, sustainable development, and human rights by connecting donors and various stakeholders with the UN's efforts. The United Nations Foundation engages in fundraising, issue-based campaigns, public outreach, and collaboration with a wide network of UN partners. Major focuses include eradicating poverty, providing support for global health and the environment, empowering women and youth, and strengthening partnerships to support UN activities.

Purple is any of a variety of colors with hue between red and blue. In the RGB color model used in computer and television screens, purples are produced by mixing red and blue light. In the RYB color model historically used by painters, purples are created with a combination of red and blue pigments. In the CMYK color model used in printing, purples are made by combining magenta pigment with either cyan pigment, black pigment, or both.Purple has long been associated with royalty, originally because Tyrian purple dye, made from crushed shells, was extremely expensive in antiquity.

Rococo ( , also ) , less commonly Roccoco or Late Baroque , is an exceptionally ornamental and theatrical style of architecture, art, and design that originated in France in the early 18th century. It flourished in Europe during the 1730s-1740s and evolved from the earlier, more formal Baroque aesthetic. Characterized by intricate detailing, graceful curves, pastel colors, and the use of gold leaf, Rococo showcases themes of playfulness, romanticism, and elaborate ornamentation. Significant artists of this movement include Jean-Antoine Watteau, François Boucher, and Jean-Honoré Fragonard, whose masterpieces exude a lighthearted, whimsical quality in composition and subject matter.

Giuseppe Saverio Raffaele Mercadante ( baptised 17 September 179517 December 1870 ) was an Italian composer , particularly of operas . Born in Altamura, Italy, Mercadante grew to become a central figure in 19th century Italian music, working contemporaneously with iconic composers such as Rossini, Donizetti, and Verdi. He initially started learning the flute but soon developed an interest in composing. With over 50 operas to his name, Mercadante's works demonstrate a clear evolution from traditional bel canto opera styles to more dramatic structures, paving the way for later Italian Romantic composers.

Note : This compilation includes only those attacks that resulted in casualties . Attacks which did not kill or wound anyone have been excluded from this list. While it is important to acknowledge and analyze all instances of violence, the purpose of this particular compilation is to highlight the attacks that have had the most significant impact on human lives. This approach provides a clearer picture of the severity and consequences of such acts. It also emphasizes the pressing need for concerted efforts in combating and preventing terrorism and violent extremism in all its forms.

The Jagiellonian University ( Polish : Uniwersytet Jagielloński ( UJ ) ) is a public research university in Kraków , Poland. Established in 1364 by King Casimir III the Great, it is the oldest university in Poland and one of the oldest in Europe. Ranked as one of the top universities in Central Europe, the Jagiellonian University boasts a rich history and has fostered intellectual excellence, including notable alumni such as Nicolaus Copernicus and Pope John Paul II. Today, it offers a wide range of programs and disciplines, focusing on humanities, natural and social sciences.

Monte Cassino ( today usually spelled Montecassino ) is a rocky hill about southeast of Rome , in the Latin Valley, Italy. The site is renowned for its historical and architectural significance, mainly as the home of the Montecassino Abbey, the oldest monastery in Europe. Founded by Saint Benedict in 529 AD, it has played a pivotal role in shaping Western European monastic culture. Throughout history, the abbey has been severely damaged and restored multiple times, with the most notable destruction during the Battle of Monte Cassino in World War II. The hill's strategic position also made it a significant battleground in previous wars.

Edward Teller (; January 15, 1908 – September 9, 2003) was a Hungarian-American theoretical physicist who is known colloquially as "the father of the hydrogen bomb" (see the Teller–Ulam design), although he did not care for the title, considering it to be in poor taste. Throughout his life, Teller was known both for his scientific ability and for his difficult interpersonal relations and volatile personality.Born in Hungary in 1908, Teller emigrated to the United States in the 1930s, one of the many so-called "Martians", a group of prominent Hungarian scientist émigrés.

Blake Edwards ( born William Blake Crump ; July 26 , 1922 – December 15 , 2010 ) was an American filmmaker and screenwriter. Over the course of his six-decade long career, Edwards gained immense success in multiple film genres, including comedy, drama, and musicals. Some of his most iconic work includes directing and co-writing the highly celebrated Pink Panther series featuring Peter Sellers, as well as classic films like Breakfast at Tiffany's, 10, and Victor Victoria. Often collaborating with his wife, Julie Andrews, Edwards displayed an impeccable gift for storytelling, pushing boundaries, and delving into deep emotional subject matters.

An ion thruster , ion drive , or ion engine is a form of electric propulsion used for spacecraft propulsion . It works by accelerating ions through an electric field, providing a nearly continuous and highly efficient propulsive force. Ion engines typically have much lower thrust compared to chemical rocket engines but make up for it with significantly higher specific impulse – a measure of fuel efficiency. This allows ion-propelled spacecraft to travel further, using less propellant than traditional chemical rockets. In the past decades, ion thrusters have been utilized for deep space exploration, satellite orbit adjustment, and interplanetary missions.

In celestial mechanics , escape velocity or escape speed is the minimum speed needed for a free , non-propelled object to break away from the gravitational attraction of a massive celestial body, like a planet or moon. The concept plays a critical role in space travel, particularly for launching space probes and rockets to explore and navigate within our solar system and beyond. The precise value of escape velocity depends on the mass and radius of the celestial body as well as the distance of the object from its center. Consequently, the escape velocity of Earth is approximately 11.2 km/s, while for the Moon it is about 2.38 km/s.

Pope John XXII (; 1244 – 4 December 1334), born Jacques Duèze (or d'Euse), was head of the Catholic Church from 7 August 1316 to his death in 1334.He was the second and longest-reigning Avignon Pope, elected by the Conclave of Cardinals, which was assembled in Lyon through the work of King Louis X's brother Philip, the Count of Poitiers, later King Philip V of France. Like his predecessor, Clement V, Pope John centralized power and income in the Papacy and lived a princely life in Avignon.

Bi-curious is a term for a person , usually someone who is a heterosexual , who is curious or open to experimenting or exploring romantic or sexual attractions and activities with people of the same sex. While being bi-curious does not necessarily mean that an individual identifies as bisexual, it suggests a willingness or curiosity to explore new experiences and attractions beyond their traditional gender preferences. These individuals may want to further understand their sexuality by interacting or forming relationships with individuals from their own or opposite sex without necessarily assigning themselves to a specific sexual identity or label.

The World Federation of Trade Unions ( WFTU ) is an international federation of trade unions . WFTU was established in October 1945 and is now headquartered in Athens, Greece. Representing approximately 100 million workers from 130 countries, it strives to create a unified international trade union movement to address common worker issues like inequality, globalization, and exploitation. Through solidarity and common action, the WFTU aims to safeguard workers' rights, establish fair living standards, and create safe working conditions. Collaborating with regional organizations, it prioritizes building class-oriented trade union movements, preserving social rights, and challenging the multinational domination on the global workforce.

Script Creation Utility for Maniac Mansion ( SCUMM ) is a video game engine developed at Lucasfilm Games , later renamed LucasArts, in the late 1980s. SCUMM was designed by Ron Gilbert, a visionary game designer and programmer, to facilitate the development process of point-and-click adventure games. The engine garnered popularity through iconic games like Maniac Mansion, The Secret of Monkey Island, and Day of the Tentacle. SCUMM utilized a scripting language that made game creation more accessible, leading to faster and smoother production cycles. Though no longer actively used, SCUMM left an indelible mark on the history of gaming and its advancements in game design.

Theories of political behavior, as an aspect of political science, attempt to quantify and explain the influences that define a person's political views, ideology, and levels of political participation. Political behavior is the subset of human behavior that involves politics and power. Theorists who have had an influence on this field include Karl Deutsch and Theodor Adorno.Long-term influences on political orientationInteraction with the political views of parental figures is often thought of as the primary long-term influence on political orientation and willingness to take part in the political system.Teachers and other educational authority figures are also often thought to have a significant impact on political orientation.

The IAI RQ-5 Hunter unmanned aerial vehicle ( UAV ) was originally intended to serve as the United States Army 's primary reconnaissance and surveillance platform. Developed in the early 1990s by the Israel Aircraft Industries (IAI), it entered service in 1996 as the U.S Army's first field-operational UAV. The RQ-5 Hunter's capabilities included real-time data and imagery gathering, battlefield management support, target acquisition, and even target designation for indirect-fire weapons. However, advancements in drone technology and the emergence of advanced systems such as the General Atomics MQ-1 Predator UAV ultimately led to its replacement in 2015, leaving a significant legacy in military aviation history.

Domenico Cimarosa (; 17 December 1749 – 11 January 1801) was an Italian composer of the Neapolitan school and of the Classical period. He wrote more than eighty operas, the best known of which is Il matrimonio segreto (1792); most of his operas are comedies. He also wrote instrumental works and church music.Cimarosa was principally based in Naples, but spent some of his career in various other parts of Italy, composing for the opera houses of Rome, Venice, Florence and elsewhere. He was engaged by the empress of Russia Catherine the Great as her court composer and conductor between 1787 and 1791.

François Marie Adrien Maurice Mitterrand (26 October 19168 January 1996) served as President of France from 1981 to 1995, the longest time in office in the history of France. As First Secretary of the Socialist Party, he was the first left-wing politician to assume the presidency under the Fifth Republic.Reflecting family influences, Mitterrand started political life on the Catholic nationalist right. He served under the Vichy Regime during its earlier years. Subsequently he joined the Resistance, moved to the left, and held ministerial office several times under the Fourth Republic. Mitterrand opposed Charles de Gaulle's establishment of the Fifth Republic.

Lumbar disc disease is the drying out of the spongy interior matrix of an intervertebral disc in the spine. Many physicians and patients use the term lumbar disc disease to encompass several different causes of back pain or sciatica. In this article, the term is used to describe a lumbar herniated disc. It is thought that lumbar disc disease causes about one-third of all back pain.SymptomsPain, loss of muscle strength and loss of touch sensation may occur if this herniation causes the compression of the most proximal part of the nerve closely neighbouring the intervertebral disc material.

Year 1030 ( MXXX ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. In this year, the Byzantine Empire experienced the Battle of Azaz, wherein Emperor Romanos III faced a heavy defeat against the Mirdasid emirate of Aleppo, contributing to further chaos in the empire. This year also witnessed the creation of Theotokos Panachrantos church in Constantinople, which displays architectural brilliance even today. Notably, St. Sophia cathedral, one of the oldest stone churches in Russia, began its construction in Kiev around this time, profoundly impacting the regional culture and history.

was the 68th emperor of Japan , according to the traditional order of succession.Go-Ichijō 's reign spanned the years from 1016 until his death in 1036. Born to Emperor Ichijō and Empress Fujiwara no Kenshi, his personal name was originally Atsuhira-shinnō. During Go-Ichijō's reign, Japan was in a period of cultural and artistic growth, referred to as the Heian period. Significant events during his rule included the continuation of the development of Japanese calligraphy, poetry, and court life. The Fujiwara clan retained power as regents and important advisers, playing a key role in shaping politics and government affairs.

was the 68th emperor of Japan, according to the traditional order of succession.Go-Ichijō's reign spanned the years from 1016 through 1036.This 11th century sovereign was named after Emperor Ichijō and go- (後), translates literally as "later;" and thus, he is sometimes called the "Later Emperor Ichijō", or, in some older sources, may be identified as " Emperor Ichijō, the second. "BiographyBefore his ascension to the Chrysanthemum Throne, his personal name (imina) was Atsuhira -shinnō (敦成親王). He was also known as Atsunari-shinnō.Atsuhira was the second son of Emperor Ichijō.

Edward Higgins White II (November 14, 1930 – January 27, 1967) was an American aeronautical engineer, United States Air Force officer, test pilot, and NASA astronaut. He was a member of the crews of Gemini 4 and Apollo 1.After graduating from West Point in 1952 with a Bachelor of Science degree, White was sent to flight training, and assigned to the 22nd Fighter Day Squadron at Bitburg Air Base, West Germany, where he flew the F-86 Sabre and F-100 Super Sabre fighters. In 1958, he enrolled in the University of Michigan to study aeronautical engineering.

Paclitaxel (PTX), sold under the brand name Taxol among others, is a chemotherapy medication used to treat a number of types of cancer. This includes ovarian cancer, esophageal cancer, breast cancer, lung cancer, Kaposi's sarcoma, cervical cancer, and pancreatic cancer. It is administered by intravenous injection. There is also an albumin-bound formulation.Common side effects include hair loss, bone marrow suppression, numbness, allergic reactions, muscle pains, and diarrhea. Other serious side effects include heart problems, increased risk of infection, and lung inflammation. There are concerns that use during pregnancy may cause birth defects.

Year 959 (CMLIX) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  April - May – The Byzantines refuse to pay the yearly tribute. A Hungarian army, led by Apor, invades Macedonia and Thrace. He plunders its territories until reaching Constantinople. On his way back, Apor is defeated during a night attack by Byzantine forces. November 9 – Emperor Constantine VII Porphyrogennetos ("born in the purple") dies at Constantinople after a 46-year reign. He is succeeded by his 21-year-old son Romanos II as ruler of the Byzantine Empire.

Brighella ( in Bergamasque dialect : Brighèla ) is a comic , masked character from the Italian theatre style Commedia dell'Arte. This form of theatre began in the 16th century and rapidly gained popularity in Europe due to its highly improvised nature, humorous plotlines, and ensemble of dynamic stock characters. Brighella is typically portrayed as a cunning, deceitful, and highly adaptive character, often occupying roles such as servant or middle-class citizen. He has a dark and untrustworthy side while possessing an undeniable charm, which enables him to take advantage of others.

Cranial nerves are the nerves that emerge directly from the brain ( including the brainstem ) , of which there are 12 pairs in humans. These nerves relay information between the brain and various parts of the body, including the head, neck, and facial regions, as well as control various essential functions such as vision, hearing, and taste. Each cranial nerve has a specific function or a combination of sensory, motor, or parasympathetic functions. Examples of cranial nerves include the optic nerve, which transmits visual signals, and the vagus nerve, which regulates several key autonomic processes throughout the body.

Year 873 (DCCCLXXIII) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Carloman, son of King Charles the Bald, is hailed before a secular court and condemned to death – for plotting against his father. He is blinded, but avoids imprisonment by escaping to the East Frankish Kingdom, where his uncle, Louis the German, gives him protection. Al-Andalus: The city of Toledo (modern Spain) rises up for a second time against Umayyad rule, due to ethnic tensions over two years.

Depleted uranium ( DU ; also referred to in the past as Q-metal , depletalloy or D-38 ) is uranium with a reduced proportion of the isotope uranium-235. It is primarily composed of uranium-238 and is a byproduct of the nuclear fuel cycle, typically obtained through the reprocessing of spent nuclear fuel rods. DU is characterized by its high density, which makes it an ideal choice for certain military applications such as armor-piercing projectiles and as counterweights in aircraft. However, its use remains controversial due to potential health risks and environmental impacts, especially when pulverized and inhaled in large amounts after an explosion or impact.

Monte Cassino (today usually spelled Montecassino) is a rocky hill about  southeast of Rome, in the Latin Valley, Italy,  west of Cassino and at an elevation of . Site of the Roman town of Casinum, it is widely known for its abbey, the first house of the Benedictine Order, having been established by Benedict of Nursia himself around 529. It was for the community of Monte Cassino that the Rule of Saint Benedict was composed.The first monastery on Monte Cassino was sacked by the invading Lombards around 570 and abandoned. Of the first monastery almost nothing is known.

New Sweden ( ; ; ) was a Swedish colony along the lower reaches of the Delaware River in America from 1638 to 1655, established during the peak of Swedish imperialism under Queen Christina and the leadership of Governor Johan Björnsson Printz. Spanning parts of present-day Delaware, New Jersey, and Pennsylvania, New Sweden included Swedish, Finnish, and Dutch settlers who engaged primarily in agriculture and trade. Conflicts eventually arose with Dutch New Netherland and English colonies, culminating in a Dutch takeover in 1655. Despite its short existence, the colony left lasting legacies, such as introducing the American log cabin and preserving strong Swedish heritage in the region.

Peperomia ( radiator plant ) is one of the two large genera of the family Piperaceae . Most of them are compact, small perennial epiphytes growing on rotten wood. They have over 1,500 recorded species, which display an impressive variety of leaf shapes, sizes, and colors. These plants are native to tropical and subtropical regions across the world, with the highest concentration found in Central and South America. Peperomia plants make excellent houseplants as they are low-maintenance, requiring little water and attention. They can also effectively clean the indoor air and can thrive in lower light conditions.

Antioch on the Orontes ( ; , Antiókheia hē epì Oróntou ; also Syrian Antioch ) was a Hellenistic city established in the 4th century BCE by Seleucus I Nicator, a general of Alexander the Great, and one of his successors. Strategically located on the crossroads between Europe and Asia, the city rapidly flourished and became one of the greatest and most cosmopolitan metropolises in the ancient world. Its notable attractions included impressive fortifications, a royal palace, and the colossal Hippodrome that hosted breathtaking chariot races. Its melting pot of cultures nurtured vibrant intellectual life, resulting in advancements in art, architecture, philosophy, and even early Christianity.

Gerard Adams (; born 6 October 1948) is an Irish republican politician who was the president of Sinn Féin between 13 November 1983 and 10 February 2018, and served as a Teachta Dála (TD) for Louth from 2011 to 2020. From 1983 to 1992 and from 1997 to 2011, he followed the policy of abstentionism as a Member of Parliament (MP) of the British Parliament for the Belfast West constituency.In 1984, Adams was seriously wounded in an assassination attempt by several gunmen from the Ulster Defence Association (UDA), including John Gregg.

Year 1045 (MXLV) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January 20 – Pope Sylvester III becomes the 146th pope, succeeding Benedict IX, who abdicated during the previous year. January 23 – Edward the Confessor, King of England, marries Edith of Wessex, and begins construction of Westminster Abbey in England. February – Pope Sylvester III is deposed (election deemed invalid); Pope Benedict IX is elected once more, becoming the 147th pope. February 5 – Emperor Go-Reizei ascends the throne of Japan.

Activision Publishing , Inc. is an American video game publisher based in Santa Monica , California . It serves as the operating subsidiary of Activision Blizzard and is one of the leading gaming companies in the industry. Established in 1979, Activision has built a strong reputation for creating innovative and immersive gaming experiences. They are best known for their wildly successful game franchises like Call of Duty, Tony Hawk's Pro Skater, Skylanders, Destiny, and Crash Bandicoot. The company strives to push the boundaries of game development while nurturing and growing its diverse creative talent, consistently earning it critical acclaim and the admiration of gamers worldwide.

( All Women Do It , or The School for Lovers ) , K. 588 , is an opera buffa (All Women Do It, or The School for Lovers), K. 588, is an opera buffa composed by the prolific musical genius, Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart. The story unfolds through the satirical lens of various romantic entanglements, as the central characters embark on their hilarious, heartfelt journey to discover and understand love. Throughout the masterfully crafted arias and witty banter, the dynamic protagonists explore themes of betrayal, seduction, jealousy, and the transformative nature of passion, all while maneuvering within their distinct social strata.

Columbia Business School (CBS) is the business school of Columbia University in the City of New York in Manhattan, New York City. Established in 1916, Columbia Business School is one of six Ivy League business schools and is one of the oldest business schools in the world. In 2022, it was ranked as the 2nd best business school.History The school was founded in 1916 with 11 full-time faculty members and an inaugural class of 61 students, including 8 women. Banking executive Emerson McMillin provided initial funding in 1916, while A. Barton Hepburn, then president of Chase National Bank, provided funding for the School's endowment in 1919.

Steven C. McConnell is an author of software engineering textbooks such as Code Complete , Rapid Development , and Software Estimation: Demystifying the Black Art. He is renowned for his expertise in software development methodologies, project management, and estimation techniques. With over two decades of experience, Steven has significantly impacted the field of software engineering and helped many developers improve their skills through his books, lectures, and insightful contributions to online discussions. His pragmatic approach towards software development, keen observations on industry best practices, and relatability make Steven's writings essential references for software professionals across the globe.

The Hippocratic Oath is an oath of ethics historically taken by physicians. It is one of the most widely known of Greek medical texts. In its original form, it requires a new physician to swear, by a number of healing gods, to uphold specific ethical standards. The oath is the earliest expression of medical ethics in the Western world, establishing several principles of medical ethics which remain of paramount significance today. These include the principles of medical confidentiality and non-maleficence. As the seminal articulation of certain principles that continue to guide and inform medical practice, the ancient text is of more than historic and symbolic value.

A funeral home , funeral parlor or mortuary , is a business that provides burial and funeral services for the deceased and their families. These services may include embalming, cremation, memorial services, and arranging for the interment or inurnment of the remains in a final resting place. Funeral homes can also offer services such as grief counseling, assistance with paperwork and documentation, funeral pre-planning, and coordinating with the cemetery, clergy or religious leaders, florists, musicians, and transportation. With an unwavering focus on professionalism, compassion, and empathy, the funeral home plays a vital role in assisting bereaved families during their most difficult time.

In chemistry , a nucleophile is a chemical species that forms bonds with electrophiles by donating an electron pair . In simpler terms, a nucleophile is an electron-rich molecule or ion that actively seeks an electron-deficient species, also known as electrophiles, to bond with. This affinity between nucleophiles and electrophiles is due to their inherent electron donating and accepting behavior, respectively, making them significant components in a myriad of chemical reactions. An example of such reaction is the formation of covalent bonds in which nucleophiles donate their electron pairs to the electrophiles.

Linus Carl Pauling ( ; February 28 , 1901 – August 19 , 1994 ) was an American chemist , biochemist, peace activist, author, and educator, widely considered as one of the greatest scientists of the 20th century. Born in Portland, Oregon, Pauling showed an early interest in chemistry, conducting experiments in his childhood. After completing his studies at Oregon Agricultural College and the California Institute of Technology, he dedicated his life to pioneering research, developing groundbreaking contributions to areas such as quantum chemistry, molecular biology, and inorganic chemistry.

Svante August Arrhenius ( , ; 19 February 1859 – 2 October 1927 ) was a Swedish scientist . Originally a physicist, Arrhenius later became interested in chemistry and contributed significantly to the field. He is best known for his groundbreaking research in the area of electrolytic dissociation and his work on the behavior of dissolved substances in water. His discoveries and equations facilitated an increased understanding of how acids, bases, and salts interact in solutions. Additionally, he provided the earliest estimates of Earth's greenhouse effect, establishing the basic principles behind global warming.

Kingston is the capital and largest city of Jamaica , located on the southeastern coast of the island . It boasts a population of approximately 670,000 people and serves as the island's cultural, economic, and political hub. The city's vibrant culture can be witnessed through its pulsating music scene, lively festivals, and colorful street art. A key port for trade, Kingston also thrives on industries such as tourism, manufacturing, and telecommunications. Some major attractions in Kingston include the famous Bob Marley Museum, the historic Devon House, and the natural beauty of Blue Mountains National Park.

An inverse multiplexer ( often abbreviated to inverse MUX or IMUX ) allows a data stream to be broken into several lower-speed streams, which are then transmitted simultaneously over multiple separate channels. The primary function of an inverse multiplexer is to enable the transmission of high-speed data over multiple low-capacity links by optimizing available bandwidth. This technique is particularly beneficial when higher-speed connections are unavailable, costly, or when several lower-capacity links need to be utilized efficiently. At the receiving end, the inverse demultiplexer recombines the lower-speed streams back into a single data stream for proper interpretation and decoding.

A musician is a person who composes , conducts , or performs music . According to the United States Employment Service, there are over 124,000 professional musicians in the United States. Music is often associated with emotions and transcending cultural barriers, and thus it plays a vital role in society. Many musicians have an array of diverse roles including songwriting, singing, playing musical instruments, orchestrating or arranging scores, and producing records. Although careers in music vary, they share the ultimate goal of engaging, entertaining and inspiring audiences through their creative expression and connection.

The Hoysala Empire was a Kannadiga power originating from the Indian subcontinent that ruled most of what is now Karnataka, India between the 10th and the 14th centuries. The capital of the Hoysalas was initially located at Belur but was later moved to Halebidu.The Hoysala rulers were originally from Malenadu, an elevated region in the Western Ghats. In the 12th century, taking advantage of the internecine warfare between the Western Chalukya Empire and Kalachuris of Kalyani, they annexed areas of present-day Karnataka and the fertile areas north of the Kaveri delta in present-day Tamil Nadu.

Montevideo  is the capital and largest city of Uruguay. According to the 2011 census, the city proper has a population of 1,319,108 (about one-third of the country's total population) in an area of . Montevideo is situated on the southern coast of the country, on the northeastern bank of the Río de la Plata.The city was established in 1724 by a Spanish soldier, Bruno Mauricio de Zabala, as a strategic move amidst the Spanish-Portuguese dispute over the platine region. It was also under brief British rule in 1807, but eventually the city was retaken by Spanish criollos.

"The Ones Who Walk Away from Omelas" is a 1973 work of short philosophical fiction by American writer Ursula K. Le Guin. With deliberately both vague and vivid descriptions, the narrator depicts a summer festival in the utopian city of Omelas, whose prosperity depends on the perpetual misery of a single child. "The Ones Who Walk Away from Omelas" was nominated for the Locus Award for Best Short Fiction in 1974 and won the Hugo Award for Best Short Story in 1974.PlotThe only chronological element of the work is that it begins by describing the first day of summer in Omelas, a shimmering city of unbelievable happiness and delight.

Bruce Lee (; November 27, 1940 – July 20, 1973), born Lee Jun-fan , was a Hong Kong and American martial artist, martial arts instructor, actor, director, screenwriter, producer, and philosopher. He was the founder of Jeet Kune Do, a hybrid martial arts philosophy drawing from different combat disciplines that is often credited with paving the way for modern mixed martial arts (MMA). Lee is considered by critics, media, and other martial artists to be the most influential martial artist of all time and a pop culture icon of the 20th century, who bridged the gap between East and West.

Toilet humour, or potty or scatological humour (compare scatology), is a type of off-colour humour dealing with defecation, constipation, urination and flatulence, and to a lesser extent vomiting and other bodily functions. It sees substantial crossover with sexual humour, such as dick jokes.Toilet humour is commonly an interest of children and young teenagers, for whom cultural taboos related to acknowledgement of waste excretion still have a degree of novelty. The humour comes from the rejection of such taboos, and is a part of modern culture.MusicToilet humour is sometimes found in song and rhyme, particularly schoolboy songs.

The Hoysala Empire was a Kannadiga power originating from the Indian subcontinent that ruled most of what is now Karnataka , a southern Indian state, during the 10th-14th centuries. The empire was named after the lion emblem ('hoy' meaning "strike" and 'sala' meaning "lion"), representing their dynastic identity. The Hoysalas emerged as a fierce power by promoting economic and cultural prosperity, showcasing remarkable achievements in art, architecture, and military power. Many prominent structures, such as the Chennakeshava temple in Belur and Hoysaleshwara temple in Halebidu, exemplify the exuberant artistic craftsmanship that prospered during their reign.

The heart is a muscular organ in most animals , which pumps blood through the blood vessels of the circulatory system. It accomplishes this vital task by rhythmically contracting and relaxing, enabling blood to flow to all parts of the body and supply oxygen, nutrients, and other essential elements required for survival. As blood circulates, it also aids in waste removal and supports the body's natural defense mechanisms. The heart's function and health are influenced by factors such as genetics, age, diet, and exercise, emphasizing the importance of a balanced lifestyle in maintaining heart health and reducing the risk of heart-related ailments.

Gossypium is a genus of flowering plants in the tribe Gossypieae of the mallow family , Malvaceae , from which cotton is harvested. It is native to tropical and subtropical regions around the world, including Africa, Asia, and the Americas. There are over 50 species of Gossypium, varying in fiber quality, yield, and environmental adaptability. Cotton, being a major cash crop, contributes significantly to the economies of cotton-producing countries. The soft, fluffy staple fiber of Gossypium has versatile uses, such as in the manufacturing of textiles, clothing, and various consumer goods.

Plotinus ( ; , Plōtînos ; – 270 CE ) was a philosopher in the Hellenistic tradition , born and raised in Roman Egypt. As a key figure in the development of Neoplatonism, a school of philosophy that focused on the concepts of unity and the absolute, Plotinus was highly influential on subsequent generations of philosophers and theologians. Drawing on the teachings of Plato, Aristotle, and earlier thinkers, Plotinus centered his work on the central role of the human soul, striving towards its spiritual home—the realm of the transcendent One, or Good.

Pope Leo VII (; died 13 July 939) was the bishop of Rome and nominal ruler of the Papal States from 3 January 936 to his death.Election Leo VII's election to the papacy in 936, after the death of Pope John XI, was secured by Alberic II of Spoleto, the ruler of Rome at the time. Alberic wanted to choose the pope so that the papacy would continue to yield to his authority. Leo was the priest of the church of San Sisto Vecchio in Rome, thought to be a Benedictine monk.

Nord (; officially ; ; , ), is a department in Hauts-de-France region, France bordering Belgium. It was created from the western halves of the historical counties of Flanders and Hainaut, and the Bishopric of Cambrai. The modern coat of arms was inherited from the County of Flanders.Nord is the country's most populous department. It also contains the metropolitan region of Lille (the main city and the prefecture of the department), the fourth-largest urban area in France after Paris, Lyon and Marseille. Within the department is located the part of France where the French Flemish dialect of Dutch has historically been spoken as a native language.

The oxidation state , or oxidation number , is the hypothetical charge of an atom if all of its bonds to other atoms were completely ionic. It is an important concept in chemistry, as it helps to determine the distribution of electrons within a compound and also dictates an atom's ability to gain or lose electrons during reactions. The sum of oxidation states within a compound must equal its overall charge. Calculating oxidation states assists in balancing chemical reactions and understanding reactivity trends within elements. Factors influencing the oxidation state include electronegativity and the atom's position within the periodic table, making it a key concept in predicting chemical behavior.

Igor Fyodorovich Stravinsky ( 6 April 1971 ) was a Russian composer , pianist and conductor , later of French (6 April 1882 – 6 April 1971) was a Russian composer, pianist, and conductor, later of French nationality and eventually, an American citizen. Regarded as one of the most influential composers of the 20th century, he incorporated distinct styles into his works, often creating avant-garde pieces that shook the foundation of traditional classical music. His compositions covered a variety of genres, such as ballets, orchestral works, and choral music.

Year 870 (DCCCLXX) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  August 8 – Treaty of Meerssen: King Louis the German forces his half-brother Charles the Bald to accept a peace treaty, which partitions the Middle Frankish Kingdom into two larger east and west divisions. Louis receives most of Austrasia (which evolves into the Kingdom of Germany), and Charles receives territory in Lower Burgundy (which evolves into the Kingdom of France). However, large parts of the Frisian coast are under Viking control.

Medina , officially Al Madinah Al Munawwarah and also commonly simplified as Madīnah or Madinah , is the second-holiest city in Islam, after Mecca. Located in the Hejaz region of western Saudi Arabia, Madinah is revered for being the burial site of the Prophet Muhammad, who spent his last days in this city, leading the Muslim community from 622 CE until his death in 632 CE. It houses the Prophet's Mosque (Al-Masjid An-Nabawi), the second largest mosque in the world, attracting millions of Muslims for pilgrimage throughout the year, during both Hajj and Umrah seasons.

The Etruscan civilization  of ancient Italy covered a territory, at its greatest extent, of roughly what is now Tuscany, western Umbria, and northern Lazio, as well as what are now the Po Valley, Emilia-Romagna, south-eastern Lombardy, southern Veneto, and western Campania.The earliest evidence of a culture that is identifiably Etruscan dates from about 900BC. This is the period of the Iron Age Villanovan culture, considered to be the earliest phase of Etruscan civilization, which itself developed from the previous late Bronze Age Proto-Villanovan culture in the same region. Etruscan civilization endured until it was assimilated into Roman society.

Dorset ( ; archaically : Dorsetshire ) is a county in South West England on the English Channel coast . The area, comprising mainly of rural landscape and picturesque coastline, is renowned for its rich history, cultural heritage, and striking natural beauty. Notable landmarks include the Jurassic Coast, a World Heritage Site boasting some of the finest cliffs and rock formations that tell the story of Earth's prehistoric past. Along with bustling market towns and idyllic villages, Dorset is home to the popular resort towns of Bournemouth, Poole, and Weymouth, which offer golden sandy beaches and family-friendly attractions.

Montevideo is the capital and largest city of Uruguay . According to the 2011 census , the city proper has a population of 1,319,108, which represents approximately one-third of the country's total population. Established in 1724, Montevideo sits along the southern coast of Uruguay, making it a strategic port in the South Atlantic region. Known for its rich history, the city boasts numerous well-preserved buildings, museums, and vibrant cultural events that attract tourists from around the world. In recent years, Montevideo has emerged as a technology and startup hub, drawing international investors and entrepreneurs alike.

Hoysala architecture is the building style in Hindu temple architecture developed under the rule of the Hoysala Empire between the 11th and 14th centuries, primarily in the region of modern-day Karnataka in South India. The style is characterized by elaborate carvings, detailed sculptures, ornate pillared halls, and uniquely-shaped vimanas, or temple sanctum towers. One key feature is the intricate use of soapstone, which allowed for extensive detailing and lasting resilience. Hoysala temples are distinguished by the intricately-carved base, known as a Jagati, featuring images of mythology, epics, and natural scenes.

Éraic ( or eric ) was the Irish equivalent of the Welsh galanas and the Anglo-Saxon and Scandinavian weregild , a system of restitution in ancient and medieval societies wherein a person found guilty of a wrongful act or crime was required to make monetary or material reparations to the wronged party or their family. It was seen as a way to maintain harmony and social order by compensating for a perceived loss or damage, thereby avoiding a cycle of violent feuds and vengeance. In early Irish society, éraic values were carefully laid out in Brehon Laws and often varied according to social rank and nature of the wrongdoing.

The National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration ( NOAA ) is an American scientific and regulatory agency within the United States Department of Commerce focused on studying the conditions of the Earth's atmosphere and oceans. It monitors and forecasts weather, conducts research on climate and ecosystems, and manages oceanic and atmospheric resources. Established in 1970, NOAA provides crucial data to safeguard coastal areas and communities, maintain sustainable economies, and ensure public health and safety. In collaboration with partner organizations and governments, NOAA strives to better understand environmental changes, share actionable scientific knowledge, and drive innovations that lead to healthier environments for current and future generations.

A jubilee is a particular anniversary of an event , usually denoting the 25th , 40th , 50th , 60th , or 75th anniversary of significant milestones in a person's life, a monarchy, or other notable events. These celebrations often serve as an opportunity to reflect upon past achievements and accomplishments, as well as renew and strengthen relationships and aspirations for the future. Traditionally, a jubilee event involves gatherings, special ceremonies, or performances dedicated to the respective occasion. Many organizations and institutions also participate, such as churches or community groups, to make the occasion even more memorable for all those involved.

Henry Dunant (born Jean-Henri Dunant; 8 May 182830 October 1910), also known as Henri Dunant, was a Swiss humanitarian, businessman and social activist. He was the visionary, promoter and co-founder of the Red Cross. In 1901, he received the first Nobel Peace Prize together with Frédéric Passy, making Dunant the first Swiss Nobel laureate.During a business trip in 1859, Dunant was witness to the aftermath of the Battle of Solferino in modern-day Italy. He recorded his memories and experiences in the book A Memory of Solferino which inspired the creation of the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) in 1863.

The following outline is provided as an overview of and topical guide to the history of South Asia : History of South Asia – South Asia, also known as the Indian subcontinent, comprises eight countries: India, Pakistan, Bangladesh, Sri Lanka, Nepal, Bhutan, Maldives, and Afghanistan. It boasts a rich historical heritage shaped by numerous civilizations, religions, and cultures. Over the course of centuries, South Asia has been subjected to various conquests and interactions, resulting in a multitude of linguistic, social, political, and artistic influences.

In the philosophy of mathematics, the abstraction of actual infinity involves the acceptance (if the axiom of infinity is included) of infinite entities as given, actual and completed objects. These might include the set of natural numbers, extended real numbers, transfinite numbers, or even an infinite sequence of rational numbers. Actual infinity is to be contrasted with potential infinity, in which a non-terminating process (such as "add 1 to the previous number") produces a sequence with no last element, and where each individual result is finite and is achieved in a finite number of steps.

Year 976 (CMLXXVI) was a leap year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  January 10 – Emperor John I Tzimiskes dies at Constantinople, after returning from a second campaign against the Abbasids in Syria. He is buried in the Church of Christ Chalkites, and succeeded by his 18-year-old nephew Basil II, who becomes sole ruler of the Byzantine Empire. The administration remains in the hands of Basil Lekapenos (an illegitimate son of the late Emperor Romanos I). Europe  June – Emir Abu'l-Qasim launches a raiding expedition into Byzantine Italy from Sicily.

was the 75th emperor of Japan, according to the traditional order of succession.Sutoku's reign spanned the years from 1123 through 1142.GenealogyBefore his ascension to the Chrysanthemum Throne, his personal name (his imina) was Akihito (顕仁). Sutoku was the eldest son of Emperor Toba. Some old texts say he was instead the son of Toba's grandfather, Emperor Shirakawa.Chūgū: Fujiwara no Kiyoko (藤原 聖子) later Kōkamon'in (皇嘉門院), Fujiwara Tadamichi’s daughter Hyounosuke-no-Tsubone (兵衛佐局), Minamoto Masamune's adopted daughter First son: Imperial  (1140–1162).

The word  comes from the Japanese word for logographic characters of the Chinese script, which were made a major part of the Japanese writing system along with the syllabic scripts of hiragana and katakana. More specifically, it refers to that set of Chinese characters directly incorporated into the written Japanese language with often Japanese pronunciation, inclusive of those few characters invented in Japan based on character components derived from other Chinese characters.The term kanji literally means "Han characters", and this word is spelled in Japanese using the same characters as traditional Chinese in reference to the character writing system, which is known as hanzi .

Soil is a mixture of organic matter, minerals, gases, liquids, and organisms that together support life. Earth's body of soil, called the pedosphere, has four important functions: as a medium for plant growth as a means of water storage, supply and purification as a modifier of Earth's atmosphere as a habitat for organismsAll of these functions, in their turn, modify the soil and its properties.Soil is also commonly referred to as earth or dirt; some scientific definitions distinguish dirt from soil by restricting the former term specifically to displaced soil.

Charles University , known also as Charles University in Prague ( ( UK ) ; ; ) or historically as the University of Prague, is the oldest and most prestigious university in the Czech Republic. Founded in 1348 by Charles IV, Holy Roman Emperor, and the King of Bohemia, it has a rich academic and cultural heritage. It serves as a leading research institution, boasting numerous eminent alumni, such as astronomer Johannes Kepler, writer Franz Kafka, and philosopher Jan Patočka. With 17 faculties, Charles University covers a wide range of disciplines including humanities, social sciences, natural sciences, and medicine.

Year 1170 (MCLXX) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place   Levant  Winter – Egyptian forces led by Saladin invade Palestine and besiege Darum on the Mediterranean coast. Its defenses are weak and though Saladin has no siege-engines with him, its fall seems imminent. King Amalric I withdraws his Templar garrison from Gaza, to assist him in defending Darum. Saladin raises the siege and marches on Gaza, where he captures the lower town (despite the stiff resistance ordered by Lord Miles of Plancy), and massacres the inhabitants.

Mercury ( ; ) is a major god in Roman religion and mythology , being one of the 12 Dii Consentes within the ancient Roman pantheon. He is the god of financial gain, commerce, eloquence, communication, travelers, boundaries, luck, and trickery. Mercury is the son of Jupiter and Maia, one of the Pleiades. Often depicted wearing a winged petasos (hat) and winged sandals, he is known for his speed and ability to travel between the mortal and divine realms. Mercury was a vital part of the Roman people's lives, as they relied heavily on trade, diplomacy, and cross-cultural communication.

A terrarium (plural: terraria or terrariums) is usually a sealable glass container containing soil and plants, and can be opened for maintenance to access the plants inside. However, terraria can also be open to the atmosphere rather than being sealed. Terraria are often kept as decorative or ornamental items. Closed terraria create a unique environment for plant growth, as the transparent walls allow for both heat and light to enter the terrarium. The sealed container combined with the heat entering the terrarium allows for the creation of a small scale water cycle.

Lieutenant General Henry Shrapnel (3 June 1761 – 13 March 1842) was a British Army officer whose name has entered the English language as the inventor of the shrapnel shell.Henry Shrapnel was born at Midway Manor in Bradford-on-Avon, Wiltshire, England, the ninth child of Zachariah Shrapnel and his wife Lydia.In 1784, while a lieutenant in the Royal Artillery, he perfected, with his own resources, an invention of what he called "spherical case" ammunition: a hollow cannonball filled with lead shot that burst in mid-air. He successfully demonstrated this in 1787 at Gibraltar.

Genus  (plural genera ) is a taxonomic rank used in the biological classification of living and fossil organisms as well as viruses. In the hierarchy of biological classification, genus comes above species and below family. In binomial nomenclature, the genus name forms the first part of the binomial species name for each species within the genus.E.g. Panthera leo (lion) and Panthera onca (jaguar) are two species within the genus Panthera. Panthera is a genus within the family Felidae.The composition of a genus is determined by taxonomists. The standards for genus classification are not strictly codified, so different authorities often produce different classifications for genera.

The European Bank for Reconstruction and Development ( EBRD ) is an international financial institution founded in 1991 . As a response to the collapse of communism in Central and Eastern Europe, the EBRD was established to support market-oriented economies and the private sector's development within these regions. Today, the EBRD invests in 38 countries across three continents, ranging from Estonia to Morocco and from Mongolia to Greece. By providing financial support, technical assistance, and policy advice, the bank plays a vital role in promoting economic growth, fostering innovation, and building a more sustainable and inclusive future for millions of people across these countries.

Antioch on the Orontes (; , Antiókheia hē epì Oróntou; also Syrian Antioch) was a Hellenistic city side of the Orontes River. Its ruins lie near the current city of Antakya, Turkey, to which the ancient city lends its name.Antioch was founded near the end of the fourth century BC by Seleucus I Nicator, one of Alexander the Great's generals. The city's geographical, military, and economic location benefited its occupants, particularly such features as the spice trade, the Silk Road, and the Royal Road. It eventually rivaled Alexandria as the chief city of the Near East.

Padthaway is a small town in the Australian state of South Australia located in the state's south-east within the Limestone Coast region about  south east of the state capital of Adelaide and about  south-east of the municipal seat of Bordertown. The name is derived from the Potawurutj, the Aboriginal name for Good Water. Padthaway is in the Tatiara District Council, the state electorate of MacKillop and the federal Division of Barker.The 2016 Australian census which was conducted in August 2016 reports that Padthaway had a population of 418 people.Wine regionPadthaway is also the name of a wine region surrounding the town.

François Marie Adrien Maurice Mitterrand ( 26 October 19168 January 1996 ) served as President of France from 1981 to 1995, making him the longest-serving President in French history. A member of the Socialist Party, Mitterrand's time in office was characterized by various progressive policies and a focus on social reform. Significant initiatives undertaken during his presidency included nationalizing key industries, implementing welfare state measures, increasing worker's rights, and boosting environmental protection efforts. Additionally, Mitterrand played a crucial role in shaping the development of the European Union by supporting its creation and expanding France's global influence.

Pope Gregory VII ( ; 1015 – 25 May 1085 ) , born Hildebrand of Sovana , was head of the Catholic Church and ruler of the Papal States from 22 April 1073 to his death in 1085. One of the most prominent figures during the Investiture Controversy, Pope Gregory VII's papacy saw him excommunicate the Holy Roman Emperor, Henry IV, as he endeavored to limit secular power over the Church. Gregory was dedicated to ecclesiastical reforms and initiated the Gregorian Reform, advocating clerical celibacy, ending the selling of ecclesiastical offices (simony), and combating other prevalent abuses.

KFC (also known as Kentucky Fried Chicken) is an American fast food restaurant chain headquartered in Louisville, Kentucky that specializes in fried chicken. It is the world's second-largest restaurant chain (as measured by sales) after McDonald's, with 22,621 locations globally in 150 countries . The chain is a subsidiary of Yum! Brands, a restaurant company that also owns the Pizza Hut, Taco Bell and WingStreet chains.KFC was founded by Colonel Harland Sanders, an entrepreneur who began selling fried chicken from his roadside restaurant in Corbin, Kentucky during the Great Depression.

Sir Philip Nicholas Outram Pullman ( born 19 October 1946 ) is an English writer . His books include the His Dark Materials trilogy, comprising of "Northern Lights" (1995), "The Subtle Knife" (1997), and "The Amber Spyglass" (2000). Sir Pullman has won numerous awards throughout his career, such as the prestigious Carnegie Medal, and was knighted in the 2019 New Year Honours list for his services to literature. His works often contain elements of fantasy, philosophy, and social commentary.

Henry Richard Enfield (born 30 May 1961) is an English comedian, actor, writer, and director. He is known in particular for his television work, including Harry Enfield's Television Programme and Harry & Paul, and for the creation and portrayal of comedy characters such as Kevin the Teenager and Loadsamoney.Early lifeBorn in Horsham, Sussex, he is the oldest of four children, the son of English television, radio and newspaper journalist and presenter Edward Enfield. He has three sisters. The Enfield family are descendants of the nineteenth-century philanthropist Edward Enfield.

Year 1025 ( MXXV ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. This particular year marked several significant events across the globe, especially in the realms of politics and religion. In Europe, Emperor Constantine VIII took control of the Byzantine Empire and became a prominent ruler. Over in Ireland, several High Kings vied for power, adding to the turmoil that had been a constant for decades. As far as religion was concerned, various religious institutions continued to grow, further asserting their influence in regional and local affairs.

The Arctic ( or ) is a polar region located at the northernmost part of Earth . The Arctic consists of the Arctic Ocean and parts of Canada, Russia, Greenland, the United States, Norway, Sweden, Finland, and Iceland. This frigid region is characterized by its unique flora, fauna, and indigenous cultures that have adapted to the extreme cold conditions. Temperatures in the Arctic are known to reach well below freezing point, making it an inhospitable environment for many living creatures. Nevertheless, various species, including polar bears, Arctic foxes, and reindeer, have developed survival strategies to thrive in these harsh conditions.

New Zealand consists of more than six hundred islands, mainly remnants of a larger land mass now beneath the sea. New Zealand is the seventh-largest island nation on earth, and the third-largest located entirely in the Southern Hemisphere. The following is a list of islands of New Zealand.Each of the two largest islands – where most of the human population lives – has two official names, in English and in the Māori language. They are the North Island or Te Ika-a-Māui and the South Island or Te Waipounamu. Various Māori iwi sometimes use other names, with some preferring to call the South Island Te Waka o Aoraki.

Dekker's algorithm is the first known correct solution to the mutual exclusion problem in concurrent programming. The solution is attributed to Dutch mathematician Th. J. Dekker by Edsger W. Dijkstra in an unpublished paper on sequential process descriptions and his manuscript on cooperating sequential processes. It allows two threads to share a single-use resource without conflict, using only shared memory for communication.It avoids the strict alternation of a naïve turn-taking algorithm, and was one of the first mutual exclusion algorithms to be invented.OverviewIf two processes attempt to enter a critical section at the same time, the algorithm will allow only one process in, based on whose turn it is.

Montague Rhodes James  (1 August 1862 – 12 June 1936) was an English author, medievalist scholar and provost of King's College, Cambridge (1905–1918), and of Eton College (1918–1936). He was Vice-Chancellor of the University of Cambridge (1913–15).James's work as a medievalist and scholar is still highly regarded, but he is best remembered for his ghost stories, which some consider among the best in the genre. He redefined the ghost story for the new century by abandoning many of the formal Gothic clichés of his predecessors and using more realistic contemporary settings.

Rococo (, also ), less commonly Roccoco or Late Baroque, is an exceptionally ornamental and theatrical style of architecture, art and decoration which combines asymmetry, scrolling curves, gilding, white and pastel colors, sculpted molding, and trompe-l'œil frescoes to create surprise and the illusion of motion and drama. It is often described as the final expression of the Baroque movement.The Rococo style began in France in the 1730s as a reaction against the more formal and geometric Louis XIV style. It was known as the "style Rocaille", or "Rocaille style".

Dotdash Meredith ( formerly About.com ) is an American digital media company that publishes articles and videos about various subjects across numerous verticals, including health, finance, travel, and technology. Founded in 1996, the company rebranded from About.com to Dotdash Meredith in 2021. With a team of experienced writers and experts, Dotdash Meredith aims to provide its users with trustworthy and in-depth information, catering to the constantly evolving interests and needs of a diverse online audience. Leveraging data-driven strategies, the company is committed to delivering timely, reliable, and valuable content for both novice and seasoned digital users around the globe.

Montague Rhodes James ( 1 August 1862 – 12 June 1936 ) was an English author , medievalist scholar and provost of King's College, Cambridge, and later of Eton College. He is best remembered for his ghost stories, which have been heralded as some of the most influential works of the horror genre. James developed a unique storytelling method that evoked suspense, which set him apart from contemporary horror fiction authors. Despite having several works published, it was his oral storytelling skills that made the biggest impact. Over the years, his stories have remained in print, enjoying various adaptions on both stage and screen.

The Martian Chronicles is a science fiction fix-up novel, published in 1950, by American writer Ray Bradbury that chronicles the exploration and settlement of Mars, the home of indigenous Martians, by Americans leaving a troubled Earth that is eventually devastated by nuclear war.SynopsisThe book projects American society immediately after World War II into a technologically advanced future where the amplification of humanity's potentials to create and destroy have both miraculous and devastating consequences.Events in the chronicle include the apocalyptic destruction of both Martian and human civilizations, both instigated by humans, though there are no stories with settings at the catastrophes.

Gregory of Nyssa, also known as Gregory Nyssen (; c. 335 – c. 395), was bishop of Nyssa, Cappadocia, from 372 to 376 and from 378 until his death. He is venerated as a saint in Roman Catholicism, Eastern Orthodoxy, Oriental Orthodoxy, Anglicanism, and Lutheranism. Gregory, his elder brother Basil of Caesarea, and their friend Gregory of Nazianzus are collectively known as the Cappadocian Fathers.Gregory lacked the administrative ability of his brother Basil or the contemporary influence of Gregory of Nazianzus, but he was an erudite theologian who made significant contributions to the doctrine of the Trinity and the Nicene Creed.

Domenico Gaetano Maria Donizetti ( 29 November 1797 – 8 April 1848 ) was an Italian composer , best known for his operas, particularly in the bel canto style. Born in Bergamo, Italy, Donizetti began his career in music early on under notable teacher Mayr, and gained popularity with the success of his first significant opera, "Zoraida di Granata" (1822). With an impressive output of nearly 75 operas throughout his career, some of his most renowned works include "Lucia di Lammermoor" (1835), "Don Pasquale" (1843), and "L'Elisir d'Amore" (1832).

Imre Lakatos ( , ; ; November 9 , 1922 – February 2 , 1974 ) was a Hungarian philosopher of science and mathematics, best known for his contributions to the philosophy of science, particularly the demarcation criterion between scientific and non-scientific theories. Born in Debrecen, Hungary, he initially pursued a career in mathematics before shifting to the philosophy of science under the influence of Karl Popper. He taught at the London School of Economics, developing his concept of research programmes, which aimed to clarify how scientific theories evolve and are revised over time.

Year 1107 (MCVII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Scotland January 8 – King Edgar (the Valiant) dies at Edinburgh Castle after a 9-year reign. He is succeeded by his brother Alexander I (the Fierce), who is married to Sybilla of Normandy (an illegitimate daughter of King Henry I). A split of unity, between Alexander and his younger brother David I, makes David co-ruler in Lothian and Strathclyde (Southern Scotland). He does not receive the title of king, but of "Prince of the Cumbrians".

Humour (Commonwealth English) or humor (American English) is the tendency of experiences to provoke laughter and provide amusement. The term derives from the humoral medicine of the ancient Greeks, which taught that the balance of fluids in the human body, known as humours (Latin: humor, "body fluid"), controlled human health and emotion.People of all ages and cultures respond to humour. Most people are able to experience humour—be amused, smile or laugh at something funny (such as a pun or joke)—and thus are considered to have a sense of humour.

Central Park is an urban park in New York City located between the Upper West and Upper East Sides of Manhattan. It is the fifth-largest park in the city by area, covering . It is the most visited urban park in the United States, with an estimated 42 million visitors annually , and is the most filmed location in the world.Following proposals for a large park in Manhattan during the 1840s, it was approved in 1853 to cover . In 1857, landscape architects Frederick Law Olmsted and Calvert Vaux won a design competition for the park with their "Greensward Plan".

The Battle of the Chesapeake, also known as the Battle of the Virginia Capes or simply the Battle of the Capes, was a crucial naval battle in the American Revolutionary War that took place near the mouth of the Chesapeake Bay on 5 September 1781. The combatants were a British fleet led by Rear Admiral Sir Thomas Graves and a French fleet led by Rear Admiral François Joseph Paul, the Comte de Grasse. The battle was strategically decisive, in that it prevented the Royal Navy from reinforcing or evacuating the besieged forces of Lieutenant General Lord Cornwallis at Yorktown, Virginia.

Today's New International Version (TNIV) is an English translation of the Bible which was developed by the Committee on Bible Translation (CBT). The CBT also developed the New International Version (NIV) in the 1970s. The TNIV is based on the NIV. It is explicitly Protestant like its predecessor; the deuterocanonical books are not part of this translation. The TNIV New Testament was published in March 2002. The complete Bible was published in February 2005. The rights to the text are owned by Biblica (formerly International Bible Society). Zondervan published the TNIV in North America.

Year 1493 ( MCDXCIII ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. In this year, noteworthy events took place that shaped the course of history. The renowned explorer, Christopher Columbus, returned from his monumental first voyage to the Americas in March. His discovery led to a significant expansion of European trade, ultimately forging stronger connections across various continents. Also during this period, Pope Alexander VI issued the Inter caetera papal bull, aiming to settle conflicts over territorial claims by the Spanish and Portuguese empires, ultimately creating the first demarcation line between them in the Atlantic Ocean.

Poznań University of Technology, PUT (Polish name: Politechnika Poznańska) is a university in Poznań, Poland. Poznań University of Technology is known as one of the best technical universities in Poland. URAP ranked PUT as in top 6% of world universities and Webometrics ranked it at no. 842 in the world by Google citations for the year 2015. In 1995 it became the first Polish university to become a member of the Conference of European Schools for Advanced Engineering Education and Research (CESAER), an organization comprising the best technical universities in Europe.

Pali is a Middle Indo-Aryan liturgical language native to the Indian subcontinent . It is widely studied because it is the language of many of the earliest and most substantial texts of the Buddhist tradition, including the Pali Canon, also known as the Tipiṭaka or "Three Baskets." Pali has thus been crucial for the study of Theravada Buddhism and ancient Indian philosophy, culture, and history. Even though Pali is no longer used as a spoken language, it remains a significant tool for scholars of Buddhism, and a few contemporary monastic communities still use it in religious practice.

In the 1980s, the telecommunications industry expected that digital services would follow much the same pattern as voice services did on the public switched telephone network, and conceived an end-to-end circuit switched service, known as Broadband Integrated Services Digital Network (B-ISDN).HistoryBefore B-ISDN, the original ISDN attempted to substitute the analog telephone system with a digital system which was appropriate for both voice and non-voice traffic. Obtaining worldwide agreement on the basic rate interface standard was expected to lead to a large user demand for ISDN equipment, hence leading to mass production and inexpensive ISDN chips.

In their most common sense, the terms thought and thinking refer to conscious cognitive processes that can happen independently of sensory stimulation. Their most paradigmatic forms are judging, reasoning, concept formation, problem solving, and deliberation. But other mental processes, like considering an idea, memory, or imagination, are also often included. These processes can happen internally independent of the sensory organs, unlike perception. But when understood in the widest sense, any mental event may be understood as a form of thinking, including perception and unconscious mental processes.

A finger is a limb of the body and a type of digit , an organ of manipulation and sensation found in the hands of humans and other primates. Typically, humans have five fingers on each hand, consisting of the thumb, index finger, middle finger, ring finger, and pinky finger. Each finger comprises multiple segments, connected by joints, and is equipped with nerves and muscles, enabling precise movements and dexterity. Furthermore, fingerprints located at the tips provide a unique identification pattern, enhancing grip on objects.

Fidelio , originally titled  (Leonore, or The Triumph of Marital Love), Op. 72, is Ludwig van Beethoven's only opera. The German libretto was originally prepared by Joseph Sonnleithner from the French of Jean-Nicolas Bouilly, with the work premiering at Vienna's Theater an der Wien on 20 November 1805. The following year, Stephan von Breuning helped shorten the work from three acts to two. After further work on the libretto by Georg Friedrich Treitschke, a final version was performed at the Kärntnertortheater on 23 May 1814.

The History of East Asia generally encompasses the histories of China , Japan , Korea , and Mongolia from prehistoric times to the present day. The East Asian region has been shaped by several defining events and eras that have contributed to its development, including the emergence of great empires and dynasties like the Han Dynasty, the Mongolian Empire under Genghis Khan, and the Japanese Shogunate. Notable historical periods, such as China's Imperial Dynastic Age and Japan's Edo Period, showcase a rich cultural exchange, territorial conquests, and diplomatic interactions.

Year 1036 ( MXXXVI ) was a leap year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. This year held significant events across various countries and cultures. In Europe, an important political event unfolded when Conrad II succeeded his son, Henry III, to become the King of Germany. Additionally, England was besieged with the turmoil caused by several ill-fated weather phenomena such as torrential rains, causing severe flooding across the nation, severely affecting agriculture and food supply. Over in Asia, India witnessed the rise of the Western Chalukya Empire under King Someshvara I.

Reptilia is Canada's largest indoor reptile zoo, with  of indoor exhibits featuring over 250 reptiles, amphibians and arachnids. It is accredited by CAZA.Currently there are two Ontario locations, one in Vaughan and one in Whitby.LocationsThe original Reptilia zoo was established in Vaughan; it is housed in a  facility. In 2018, it opened a second location in Whitby in a former  Rona store. In late 2018, it announced plans to create similar zoos in London and Barrie. London City Council rejected the proposal for a  reptile zoo in Westmount Mall.AttractionsAbout 250 species of reptiles are in the zoo's collection.

Turbo Pascal is a software development system that includes a compiler and an integrated development environment (IDE) for the Pascal programming language running on CP/M, CP/M-86, and DOS. It was originally developed by Anders Hejlsberg at Borland, and was notable for its extremely fast compiling times. Turbo Pascal, and the later but similar Turbo C, made Borland a leader in PC-based development.For versions 6 and 7 (last), both a lower-priced Turbo Pascal and more expensive Borland Pascal were produced; Borland Pascal was more oriented toward professional software development, with more libraries and standard library source code.

Numismatics is the study or collection of currency,  including coins, tokens, paper money, medals and related objects.Specialists, known as numismatists, are often characterized as students or collectors of coins, but the discipline also includes the broader study of money and other means of payment used to resolve debts and exchange goods.The earliest forms of money used by peoples is referred to as "Odd and Curious", but the use of other goods in barter exchange is excluded, even where used as a circulating currency (e.g., cigarettes in prison).

Salmon  is the common name for several species of ray-finned fish in the family Salmonidae. Other fish in the same family include trout, char, grayling, and whitefish. Salmon are native to tributaries of the North Atlantic (genus Salmo) and Pacific Ocean (genus Oncorhynchus). Many species of salmon have been introduced into non-native environments such as the Great Lakes of North America and Patagonia in South America. Salmon are intensively farmed  in many parts of the world.Typically, salmon are anadromous: they hatch in fresh water, migrate to the ocean, then return to fresh water to reproduce.

A spacecraft is a vehicle or machine designed to fly in outer space . A type of artificial satellite , a spacecraft is specifically engineered for space travel and exploration. Often used for various purposes such as scientific research, communication, military intelligence, or navigating our universe, these specialized vehicles play a significant role in deepening our understanding of space and its potential impacts on our world. Propelled by sophisticated propulsion systems, these state-of-the-art vehicles withstand the challenges of harsh space environments, while collecting valuable data and expanding human reach to the far corners of our solar system and beyond.

George Catlett Marshall Jr. ( December 31 , 1880 – October 16 , 1959 ) was an American army officer and statesman who rose to prominence during and after World War II. He served as Chief of Staff under Presidents Franklin D. Roosevelt and Harry S. Truman, and later as Secretary of State and Secretary of Defense under Truman. Marshall played a critical role in the Allied victory of World War II by overseeing the mobilization of American forces and orchestrating the overall military strategy. Following the war, Marshall helped devise the Marshall Plan, an ambitious aid initiative that helped rebuild Western Europe and set the foundation for the NATO alliance.

Year 878 (DCCCLXXVIII) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Britain  January 6 – King Alfred the Great is surprised by a Viking attack at Chippenham. He is forced to flee, with his retinue, into the Somerset Levels for safety. From his headquarters at Athelney, Alfred wages a guerrilla war against the Vikings. May – Battle of Edington: Supported by all the levies of Somerset, Wiltshire and Hampshire, Alfred the Great decisively defeats the main body of Danish Vikings, led by King Guthrum, at present-day Edington (near Bratton Castle).

Garnets  are a group of silicate minerals that have been used since the Bronze Age as gemstones and abrasives.All species of garnets possess similar physical properties and crystal forms, but differ in chemical composition. The different species are pyrope, almandine, spessartine, grossular (varieties of which are hessonite or cinnamon-stone and tsavorite), uvarovite and andradite.
