His works encompass various popular science fiction franchises such as the Star Wars Expanded Universe, The X-Files, Dune, and The Saga of the Seven Suns series. Additionally, Anderson has collaborated with multiple authors, most notably Brian Herbert, Frank Herbert's son, for continuing the legendary Dune saga. He also co-authored The Hellhole Trilogy, as well as various works set in the Dan Shamble, Zombie PI universe.

An ion thruster, ion drive, or ion engine is a form of electric propulsion used for spacecraft propulsion. It creates thrust by accelerating ions using electricity.An ion thruster ionizes a neutral gas by extracting some electrons out of atoms, creating a cloud of positive ions. These ion thrusters rely mainly on electrostatics as ions are accelerated by the Coulomb force along an electric field. Temporarily stored electrons are finally reinjected by a neutralizer in the cloud of ions after it has passed through the electrostatic grid, so the gas becomes neutral again and can freely disperse in space without any further electrical interaction with the thruster.

Alkanna tinctoria , the dyer 's alkanet or simply alkanet , is a herb in the borage family . Its main use is as a natural dye for textiles, cosmetics, and food. The plant is native to the Mediterranean region and can be found in rocky soils or disturbed habitats such as roadsides. Alkanet's vibrant red color is due to the presence of the pigment alkanin, which can be extracted from its roots. In traditional medicine, alkanet has been used to soothe skin inflammations and help in wound healing due to its antimicrobial and anti-inflammatory properties.

Fishing is the activity of trying to catch fish. Fish are often caught in the wild but may also be caught from stocked bodies of water. Techniques for catching fish include hand gathering, spearing, netting, angling and trapping. "Fishing" may include catching aquatic animals other than fish, such as molluscs, cephalopods, crustaceans, and echinoderms. The term is not normally applied to catching farmed fish, or to aquatic mammals, such as whales where the term whaling is more appropriate. In addition to being caught to be eaten, fish are caught as recreational pastimes.

Domenico Cimarosa ( ; 17 December 1749 – 11 January 1801 ) was an Italian composer of the Neapolitan school and opera buffa. Born in Aversa, near Naples, Cimarosa showed exceptional musical talent from a young age and was eventually accepted into the Conservatorio di Santa Maria di Loreto in Naples. His prolific career led him to compose over 60 operas and other diverse works, such as sacred music, orchestral compositions, chamber music, and keyboard pieces. His most famous opera, "Il matrimonio segreto," became an instant success following its premiere in 1792.

Isotope separation is the process of concentrating specific isotopes of a chemical element by removing other isotopes . The use of isotope separation is vital for various applications across several fields, such as medicine, nuclear power, research, and even nuclear weapons production. Techniques used for isotope separation include methods such as mass spectrometry, gas diffusion, and laser separation. In medical field, isotopes play a critical role, specifically in diagnostic imaging and cancer treatments like radiation therapy. Meanwhile, in nuclear power plants, the enriched uranium-235 isotope is a key fuel source for creating the energy produced via fission reactions.

A funeral home, funeral parlor or mortuary, is a business that provides burial and funeral services for the dead and their families. These services may include a prepared wake and funeral, and the provision of a chapel for the funeral.ServicesFuneral homes arrange services in accordance with the wishes of surviving friends and family, whether immediate next of kin or an executor so named in a legal will. The funeral home often takes care of the necessary paperwork, permits, and other details, such as making arrangements with the cemetery, and providing obituaries to the news media.

A solvent ( from the Latin solvō , `` loosen , untie , solve '' ) is a substance that dissolves another substance, often forming a homogeneous liquid mixture called a solution. Solvents are essential components in many industrial and chemical processes, as well as everyday products such as cleaning agents, inks, and pharmaceuticals. Typically, solvents are liquids but can also be gases, solids, or supercritical fluids. They work by breaking the chemical bonds in a solute, causing it to become evenly dispersed and essentially 'disappearing' within the solvent.

Millets are a group of highly variable small-seeded grasses , widely grown around the world as cereal crops or grains for human food and as fodder. They are nutritionally rich in protein, fiber, and essential minerals, offering a great alternative to people with gluten sensitivity. Millets can also aid in maintaining good heart health and digestion while boosting the immune system. They can grow under adverse climate conditions, such as dry or high-temperature environments, with a significantly low need for water or synthetic fertilizers. Consequently, incorporating millets into global crop production can contribute to achieving agricultural sustainability and improving food security in drought-prone areas.

Year 1103 (MCIII) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Levant  Spring – Bohemond I, Norman prince of Antioch, is released from Seljuk imprisonment at Niksar, after a ransom is paid of 100,000 gold pieces. During his absence, Tancred (Bohemond's nephew) attacks the Byzantines, and re-captures the cities of Tarsus, Adana and Mamistra in Cilicia. Tancred is deprived of his lordship by Bohemond's return, and is rewarded with a small fief within the Principality of Antioch.

Year 952 ( CMLII ) was a leap year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. It was marked by several notable events that shaped the course of history. The Byzantine Emperor, Constantine VII, published a 53-volume encyclopedia called "De Ceremoniis" containing political and cultural insights. Additionally, the Magyars continued to expand their territory, fortifying the settlement of Bihar. In North Africa, the Kingdom of the Idrisids in Morocco fought against invading Fatimids. Although each event was distinct in its effects, they together represented an ever-evolving global society in the year 952.

Year 1068 (MLXVIII) was a leap year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  January 1 – Empress Eudokia Makrembolitissa, wife of the late Emperor Constantine X, marries General Romanos Diogenes (a member of a prominent Cappadocian family) – who is proclaimed co-emperor as Romanos IV of the Byzantine Empire. Autumn – Romanos IV begins a campaign against the Seljuk Turks, leading a Byzantine expeditionary force (which is in poor condition). He is successful in recapturing the fortress city of Hieropolis (modern-day Manbij) near Aleppo in northern Syria.

Turtles are an order of reptiles known as Testudines, characterized by a shell developed mainly from their ribs. Modern turtles are divided into two major groups, the side-necked turtles and hidden neck turtles which differ in the way the head retracts. There are 360 living and recently extinct species of turtles, including tortoises and terrapins. They are found on most continents, some islands and much of the ocean. Like other reptiles, birds, and mammals, they breathe air and do not lay eggs underwater, although many species live in or around water.

Isotope separation is the process of concentrating specific isotopes of a chemical element by removing other isotopes. The use of the nuclides produced is varied. The largest variety is used in research (e.g. in chemistry where atoms of "marker" nuclide are used to figure out reaction mechanisms). By tonnage, separating natural uranium into enriched uranium and depleted uranium is the largest application. In the following text, mainly the uranium enrichment is considered. This process is crucial in the manufacture of uranium fuel for nuclear power plants, and is also required for the creation of uranium-based nuclear weapons.

The history of Southeast Asia covers the people of Southeast Asia from prehistory to the present in two distinct sub-regions : Mainland Southeast Asia (also known as Indochina) and Maritime Southeast Asia (also known as the Malay Archipelago). The diverse ethnic, cultural, and linguistic background of the region is attributed to its long history of interaction, trade, and migrations. Key empires that have shaped the history of Southeast Asia include the Dvaravati, Funan, Chenla, Khmer, Champa, Sriwijaya, Majapahit, and various Indo-Islamic sultanates.

Year 968 ( CMLXVIII ) was a leap year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. At the time, it was known as the Year of the Consulship of Crescentius and Victor. Several important events occurred during this year, significantly impacting the European landscape. King Géza of Hungary began his reign, consolidating power among Hungarian tribes, while Bishopric of Prague was established and Saint Adalbert of Prague became the first bishop of this important diocese. In Spain, the Muslims launched another raid against the Kingdom of Asturias, indicating the continuation of battles over religious influence in the region.

The Bell UH-1 Iroquois (nicknamed "Huey") is a utility military helicopter powered by a single turboshaft engine, with two-bladed main and tail rotors. The first member of the prolific Huey family, it was developed by Bell Helicopter to meet a 1952 US Army requirement for a medical evacuation and utility helicopter, and first flew in 1956. The UH-1 was the first turbine-powered helicopter produced for the United States military, and more than 16,000 have been built since 1960.The Iroquois was originally designated HU-1, hence the Huey nickname, which has remained in common use, despite the official redesignation to UH-1 in 1962.

Pioneer 10 (originally designated Pioneer F) is an American space probe, launched in 1972 and weighing , that completed the first mission to the planet Jupiter. Thereafter, Pioneer 10 became the first of five artificial objects to achieve the escape velocity needed to leave the Solar System. This space exploration project was conducted by the NASA Ames Research Center in California. The space probe was manufactured by TRW Inc.Pioneer 10 was assembled around a hexagonal bus with a  diameter parabolic dish high-gain antenna, and the spacecraft was spin stabilized around the axis of the antenna.

Giovanni Pacini ( 17 February 17966 December 1867 ) was an Italian composer , best known for his operas . Giovanni Pacini was born in Catania, Sicily, and began his musical career as a child prodigy in violin and composition. Throughout his prolific career, he composed nearly 100 operas, along with numerous sacred, instrumental, and chamber works. He reached his artistic peak during the 1830s, garnering attention across Europe with operas like "Saffo" and "Il Corsaro". Despite living and working during the height of Romanticism, Pacini's style adhered more closely to classical traditions, favoring elegance over excessive emotion.

Gregory of Nyssa , also known as Gregory Nyssen ( ; c. 335 – c. 395 ) , was bishop of Nyssa from 372 to 376 and from 378 until his death. He was a prominent theologian, philosopher, and church father in the 4th-century Christian church, playing a crucial role in the development of early Christian doctrine. As one of the three Cappadocian Fathers, alongside his older brother Basil the Great and friend Gregory of Nazianzus, Gregory helped define and reinforce Trinitarian theology, advocating for the divinity of the Holy Spirit and coining key terms like "consubstantial."

Porphyry (; , Porphyrios "purple-clad") may refer to: Porphyry (geology), an igneous rock with large crystals in a fine-grained matrix and important Roman building material  Porphyritic, the general igneous texture of a rock with two distinct crystal (phenocryst) sizes Porphyry copper deposit, a primary (low grade) ore deposit of copper, consisting of porphyry rocks Porphyry Island in Lake Superior  Porphyry Mountain in Alaska Porphyry (philosopher) (234–305), Neoplatonic philosopher Porphyry of Gaza (or "St. Porphyry of Gaza", 347–420), Bishop of Gaza Porfirije, Serbian Patriarch (b.

In quantum mechanics, counterfactual definiteness (CFD) is the ability to speak "meaningfully" of the definiteness of the results of measurements that have not been performed (i.e., the ability to assume the existence of objects, and properties of objects, even when they have not been measured). The term "counterfactual definiteness" is used in discussions of physics calculations, especially those related to the phenomenon called quantum entanglement and those related to the Bell inequalities. In such discussions "meaningfully" means the ability to treat these unmeasured results on an equal footing with measured results in statistical calculations.

Pope Leo VI (880 – 12 February 929) was the bishop of Rome and nominal ruler of the Papal States for just over seven months, from June 928 to his death. His pontificate occurred during the period known as the Saeculum obscurum.Family and early careerLeo VI was born into a Roman family, and his father was Christophorus, who had been primicerius under Pope John VIII around the year 876. Tradition has it that he was a member of the Sanguini family. Before his pontificate, Leo served as the cardinal-priest of Santa Susanna.PontificateLeo was elected pope around June 928, during a period of anarchy.

Nitrous oxide , commonly known as laughing gas , nitrous , or nos , is a chemical compound , an oxide of nitrogen with the formula N2O. This colorless, non-flammable gas has a slightly sweet odor and taste. In medicinal contexts, it is primarily used for its anesthetic and analgesic properties, but is also used recreationally for its euphoric and perception-altering effects. Nitrous oxide is produced through the reaction between ammonium nitrate and a variety of metals or metallic oxides, and is commonly found in dental and medical procedures, as well as whipped cream propellants and automotive racing industries for enhanced engine performance.

Cannabis  is a genus of flowering plants in the family Cannabaceae. The number of species within the genus is disputed. Three species may be recognized: Cannabis sativa, Cannabis indica, and Cannabis ruderalis; C. ruderalis may be included within C. sativa; all three may be treated as subspecies of a single species, C. sativa; or C. sativa may be accepted as a single undivided species. The genus is widely accepted as being indigenous to and originating from Asia.The plant is also known as hemp, although this term is often used to refer only to varieties of Cannabis cultivated for non-drug use.

The PDP-7 was a minicomputer produced by Digital Equipment Corporation as part of the PDP series. Introduced in 1964, shipped since 1965, it was the first to use their Flip-Chip technology. With a cost of , it was cheap but powerful by the standards of the time. The PDP-7 is the third of Digital's 18-bit machines, with essentially the same instruction set architecture as the PDP-4 and the PDP-9.HardwareThe PDP-7 was the first wire-wrapped PDP. The computer had a memory cycle time of  and an add time of . I/O included a keyboard, printer, paper-tape and dual transport DECtape drives (type 555).

Courtesan , in modern usage , is a euphemism for a `` kept '' mistress or prostitute , particularly one associated with wealthy or high-ranking clientele. Historically, courtesans have occupied a distinct social stratum, providing both companionship and entertainment to men of influence and nobility. In addition to their skills in love and sensuality, they were often known for their exceptional talents in art, music, dance, and intellectual discourse. As respected figures, many courtesans played influential roles in politics and the arts, acting as patrons or muses to leading creative figures.

Year 949 (CMXLIX) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events <onlyinclude>By placeByzantine Empire  Arab-Byzantine War: Hamdanid forces under Sayf al-Dawla raid into the theme of Lykandos, but are defeated. The Byzantines counter-attack and seize Germanikeia, defeating an army from Tarsus, and raiding as far south as Antioch. General (strategos) Theophilos Kourkouas captures Theodosiopolis (modern-day Erzurum) after a 7-month siege.Europe  A Byzantine expeditionary force under Constantine Gongyles attempts to re-conquer the Emirate of Crete from the Saracens.

Yucatán (, also , , ;  ), officially the Free and Sovereign State of Yucatán, is one of the 32 states which comprise the Federal Entities of Mexico. It is divided into 106 municipalities, and its capital city is Mérida.It is located on the north part of the Yucatán Peninsula. It is bordered by the states of Campeche to the southwest and Quintana Roo to the southeast, with the Gulf of Mexico off its north coast.Before the arrival of Spaniards to the Yucatán Peninsula, the name of this region was Mayab.

Year 881 (DCCCLXXXI) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  February 12 – King Charles the Fat, the third son of the late Louis the German, is crowned as Holy Roman Emperor by Pope John VIII at Rome. August 3 – Battle of Saucourt-en-Vimeu: The West Frankish kings Louis III, and his brother Carloman II, rout Viking raiders (near Abbeville). Britain  Battle of the Conwy: King Anarawd of Gwynedd (Wales) initiates a revenge attack on the Mercian armies, and defeats them on the River Conwy.

Thetis ( ; ) , is a figure from Greek mythology with varying mythological roles . She mainly appears as a sea nymph, a goddess of water, or one of the 50 Nereids, daughters of the ancient sea god Nereus and his wife Doris. Thetis is best known for being the mother of the Greek hero Achilles, whom she bore with the mortal king Peleus. To protect Achilles from his prophesied death during the Trojan War, she dipped him into the River Styx, making his entire body invulnerable except for his heel.

In the philosophy of mathematics , the abstraction of actual infinity involves the acceptance ( if the axiom of infinity is adopted) that there exists an infinite number of mathematical objects, such as numbers or points in a geometric space. This idea can be traced back to ancient Greek mathematics, but it has been a subject of rigorous debate since the invention of calculus in the late 17th century. The abstract concept of infinity offers great potential in problem-solving, as it allows mathematicians to study and model the behavior of phenomena in various contexts, from geometric progressions to mathematical operations involving infinite series or continuous quantities.

The history of Southeast Asia covers the people of Southeast Asia from prehistory to the present in two distinct sub-regions: Mainland Southeast Asia (or Indochina) and Maritime Southeast Asia (or Insular Southeast Asia). Mainland Southeast Asia comprises Cambodia, Laos, Myanmar (or Burma), Peninsular Malaysia, Thailand and Vietnam whereas Maritime Southeast Asia comprises Brunei, Cocos (Keeling) Islands, Christmas Island, East Malaysia, East Timor, Indonesia, Philippines and Singapore.The earliest Homo sapiens presence in Mainland Southeast Asia can be traced back to 70,000 years ago and to at least 50,000 years ago in Maritime Southeast Asia.

Liberation theology is a Christian theological approach emphasizing the liberation of the oppressed. In certain contexts, it engages socio-economic analyses, with "social concern for the poor and political liberation for oppressed peoples." In other contexts, it addresses other forms of inequality, such as race or caste.Liberation theology is best known in the Latin American context, especially within Catholicism in the 1960s after the Second Vatican Council, where it became the political praxis of theologians such as Gustavo Gutiérrez, Leonardo Boff, and Jesuits Juan Luis Segundo and Jon Sobrino, who popularized the phrase "preferential option for the poor".

Phenylalanine ( symbol Phe or F ) is an essential α-amino acid with the formula . It can be viewed as the phenyl derivative of alanine, a building block of proteins. Found in various dietary sources such as meat, fish, eggs, and dairy, it plays a critical role in human growth and development. Additionally, this amino acid contributes to various essential functions within the body, such as synthesizing neurotransmitters and maintaining a balanced mood. Due to its importance, phenylalanine is incorporated into many protein-based structures in cells, as well as participating in a host of enzymatic reactions.

The Little Ice Age (LIA) was a period of regional cooling, particularly pronounced in the North Atlantic region, that occurred after the Medieval Warm Period. It was not a true ice age of global extent. The term was introduced into scientific literature by François E. Matthes in 1939. The time period has been conventionally defined as extending from the 16th to the 19th centuries, but some experts prefer an alternative timespan from about 1300 to about 1850.The NASA Earth Observatory notes three particularly cold intervals. One began about 1650, another about 1770, and the last in 1850, all of which were separated by intervals of slight warming.

A seal is a device for making an impression in wax , clay , paper , or some other medium , including an embossment on paper, and is also the impression made from such a device. Seals have been used throughout history as a way of authenticating documents, signifying official approval or identification, and even representing status and authority. In ancient civilizations, seals were typically engraved with unique designs and symbols associated with individuals or organizations, such as royal insignia or emblems of professional guilds. Some cultures, particularly in Asia, used personalized seals to sign documents, which made forgery difficult.

Nitrous oxide, commonly known as laughing gas, nitrous, or nos, is a chemical compound, an oxide of nitrogen with the formula . At room temperature, it is a colourless non-flammable gas, with a slight metallic scent and taste. At elevated temperatures, nitrous oxide is a powerful oxidiser similar to molecular oxygen.Nitrous oxide has significant medical uses, especially in surgery and dentistry, for its anaesthetic and pain reducing effects. Its colloquial name, "laughing gas", coined by Humphry Davy, is due to the euphoric effects upon inhaling it, a property that has led to its recreational use as a dissociative anaesthetic.

The Magic Flute ( German : , ) , K. 620 , is an opera in two acts by Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart to a German libretto by Emanuel Schikaneder. First premiered in Vienna in 1791, The Magic Flute stands as one of Mozart's most beloved and enduring operatic works. The story revolves around the journey of young prince Tamino, who is given a magical flute that possesses the power to transform sorrow into joy. As Tamino embarks on a fantastical quest to save the beautiful Princess Pamina from the villainous sorcerer Sarastro, he encounters enchanted characters that challenge him in his mission.

In the Ancient Greek religion, Hestia (; , "hearth" or "fireside") is the virgin goddess of the hearth, the right ordering of domesticity, the family, the home, and the state. In Greek mythology, she is the firstborn child of the Titans Cronus and Rhea.Customarily, in Greek culture, Hestia received the first offering at every sacrifice in the household. In the public domain, the hearth of the prytaneum functioned as her official sanctuary, and, when a new colony was established, a flame from Hestia's public hearth in the mother city would be carried to the new settlement.

Patch collecting or badge collecting (also, scutelliphily, from Latin scutellus meaning little shield, and Greek phileein meaning to love) is the hobby of collecting patches or badges.Souvenir patchesSouvenir patches are usually shield-shaped and generally contain a coat of arms, a map or a miniature view. The patches can be made of any material, but are usually woven or embroidered fabric, though they can also be made from paper or, increasingly, plastic.Other types of collectible patches include police or service patches, space mission patches, Scout patches, fashion patches, political and sports stickers, walking stick labels, car window pennants, and pin badges.

Padthaway is a small town in the Australian state of South Australia located in the state 's south-east within the Limestone Coast region, about 338 kilometers southeast of the state capital, Adelaide. It is famous for its lush, picturesque vineyards producing award-winning wines due to its fertile terra rossa soil and Mediterranean climate. The region's cool maritime conditions result in wines with elegant flavors and age-worthy structures. Padthaway offers its visitors not only a remarkable wine-tasting experience, but also diverse leisure activities including hiking, wildlife spotting, and dining at delightful local cafes.

Gerard Adams ( ; born 6 October 1948 ) is an Irish republican politician who was the president of Sinn Féin from 1983 to 2018, and one of the most influential figures in Irish nationalism. He has also been a Member of Parliament (MP) for Belfast West, a Member of the Legislative Assembly (MLA) for Belfast West, and a Teachta Dála (TD) for Louth. Adams was a pivotal figure in the negotiations for the 1998 Good Friday Agreement, which led to power-sharing between nationalist and unionist politicians in Northern Ireland.

The National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA  ) is an American scientific and regulatory agency within the United States Department of Commerce that forecasts weather, monitors oceanic and atmospheric conditions, charts the seas, conducts deep sea exploration, and manages fishing and protection of marine mammals and endangered species in the U.S. exclusive economic zone.Purpose and functionNOAA's specific roles include: Supplying Environmental Information Products. NOAA supplies to its customers and partners information pertaining to the state of the oceans and the atmosphere, such as weather warnings and forecasts via the National Weather Service. NOAA's information services extend as well to climate, ecosystems, and commerce.

Harlequin (;  ;  ) is the best-known of the zanni or comic servant characters from the Italian commedia dell'arte. The role is traditionally believed to have been introduced by Zan Ganassa in the late 16th century, was definitively popularized by the Italian actor Tristano Martinelli in Paris in 1584–1585, and became a stock character after Martinelli's death in 1630.The Harlequin is characterized by his chequered costume. His role is that of a light-hearted, nimble, and astute servant, often acting to thwart the plans of his master, and pursuing his own love interest, Columbina, with wit and resourcefulness, often competing with the sterner and melancholic Pierrot.

In chemistry, a nucleophile is a chemical species that forms bonds with electrophiles by donating an electron pair. All molecules and ions with a free pair of electrons or at least one pi bond can act as nucleophiles. Because nucleophiles donate electrons, they are Lewis bases. Nucleophilic describes the affinity of a nucleophile to bond with positively charged atomic nuclei. Nucleophilicity, sometimes referred to as nucleophile strength, refers to a substance's nucleophilic character and is often used to compare the affinity of atoms. Neutral nucleophilic reactions with solvents such as alcohols and water are named solvolysis.

The raven paradox , also known as Hempel 's paradox , Hempel 's ravens , or rarely the paradox of inductive logic, is a thought-provoking argument in the philosophy of science. Proposed by Carl Gustav Hempel in the 1940s, it exposes inconsistencies in the scientific process of confirmation. The paradox demonstrates that certain valid deductive inferences might not work correctly in induction. Imagine the statement "all ravens are black." Logically, any instance of a black raven would be a confirming instance for this claim. The paradox emerges when an inverse statement is proposed, such as "all non-black things are non-ravens."

Eastern Europe is the eastern region of Europe . There is no consistent definition of the precise area it covers , but it generally encompasses the countries located to the east of the central and western parts of the continent. The region consists of a diverse mix of cultures, religions, and languages, including Slavic, Uralic, and Baltic communities. Some key countries in this region include Poland, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Hungary, Romania, Bulgaria, the Baltic States (Estonia, Latvia, and Lithuania), and sometimes also Belarus, Ukraine, and Moldova.

On May 25, 1865, in Mobile, Alabama, in the Southern United States, an ordnance depot or "magazine" exploded, killing some 300 persons. This event occurred just after the end of the American Civil War, during the occupation of the city by victorious Federal troops.The depot was a warehouse on Beauregard Street, where the troops had stacked some 200 tons of shells and powder. Some time in the afternoon of May 25, a cloud of black smoke rose into the air and the ground began to rumble. Flames shot up into the sky and bursting shells were heard throughout the city.

The Hippocratic Oath is an oath of ethics historically taken by physicians . It is one of the most widely known and important guidelines for medical professionals, having its origins in ancient Greece. Written by Hippocrates, often considered as the Father of Western Medicine, this pledge not only serves as a professional commitment for healthcare providers, but it also sets high standards for treating patients with utmost care and dignity. The Oath emphasizes several key principles including the promise to act in the patient's best interest, protect their privacy, and strive for continuous learning and improvement.

Albert the Magnanimous KG , elected King of the Romans as Albert II ( 10 August 139727 October 1439 ) , was known for his fair rule and kind heart. During his reign, he focused on fostering diplomacy and establishing strong alliances among European nations. Albert inherited a large territory which enabled him to implement significant legal, economic, and social reforms that transformed the lives of his people. As a great patron of arts, he welcomed eminent artists and scholars to his court. The consequences of his reign continue to shape the political landscape of Central Europe.

Celebration is a census-designated place (CDP) and a master-planned community in Osceola County, Florida, United States, located near Walt Disney World Resort and originally developed by The Walt Disney Company. The town, whose population was 7,427 at the 2010 census, is part of the Orlando–Kissimmee Metropolitan Statistical Area.After founding Celebration, Disney followed its plans to divest most of its control of the town. Several Disney business units continue to occupy the town's office buildings. Walt Disney World operates two utility companies, Smart City Telecom and Reedy Creek Energy Services, that provide services to the town.

A county is a geographical region of a country used for administrative or other purposes in certain modern nations . The term 'county' is derived from the Old French word 'conté,' which signifies a jurisdiction under a count or a lord. The size and function of counties differ considerably from one nation to another. In general, counties act as a smaller administrative division within the larger entity of a country or state. They serve to facilitate the effective governance of regional affairs by breaking down a large geographical area into smaller sections.

The Circus Maximus ( Latin for `` largest circus '' ; Italian : Circo Massimo ) is an ancient Roman chariot racing stadium and mass entertainment venue situated in Rome, Italy. Built in a valley between the Aventine and Palatine Hills, it was initially constructed in the 6th century BC and was continuously modified until the 4th century AD. With a capacity of over 150,000 spectators, the Circus Maximus was the largest stadium in Rome and the primary location for a wide range of spectacles including chariot races, religious festivals, gladiatorial shows, and staged hunts.

This is a list of monarchs who ruled over East Francia, and the Kingdom of Germany (Regnum Teutonicum), from the division of the Frankish Empire in 843 until the collapse of the German Empire in 1918.Note on titlesThe Kingdom of Germany started out as the eastern section of the Frankish kingdom, which was split by the Treaty of Verdun in 843. The rulers of the eastern area thus called themselves rex Francorum ("king of the Franks"), rex Francorum orientalium ("king of the East Franks"), and later just rex.

Flavius Odoacer ( ;  – 493 AD), also spelled Odovacer or Odovacar , was a soldier and statesman of barbarian background, who deposed the child emperor Romulus Augustulus and became King of Italy (476–493). Odoacer's overthrow of Romulus Augustulus is traditionally seen as marking the end of the Western Roman Empire as well as Ancient Rome.Though the real power in Italy was in his hands, he represented himself as the client of the emperor in Constantinople, Zeno. Odoacer often used the Roman honorific patrician, granted by Zeno, but was referred to as a king  in many documents.

The Bussard ramjet is a theoretical method of spacecraft propulsion proposed in 1960 by the physicist Robert W. Bussard , in which a spacecraft would utilize a large magnetic field to collect and compress hydrogen from the interstellar medium. This collected hydrogen would then be funneled into a nuclear fusion reactor onboard, effectively producing thrust for the spacecraft. The advantage of this propulsion method lies in its potential to eliminate the need to carry large amounts of fuel onboard, resulting in a lighter and more efficient space vehicle. Though an innovative and fascinating concept, the Bussard ramjet still faces several technical and engineering challenges before becoming a feasible technology for interstellar travel.

Stevana `` Stevie '' Case ( born 1976–1977 ) is an American businesswoman . She is known for competing in professional gaming tournaments in the late 1990s and early 2000s under the pseudonym "KillCreek," making her one of the first female esports competitors. Stevie gained recognition for her success in games like Quake and Doom, eventually being dubbed the "First Lady of Quake." Today, she continues to have an impact in the gaming world by mentoring young esports enthusiasts and advocating for diversity within the gaming community. She is also involved in multiple tech start-ups and initiatives that are focused on driving the industry forward and nurturing its growth.

Year 1054 ( MLIV ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. Notable events that occurred in 1054 included the appearance of a supernova, which formed the Crab Nebula, and was observed and documented by Chinese astronomers. In religious affairs, the Great Schism between the Roman Catholic and Eastern Orthodox Churches occurred, causing significant tensions between Christians. Politically, the Normans consolidated their control over southern Italy, and disputes over royal successions led to tensions throughout Europe, setting the stage for future conflicts in the medieval period.

Brave New World is a dystopian social science fiction novel by English author Aldous Huxley , written in 1931 and published in 1932. Set in the futuristic World State, it explores the impact of technology, genetic engineering, and consumerist culture on humanity. Central to the plot is the idea of controlled reproduction, indoctrination, and psychological manipulation used by a governing body to suppress individual thought and maintain societal stability. Through the character arcs of protagonist Bernard Marx and the genetically-modified individuals around him, the novel showcases Huxley's critique of contemporary society and delivers a chilling reminder of the potential dangers inherent in unchecked technological progress and authoritarian rule.

Stephanie Lynn Nicks ( born May 26 , 1948 ) is an American singer , songwriter , and producer known for her distinctive raspy voice and mystical stage presence. She rose to prominence as the lead vocalist and frontwoman of Fleetwood Mac, the wildly successful British-American rock band in the late 1970s. Nicks pursued a solo career as well, resulting in critically-acclaimed and top-selling albums like 'Bella Donna' and 'The Wild Heart.' Her vividly emotive lyrics and unique fashion sense have had an unmistakable impact on both music and fashion for decades, solidifying her status as the reigning "Queen of Rock 'n' Roll."

Catalase is a common enzyme found in nearly all living organisms exposed to oxygen (such as bacteria, plants, and animals) which catalyzes the decomposition of hydrogen peroxide to water and oxygen. It is a very important enzyme in protecting the cell from oxidative damage by reactive oxygen species (ROS). Catalase has one of the highest turnover numbers of all enzymes; one catalase molecule can convert millions of hydrogen peroxide molecules to water and oxygen each second.Catalase is a tetramer of four polypeptide chains, each over 500 amino acids long. It contains four iron-containing heme groups that allow the enzyme to react with hydrogen peroxide.

An infection is the invasion of an organism's body tissues by disease-causing agents, their multiplication, and the reaction of host tissues to the infectious agents and the toxins they produce. An infectious disease, also known as a transmissible disease or communicable disease, is an illness resulting from an infection.Infections can be caused by a wide range of pathogens, most prominently bacteria and viruses. Hosts can fight infections using their immune system. Mammalian hosts react to infections with an innate response, often involving inflammation, followed by an adaptive response.Specific medications used to treat infections include antibiotics, antivirals, antifungals, antiprotozoals, and antihelminthics.

Pope Leo XI ( ; 2 June 153527 April 1605 ) , born Alessandro Ottaviano de ' Medici , was an Italian priest and the 232nd pope of the Roman Catholic Church. He served from 1st April 1605 until his death just 27 days later. Born into the famous de' Medici family of Florence, Leo XI was ordained as a priest at the age of 37. Over the years, he took on various significant roles within the Church, including the Archbishop of Florence and Bishop of Pistoia. Known for his short papacy, Leo XI faced various political pressures during his tenure as the Church's leader.

In the English language , the word nigger is an ethnic slur typically used against black people , especially African Americans. Throughout history, this derogatory term has been a weapon of hate and oppression, highlighting the extreme racism and inequality experienced by the black community. Today, using this offensive term is generally considered completely unacceptable in civilized society. In recent times, there has been ongoing debate and discussion surrounding the word's place in modern culture, particularly in regards to artistic expression, historical contexts, and the reclaiming of the word by some within the African American community as a means of empowerment.

A resistojet is a method of spacecraft propulsion ( electric propulsion ) that provides thrust by heating a , typically gaseous, propellant to high temperatures and then expelling it through a nozzle. This is done using electrical energy instead of a chemical reaction. As a result, resistojets can be more efficient and provide better fuel economy compared to traditional chemical rocket engines, making them ideal for long-duration missions or satellite positioning. In a resistojet system, an electric resistor, such as a ceramic heating element, is used to transfer the electrical energy to the propellant.

Year 1493 (MCDXCIII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 19 – Treaty of Barcelona: Charles VIII of France returns Cerdagne and Roussillon to Ferdinand of Aragon. March 1 – Martín Alonso Pinzón returns to the city of Bayona in Spain from the  voyage of discovery, sending the first notice about the discovery to the Catholic Monarchs (Christopher Columbus is delayed by a storm in the Azores). March 4 – Christopher Columbus anchors in Lisbon and completes his February 15 letter on the first voyage conveying the news of his discoveries.

Pope Leo V was the bishop of Rome and nominal ruler of the Papal States from July 903 to his death in February 904. He was pope during the period known as the Saeculum obscurum, when popes wielded little temporal authority.Leo V was born at a place called Priapi, near Ardea. Although he was a priest when he was elected pope following the death of Pope Benedict IV (900–903), he was not a cardinal priest of Rome.During his brief pontificate, Leo granted the canons of Bologna a special bull (epistola tuitionis) where he exempted them from the payment of taxes.

Halebidu ( IAST : Haḷēbīḍ , literally `` old capital , city , encampment '' or `` ruined city '' ) is an ancient town located in the Hassan District of Karnataka, India. It was once the flourishing capital of the Hoysala Empire during the 12th and 13th centuries. The city is renowned for its exquisitely carved Hoysaleswara and Kedareshwara temples, which exemplify the peak of Hoysala art and architecture. These temples are adorned with intricate sculptures depicting stories from Hindu mythology, earning Halebidu the status of a significant cultural and historical heritage site.

Isis (;  Ēse; ; Meroitic:  Wos[a] or Wusa) was a major goddess in ancient Egyptian religion whose worship spread throughout the Greco-Roman world. Isis was first mentioned in the Old Kingdom  as one of the main characters of the Osiris myth, in which she resurrects her slain brother and husband, the divine king Osiris, and produces and protects his heir, Horus. She was believed to help the dead enter the afterlife as she had helped Osiris, and she was considered the divine mother of the pharaoh, who was likened to Horus.

The Porsche 914 or VW-Porsche 914 is a mid-engined sports car designed , manufactured and marketed collaboratively by Volkswagen and Porsche from 1969 to 1976. A highly innovative model for its time, it features a unique targa top that set it apart from contemporary sports cars. Developed as a joint project to replace Porsche's aging 912 and Volkswagen's Karmann Ghia, the 914 combined cutting-edge German engineering with affordability, creating a powerful yet accessible sports car. The four-cylinder engine found in the Volkswagen variants offered spirited performance, while the premium Porsche-branded 914/6 packed a 911-derived six-cylinder, further pushing performance boundaries.

Year 1155 ( MCLV ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. This particular year was marked by various noteworthy events in the realms of politics, warfare, and religion. In Europe, a power struggle occurred between Holy Roman Emperor Frederick I Barbarossa and Pope Adrian IV, as both leaders sought to exert their influence across the continent. Meanwhile, conflict ensued among various Christian and Muslim states during the Iberian Reconquista, resulting in territorial gains and losses throughout the region.

Audio Video Interleave (also Audio Video Interleaved and known by its initials and filename extension AVI, usually pronounced ), is a proprietary multimedia container format and Windows standard introduced by Microsoft in November 1992 as part of its Video for Windows software. AVI files can contain both audio and video data in a file container that allows synchronous audio-with-video playback. Like the DVD video format, AVI files support multiple streaming audio and video, although these features are seldom used.Many AVI files use the file format extensions developed by the Matrox OpenDML group in February 1996.

`` Wilhelmus van Nassouwe '' , usually known just as `` Wilhelmus '' ( ; ; English translation : `` William of Nassau''), is the national anthem of the Netherlands and one of the oldest known anthems in the world. The anthem was written between 1568 and 1572 during the Dutch Revolt against the Spanish Empire. The lyrics were composed as a political song, declaring loyalty to William the Silent, the Prince of Orange, and a covert call to Dutch independence. It has served as a unifying symbol for the Netherlands and stands as a reminder of their journey towards becoming a free and prosperous nation.

Coxsackie A virus ( CAV ) is a cytolytic Coxsackievirus of the Picornaviridae family , an enterovirus ( a group of small RNA viruses). The name "Coxsackie" comes from the New York town where it was first isolated in 1948. CAV primarily targets young children and causes illnesses such as herpangina and hand-foot-and-mouth disease. Transmission typically occurs through fecal-oral contact, ingestion of contaminated food or water, and contact with infected surfaces or respiratory droplets. Most infections are mild, self-limited, and resolve within a week. Prevention strategies include maintaining proper hygiene, thorough handwashing, and disinfecting common surfaces.

Year 874 (DCCCLXXIV) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Salomon, duke ('king') of Brittany, is murdered by a faction which includes his son-in-law Pascweten and Gurvand, son-in-law of late ruler Erispoe. After Salomon's death they divide the country, and Pascweten and Gurvand co-rule Brittany. Svatopluk I, ruler (knyaz) of Great Moravia, concludes a peace treaty at Forchheim (Northern Bavaria). He is able to expand his territories outside the Frankish sphere, and subjugates the Vistulans.Kirschbaum 2007, p. 121.

A beta particle, also called beta ray or beta radiation (symbol β), is a high-energy, high-speed electron or positron emitted by the radioactive decay of an atomic nucleus during the process of beta decay. There are two forms of beta decay, β− decay and β+ decay, which produce electrons and positrons respectively.Beta particles with an energy of 0.5 MeV have a range of about one metre in air; the distance is dependent on the particle energy.Beta particles are a type of ionizing radiation and for radiation protection purposes are regarded as being more ionising than gamma rays, but less ionising than alpha particles.

In electronics, a multiplexer (or mux; spelled sometimes as multiplexor), also known as a data selector, is a device that selects between several analog or digital input signals and forwards the selected input to a single output line. The selection is directed by a separate set of digital inputs known as select lines. A multiplexer of  inputs has  select lines, which are used to select which input line to send to the output.A multiplexer makes it possible for several input signals to share one device or resource, for example, one analog-to-digital converter or one communications transmission medium, instead of having one device per input signal.

Hildegard Frieda Albertine Knef (; 28 December 19251 February 2002) was a German actress, voice actress, singer, and writer. She was billed in some English-language films as Hildegard Neff or Hildegarde Neff.Early yearsHildegard Knef was born in Ulm in 1925. Her parents were Hans Theodor and Friede Augustine Knef. Her father, a condecorated First World War veteran, died of syphilis when she was only six months old, and her mother moved to Berlin and worked in a factory. Knef began studying acting at age 14 in 1940. She left school at 15 to become an apprentice animator with Universum Film AG.

Josiah Willard Gibbs ( ; February 11 , 1839 – April 28 , 1903 ) was an American scientist who made significant contributions to several branches of science including physics, chemistry, and mathematics. He is best known for his work in the development of thermodynamics and statistical mechanics, as well as inventing vector analysis. Gibbs' pioneering research led to the establishment of the famous Gibbs phase rule, which deals with the equilibrium conditions in a system containing multiple phases and components. He also created the concept of Gibbs free energy, a vital part of understanding chemical thermodynamics.

Theodoret of Cyrus or Cyrrhus (;  AD 393 –  458/466) was an influential theologian of the School of Antioch, biblical commentator, and Christian bishop of Cyrrhus (423–457). He played a pivotal role in several 5th-century Byzantine Church controversies that led to various ecumenical acts and schisms. He wrote against Cyril of Alexandria's 12 Anathemas which were sent to Nestorius and did not personally condemn Nestorius until the Council of Chalcedon. His writings against Cyril were included in the Three Chapters Controversy and were condemned at the Second Council of Constantinople.

The National Guard is a state-based military force that becomes part of the reserve components of the United States Army and the United States Air Force. They operate under a dual mission, serving both the federal and state governments. Established by the Constitution, the National Guard assists local authorities during natural disasters, emergencies, and civil unrest. Additionally, they can be called upon by the President to serve in overseas missions. They play a significant role in both domestic and international operations, providing critical support, enhancing defense capabilities, and ensuring the overall readiness of the US military forces.

Loris is the common name for the strepsirrhine mammals of the subfamily Lorinae (sometimes spelled Lorisinae) in the family Lorisidae. Loris is one genus in this subfamily and includes the slender lorises, while Nycticebus is the genus containing the slow lorises.DescriptionLorises are nocturnal and arboreal. They are found in tropical and woodland forests of India, Sri Lanka, and parts of southeast Asia. Loris locomotion is a slow and cautious climbing form of quadrupedalism. Some lorises are almost entirely insectivorous, while others also include fruits, gums, leaves, and slugs in their diet.Female lorises practice infant parking, leaving their infants behind in nests.

A spacecraft is a vehicle or machine designed to fly in outer space. A type of artificial satellite, spacecraft are used for a variety of purposes, including communications, Earth observation, meteorology, navigation, space colonization, planetary exploration, and transportation of humans and cargo. All spacecraft except single-stage-to-orbit vehicles cannot get into space on their own, and require a launch vehicle (carrier rocket).On a sub-orbital spaceflight, a space vehicle enters space and then returns to the surface without having gained sufficient energy or velocity to make a full orbit of the Earth.

Svante August Arrhenius ( , ; 19 February 1859 – 2 October 1927) was a Swedish scientist. Originally a physicist, but often referred to as a chemist, Arrhenius was one of the founders of the science of physical chemistry. He received the Nobel Prize for Chemistry in 1903, becoming the first Swedish Nobel laureate. In 1905, he became director of the Nobel Institute, where he remained until his death.Arrhenius was the first to use principles of physical chemistry to estimate the extent to which increases in atmospheric carbon dioxide are responsible for the Earth's increasing surface temperature.

The year 2000 in Israel and Palestine marked the beginning of the al-Aqsa Intifada leading to a number of Palestinian and Israeli deaths.TimelineJanuary - 28 September (12 Palestinians)Up to 28 September 12 Palestinian were killed by the Israeli army in the occupied territories.February (death toll: 3, all of which Israeli civilians)  February 9: Dov and Gabriella Weiss of Giv'at Ze'ev, an Israeli settlement outside of Jerusalem, were found bludgeoned to death in their home. Police confirmed the attack was by militants.September (death toll: 19 - 17 Palestinians, 2 Israeli military forces)  September 27: an Israeli soldier killed in Gaza Strip.

Arabidopsis (rockcress) is a genus in the family Brassicaceae. They are small flowering plants related to cabbage and mustard. This genus is of great interest since it contains thale cress (Arabidopsis thaliana), one of the model organisms used for studying plant biology and the first plant to have its entire genome sequenced. Changes in thale cress are easily observed, making it a very useful model.StatusCurrently, the genus Arabidopsis has nine species and a further eight subspecies recognised. This delimitation is quite recent and is based on morphological and molecular phylogenies by O'Kane and Al-Shehbaz and others.Their findings confirm the species formerly included in Arabidopsis made it polyphyletic.

A shaped charge is an explosive charge shaped to focus the effect of the explosive 's energy . Different types of shaped charges are used for various purposes, such as penetrating armored vehicles, breaching walls, or cutting through metal. Typically, a shaped charge consists of a hollow cone-shaped liner, which directs and concentrates the explosive force into a single point. This focused blast creates an extremely high-pressure jet that is capable of punching through various materials with immense speed and energy. Applications of shaped charges are diverse, including military and engineering applications.

Warren Mitchell ( born Warren Misell ; 14 January 1926 – 14 November 2015 ) was a British actor . Warren Mitchell was a renowned British actor, best known for his role as Alf Garnett in the popular television sitcoms "Till Death Us Do Part" and "In Sickness and in Health." Throughout his distinguished career, which spanned more than six decades, he appeared in numerous stage, film, and television productions, earning widespread acclaim for his versatility and exceptional talent. Born in London, England, Mitchell attended the Royal Academy of Dramatic Art (RADA) before starting his acting career in the 1950s.

The following outline is provided as an overview of and topical guide to the history of South Asia:History of South Asia – South Asia includes the contemporary political entities of India, Pakistan, Bangladesh, Nepal, Afghanistan, Bhutan, and the island nations of Sri Lanka and the Maldives.ChronologyJames Mill (1773–1836), in his The History of British India (1817), distinguished three phases in the history of India, namely Hindu, Muslim and British civilisations. This periodisation has been influential, but has also been criticised for the misconceptions it gave rise to.

Year 950 (CML) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Arab–Byzantine War: A Hamdanid army (30,000 men) led by Sayf al-Dawla raids into  Byzantine theme Anatolia. He defeats Bardas Phokas, but is then ambushed on his return and heavily defeated by Leo Phokas. Europe  November 22 – King Lothair II dies at Turin (possibly poisoned by Berengar of Ivrea). Berengar is crowned king of Italy and imprisons Lothair's now 19-year-old widow, Adelaide for four months at Como.

A supercomputer is a computer with a high level of performance as compared to a general-purpose computer . The performance of a supercomputer is measured in floating-point operations per second (FLOPS) and can handle complex computational tasks efficiently. Typically used in scientific research, weather forecasting, and advanced simulations, these powerful machines have also played a significant role in cryptography, artificial intelligence, and molecular modeling. Some notable examples of supercomputers include IBM's Summit and Japan's Fugaku. As technology continues to advance, the potential of supercomputers for problem-solving and pushing boundaries of human knowledge remains significant.

Year 1158 ( MCLVIII ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. In this pivotal year, various political, cultural, and religious events occurred throughout Europe and the world. The Bavarian town of Munich was founded by Henry the Lion, Duke of Saxony and Bavaria, becoming a critical center of commerce and influence in the region. Emperor Frederik Barbarossa allowed Archbishop Arnold of Bremen to conquer Mecklenburg and gain control over Wendish territory. In England, Bishop Hilliard's establishment of Norwich School enabled further dissemination of knowledge in literature and philosophy.

Anthony John Hancock ( 12 May 1924 – 25 June 1968 ) was an English comedian and actor.High-profile during the 1950s and 1960s, Hancock was best known for his BBC series "Hancock's Half Hour", first broadcast on radio and then later on television. This ground-breaking show blended elements of sitcom, sketch comedy, and the often surreal humour of its scripts, typically showcasing Hancock's sharp wit, charismatic persona, and natural comedic talents. Tragically, Hancock's personal life was marked by depression and substance abuse issues, ultimately culminating in his untimely death at the age of 44.

The History of East Asia generally encompasses the histories of China, Japan, Korea, and Mongolia from prehistoric times to the present. East Asia is not a uniform term and each of its countries has a different national history, but scholars maintain that the region is also characterized by a distinct pattern of historical development. This is evident in the interrelationship among East Asian countries, which not only involve the sum total of historical patterns but also a specific set of patterns that has affected all or most of East Asia in successive layers.

Turtles are an order of reptiles known as Testudines , characterized by a shell developed mainly from their ribs . These unique creatures inhabit a wide range of habitats, including oceans, forests, and deserts. They play crucial roles in maintaining ecosystem balance by serving as both predators and prey. There are over 300 species of turtles, with varying physical features and adaptations suited to their environment. Many turtles possess a sturdy beak-like mouth adapted for their specialized diets, and their scaly limbs can either function for adept digging, powerful swimming, or steady movement across land.

The Maunder Minimum , also known as the `` prolonged sunspot minimum '' , was a period around 1645 to 1715 when sunspots on the Sun's surface became extremely rare. This unusual phenomenon coincided with the coldest phase of the Little Ice Age, a period of significantly lower temperatures in the Northern Hemisphere. During this time, Europe and North America faced extreme weather conditions, including longer winters and disrupted agriculture. It is hypothesized that reduced sunspot activity diminished solar output, ultimately resulting in colder weather patterns. Although scientists continue to investigate the link, the Maunder Minimum remains a subject of great fascination in climatology and solar research.

Rice is the seed of the grass species Oryza sativa (Asian rice) or less commonly Oryza glaberrima (African rice). The name wild rice is usually used for species of the genera Zizania and Porteresia, both wild and domesticated, although the term may also be used for primitive or uncultivated varieties of Oryza.As a cereal grain, domesticated rice is the most widely consumed staple food for over half of the world's human population, especially in Asia and Africa. It is the agricultural commodity with the third-highest worldwide production, after sugarcane and maize.

A bong ( also known as a water pipe ) is a filtration device generally used for smoking cannabis , tobacco, or other herbal substances. In its most basic form, a bong consists of a bowl for packing the smoking material, a stem, and a water chamber, which together create a unique smoking experience. The main purpose of the bong is to filter and cool the smoke, making it smoother and less harsh on the user's throat and lungs. By passing the smoke through the water, unwanted particles and toxic components are filtered out, providing the user with a cleaner, more enjoyable experience.

Tilburg is a city and municipality in the Netherlands , in the southern province of North Brabant . With a population of over 219,000, it is the second-largest city in North Brabant and the sixth-largest in the country. Famous for its textile industry in the past, Tilburg is now a hub of culture, education, and modern business. It is home to the Tilburg University, known for its top-tier research and quality education in fields like economics, social sciences, and law. Furthermore, the city offers a vibrant nightlife, diverse shopping options, and various festivals like Carnival and Incubate, attracting both local and international visitors.

Tajiks (, Tājīk, Tājek; ) are a Persian-speaking Iranian ethnic group native to Central Asia, living primarily in Afghanistan, Tajikistan, and Uzbekistan. Tajiks are the largest ethnicity in Tajikistan, and the second-largest in Afghanistan and Uzbekistan. They speak varieties of Persian, a Western Iranian language. In Tajikistan, since the 1939 Soviet census, its small Pamiri and Yaghnobi ethnic groups are included as Tajiks. In China, the term is used to refer to its Pamiri ethnic groups, the Tajiks of Xinjiang, who speak the Eastern Iranian Pamiri languages.

Year 986 (CMLXXXVI) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  August 17 – Battle of the Gates of Trajan: Emperor Basil II leads a Byzantine expeditionary force (30,000 men) against the Bulgarians to capture the fortress city of Sredets. After a siege of 20 days, Basil is forced to retreat from the Sofia Valley towards the town of Ihtiman (through a passage known as the Gate of Trajan). The Bulgarians under Tsar Samuel ambush and defeat the Byzantine forces.

Mycenae ( ; or , Mykē̂nai or Mykḗnē ) is an archaeological site near Mykines in Argolis , north-eastern Peloponnese , Greece. Discovered in 1874 by renowned archaeologist Heinrich Schliemann, Mycenae served as a major center of the Mycenaean civilization during the Late Bronze Age (around 1600-1100 BCE). The ancient city was believed to be the kingdom of mythical King Agamemnon and played a crucial role in Homer's epics, the Iliad and the Odyssey. The archaeological site is characterized by the massive Lion Gate and Grave Circle, which consist of numerous royal tombs containing a variety of gold, silver, and other exquisite artifacts.

Lucia di Lammermoor is a dramma tragico (tragic opera) in three acts by Italian composer Gaetano Donizetti. Salvadore Cammarano wrote the Italian-language libretto loosely based upon Sir Walter Scott's 1819 historical novel The Bride of Lammermoor.Donizetti wrote Lucia di Lammermoor in 1835, when he was reaching the peak of his reputation as an opera composer. Gioachino Rossini had recently retired and Vincenzo Bellini had died shortly before the premiere of Lucia leaving Donizetti as "the sole reigning genius of Italian opera". Not only were conditions ripe for Donizetti's success as a composer, but there was also a widespread interest in the history and culture of Scotland.

Till Death Us Do Part is a British television sitcom that aired on BBC1 from 1965 to 1975 . The show, created by Johnny Speight, revolves around the lives of the Garnett family, consisting of the abrasive patriarch Alf Garnett, his long-suffering wife Else, daughter Rita and her husband Mike. It centers on the deeply opinionated and controversial Alf, whose loud-mouthed views on politics, religion, and race often cause conflicts within his family and neighborhood. Over the course of its ten-year run, the series gained significant attention and controversy for its explicit and confrontational exploration of societal issues and prejudices during a turbulent era in British history.

Henry Dunant ( born Jean-Henri Dunant ; 8 May 182830 October 1910 ) , also known as Henri Dunant , was a Swiss humanitarian, businessman, and social activist. He is best known as the founder of the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) in 1863, inspired by his experiences of witnessing the suffering of injured soldiers during the Battle of Solferino in Italy. In recognition of his groundbreaking work and devotion to improving the conditions of wounded soldiers and prisoners of war, Dunant was awarded the first-ever Nobel Peace Prize in 1901.

The European Bank for Reconstruction and Development (EBRD) is an international financial institution founded in 1991. As a multilateral developmental investment bank, the EBRD uses investment as a tool to build market economies. Initially focused on the countries of the former Eastern Bloc it expanded to support development in more than 30 countries from Central Europe to Central Asia. Similar to other multilateral development banks, the EBRD has members from all over the world (North America, Africa, Asia and Australia, see below), with the biggest single shareholder being the United States, but only lends regionally in its countries of operations.

Lucia di Lammermoor is a dramma tragico ( tragic opera ) in three acts by Italian composer Gaetano Donizetti . Based on Sir Walter Scott's historical novel "The Bride of Lammermoor," the opera features a libretto written by Salvadore Cammarano. Set in the 17th century, it explores the tragic tale of two feuding families – the Ravenswoods and the Lammermoors. Caught amidst the struggle, star-crossed lovers Lucia and Edgardo face mounting opposition to their love, leading Lucia to succumb to her overbearing brother Enrico's manipulation, sealing her fate in a horrifying outcome.

Dementia manifests as a set of related symptoms , which usually surface when the brain is damaged by injury or disease, such as Alzheimer's or stroke. These symptoms can greatly impact an individual's cognitive abilities and daily life, often resulting in memory loss, difficulty in processing information, problem-solving, and a decline in language and communication skills. Additional issues may arise, including changes in mood, behavior, and an increasing need for support from caregivers. Since the progression and severity of dementia varies among individuals, appropriate treatments and interventions are crucial for maintaining their overall wellbeing and promoting continued engagement in activities that are important to them.

Menstruation ( also known as a period and many other colloquial terms ) is the regular discharge of blood and mucosal tissue from the inner lining of the uterus through the vagina. This natural biological process usually occurs every month for women of reproductive age, with each cycle typically lasting between 21 to 35 days. Menstruation signals the shedding of the uterine lining due to the absence of fertilization, allowing for the possibility of a new ovulatory cycle to commence. Symptoms commonly experienced during menstruation may include abdominal cramps, bloating, fatigue, mood swings, and cravings.

A U-Boot is a beer cocktail that is made by placing a shot of vodka into a glass of beer, typically a lager. It is popular in Germany, Poland, North Macedonia, and Flanders. In Germany, the liquor korn is sometimes used instead, while in Flanders and the Netherlands, jonge jenever is preferred.It is called a U-Boot (German abbreviation of Unterseeboot, "submarine") because the shot glass of vodka sinks to the bottom of the glass of beer. The shot glass then "surfaces" when the cocktail is drunk.Preparation Place a shot glass on upside down glass and fill it with vodka.

Wind tunnels are large tubes with air blowing through them which are used to replicate the interaction between air and an object flying through the air or moving along the ground. Researchers use wind tunnels to learn more about how an aircraft will fly. NASA uses wind tunnels to test scale models of aircraft and spacecraft. Some wind tunnels are large enough to contain full-size versions of vehicles. The wind tunnel moves air around an object, making it seem as if the object is flying.Most of the time, large powerful fans suck air through the tube.

Salmon is the common name for several species of ray-finned fish in the family Salmonidae . Other fish in the same family include trout, char, grayling, and whitefish. Salmon are native to tributaries of the North Atlantic and the Pacific Ocean, where they inhabit both freshwater and saltwater environments during different stages of their life. They play a vital role in ecosystems as they serve as a key food source for a variety of predators such as bears, birds, and even humans. Famous for their ability to navigate vast distances back to their birthplaces for spawning, these fish undergo impressive physical transformations during this journey.

A museum ( ; plural museums or , rarely , musea ) is a building or institution that cares for a collection of artifacts and other objects of artistic, cultural, historical, or scientific importance. Museums play a crucial role in preserving and showcasing the cultural heritage of societies around the world. Many public museums make their collections accessible to the public through exhibits, educational programs, and various events, serving as invaluable sources of information and inspiration. Besides preserving the tangible aspects of heritage, museums often engage with local communities to promote a sense of identity and belonging.

Hugh John Lofting (14 January 1886 – 26 September 1947) was an English author trained as a civil engineer, who created the classic children's literature character of Doctor Dolittle. It first appeared in illustrated letters to his children written by Lofting from the British Army trenches in the First World War.Personal lifeLofting, born in January 1886 in Maidenhead, Berkshire, to Elizabeth Agnes (Gannon) and John Brien Lofting, was of English and Irish ancestry. His eldest brother, Hilary Lofting, later became a novelist in Australia, having emigrated there in 1915.Lofting was educated at Mount St Mary's College in Spinkhill, Derbyshire.

Offa 's Dyke is a large linear earthwork that roughly follows the border between England and Wales . The structure , named after King Offa of Mercia who is believed to have ordered its construction in the 8th century, stretches approximately 176 miles (283 kilometers) from the River Severn to the Irish Sea. Comprised mainly of a ditch and raised embankment, the dyke was likely built as a boundary marker and possible deterrent to Welsh invasions. Although not continuously maintained throughout history, many sections of Offa's Dyke remain visible today, forming part of a designated long-distance footpath and serving as an iconic symbol of the age-old Anglo-Welsh divide.

Juan Moreno y Herrera–Jiménez ( born 30 July 1948 ) , known as Jean Reno , is a French actor of Spanish descent. Over his career spanning more than four decades, he has established himself as a prominent and versatile talent in both European and Hollywood films. Jean Reno has appeared in a variety of successful projects, including notable films such as "The Big Blue" (1988), "Léon: The Professional" (1994), "The Crimson Rivers" (2000), and "The Da Vinci Code" (2006).

Toilet paper ( sometimes called toilet tissue ) is a tissue paper product primarily used to clean the anus and surrounding area of fecal material after defecation and to clean the perineal area of urine after urination, as well as other bodily fluid releases. It also acts as a layer of protection for the hands during these processes. Toilet paper is usually sold as a long strip of perforated paper wrapped around a paperboard core, and can be bought in varying thicknesses, sizes, and ply (with a higher ply representing added strength and softness).

Shakespearean tragedy is the designation given to most tragedies written by playwright William Shakespeare. Many of his history plays share the qualifiers of a Shakespearean tragedy, but because they are based on real figures throughout the history of England, they were classified as "histories" in the First Folio. The Roman tragedies—Julius Caesar, Antony and Cleopatra and Coriolanus—are also based on historical figures, but because their sources were foreign and ancient they are almost always classified as tragedies rather than histories. Shakespeare's romances (tragicomic plays) were written late in his career and published originally as either tragedy or comedy.

Hugh John Lofting ( 14 January 1886 – 26 September 1947 ) was an English author trained as a civil engineer. He is best known for creating the beloved children's character Doctor Dolittle. Lofting initially created the character to entertain his children with illustrated letters during World War I. Doctor Dolittle made his first appearance in the 1920 novel "The Story of Doctor Dolittle: Being the History of His Peculiar Life at Home and Astonishing Adventures in Foreign Parts". Lofting's ingenious creation and captivating storytelling gained him widespread acclaim and a significant contribution to children's literature.

Paclitaxel ( PTX ) , sold under the brand name Taxol among others , is a chemotherapy medication used to treat various types of cancer, including ovarian, breast, lung, and pancreatic cancer. It works by inhibiting cell division, preventing the growth and spread of cancer cells. PTX is a naturally-derived substance obtained from the bark of the Pacific Yew tree (Taxus brevifolia). It is administered intravenously, usually in combination with other anticancer agents as part of a chemotherapy regimen. Possible side effects include allergic reactions, low blood cell counts, hair loss, and neuropathy.

Niacin , also known as nicotinic acid , is an organic compound and a form of vitamin B3 , an essential nutrient required for various functions in the human body. Niacin can be obtained through a balanced diet containing animal-based products, such as poultry, beef, and fish, as well as plant-based sources like legumes and whole grains. The recommended daily amount varies with age and sex, but is generally about 14 to 16 milligrams. It plays a significant role in the production of energy in cells, synthesis of DNA, cholesterol management, and antioxidant properties.

A U-Boot is a beer cocktail that is made by placing a shot of vodka into a glass of beer . The U-Boot, which stands for 'underboat' in German, is a popular beverage choice for those looking to combine the buzz of liquor with the refreshing taste of beer. It is sometimes also known as a "Submarine" or a "Vodka-Boat" due to its unique drinking method. To enjoy this distinctive cocktail, the beer is typically consumed with the vodka shot placed in the glass – the spirit isn't usually mixed but rather sits submerged at the bottom of the glass, creating a smooth flavor blend.

Classless Inter-Domain Routing ( CIDR ) is a method for allocating IP addresses and for IP routing . The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) introduced CIDR in 1993 as a way to slow the rapid exhaustion of available IPv4 address space and improve the efficiency of Internet routing. This system replaced the previous classful network architecture by enabling a single IP address to designate multiple unique network addresses, aggregating them through a technique called supernetting. CIDR notation consists of an IP address followed by a slash and the prefix length, simplifying IP addressing and improving routing scalability.

Note: This compilation includes only those attacks that resulted in casualties. Attacks which did not kill or wound are not included.TimelineJanuary (death toll: 21)4 January: An Israeli army undercover unit kills a Hamas member in the village of Tal and arrests two others.9 January: Two Hamas militants wearing Palestinian police uniforms attack an IDF post near the Gaza Strip with grenades and assault rifles. Four Israeli soldiers and one of the attackers are killed.10 January-11: The Israeli army demolished 59 houses and damaged another 200 in Rafah refugee camp. Over six hundred Palestinians are made homeless.

Paul Leo Molitor ( born August 22 , 1956 ) , nicknamed `` Molly '' and `` The Ignitor '' , is an American former Major League Baseball (MLB) player and former manager of the Minnesota Twins. Over the span of his illustrious 21-year playing career, he has played for the Milwaukee Brewers, Toronto Blue Jays, and Minnesota Twins. Known for his impressive batting skills and versatility, Molitor amassed 3,319 hits and a .306 career batting average. The seven-time All-Star and four-time Silver Slugger inductee was elected to the Baseball Hall of Fame in 2004.

The Collatz conjecture in mathematics asks whether repeating two simple arithmetic operations will eventually transform every positive integer into one . These operations are: dividing an even number by 2, and multiplying an odd number by 3 and adding 1. The process continues for each subsequent resulting value until the number reaches one. The conjecture has remained unproven despite the intense scrutiny and computer analysis by mathematicians since its proposal by Lothar Collatz in 1937. As a result, it has become a longstanding unsolved mystery in mathematics. Some experts have come close to solving the enigma, yet none have provided a universal proof of the conjecture's truth.

In academic publishing , a scientific journal is a periodical publication intended to further the progress of science , usually by reporting new research and findings. Scientific journals serve as platforms for researchers and academicians to communicate their work, exchange ideas, and stay updated on the latest advances in their fields. Articles submitted to these journals undergo rigorous peer review processes, which aim to assess the validity and originality of the research presented. Upon successful review, articles are published in the journal, thereby disseminating the knowledge to the wider scientific community, spurring new discussions and facilitating collaborations.

Activision Publishing, Inc. is an American video game publisher based in Santa Monica, California. It serves as the publishing business for its parent company, Activision Blizzard, and consists of several subsidiary studios. Activision is one of the largest third-party video game publishers in the world and was the top United States publisher in 2016.The company was founded as Activision, Inc. on October 1, 1979 in Sunnyvale, California, by former Atari game developers upset at their treatment by Atari in order to develop their own games for the popular Atari 2600 home video game console.
