Relative density , or specific gravity , is the ratio of the density ( mass of a unit volume ) of a substance to the density of a given reference material. It is a dimensionless quantity and indicates how heavy (or light) a substance is compared to another substance. Water is often used as the reference material for liquids and solids, and air is commonly used as the reference material for gases. Determination of relative density is crucial for various scientific and industrial applications such as in fluid mechanics, civil engineering, material science, and chemistry.

Sparta (Doric Greek: Σπάρτα, Spártā; Attic Greek: Σπάρτη, Spártē) was a prominent city-state in Laconia, in ancient Greece. In antiquity, the city-state was known as Lacedaemon , while the name Sparta referred to its main settlement on the banks of the Eurotas River in Laconia, in south-eastern Peloponnese. Around 650 BC, it rose to become the dominant military land-power in ancient Greece.Given its military pre-eminence, Sparta was recognized as the leading force of the unified Greek military during the Greco-Persian Wars, in rivalry with the rising naval power of Athens.

The red slender loris (Loris tardigradus) is a small, nocturnal strepsirrhine primate native to the rainforests of Sri Lanka. This is No. 6 of the 10 focal species and No. 22 of the 100 EDGE mammal species worldwide considered the most evolutionarily distinct and globally endangered. Two subspecies have been identified, L. t. tardigradus and L. t. nycticeboides.Taxonomy Genus Loris Red slender loris, Loris tardigradus Horton Plains slender loris or mountain loris, Loris tardigradus nycticeboides Dry zone slender loris or lowland loris, Loris tardigradus tardigradus Gray slender loris, Loris lydekkerianusThe ears are less prominent in Loris tardigradus tardigradus compared to Loris lydekkerianus.

A sports governing body is a sports organization that has a regulatory or sanctioning function.Sports governing bodies come in various forms and have a variety of regulatory functions. Examples of this can include disciplinary action for rule infractions and deciding on rulechanges in the sport that they govern. Governing bodies have different scopes. They may cover a range of sport at an international level, such as the International Olympic Committee and the International Paralympic Committee, or only a single sport at a national level, such as the Rugby Football League. National bodies will largely have to be affiliated with international bodies for the same sport.

The bowline ( or ) is an ancient and simple knot used to form a fixed loop at the end of a rope. Its origins trace back to ancient maritime uses, making it an essential tool for sailors and an important knot for outdoor enthusiasts today. Known for its strength, stability, and ease of tying and untying, the bowline knot can be utilized in various situations such as rescue operations, rock climbing, and boating. Additionally, the knot can be easily tied using one hand and does not tighten or slip when loaded, providing versatility, reliability, and dependability in numerous environments and circumstances.

A radionuclide ( radioactive nuclide , radioisotope or radioactive isotope ) is a nuclide that has excess nuclear energy , making it unstable. This excess energy is released through the process of radioactive decay, where an atom emits radiation in the form of either alpha, beta, or gamma particles. Radionuclides can be naturally occurring, as in the decay of uranium or radium, or artificially produced, such as in nuclear reactors or particle accelerators. Due to their ionizing radiation, radionuclides have various applications in areas such as medical diagnostics and treatments, industrial radiography, archaeological dating, and as tracer materials in scientific research.

A gas nuclear reactor ( or gas fueled reactor or vapor core reactor ) is a proposed kind of nuclear reactor in which the nuclear fuel would be in a gaseous state rather than solid. This concept is advantageous as it offers the possibility of higher energy output, improved thermal efficiency, and enhanced fuel cycle performance. The idea revolves around the circulation of gaseous fuel mixture (e.g., uranium hexafluoride or uranium plasma) within the core that reacts and produces heat. The potential challenges for gas nuclear reactors include designing stable and safe containment systems and managing heat extraction effectively for energy production.

Casimir Jagiellon ( ; ; ; 3 October 1458 – 4 March 1484 ) was a prince of the Kingdom of Poland and a member of the Jagiellonian dynasty. He was the third son of King Casimir IV of Poland and Queen Elisabeth Habsburg. As the second surviving son, Casimir held the title of Duke of Płock, later also gaining the title Duke of Oświęcim, Zator, and Terebovl. He played a key role in the Battle of Vilnius in 1471, cementing his reputation as a talented military commander. In his personal life, Casimir was a devout Christian and a benefactor of various religious and educational institutions.

Heliox is a breathing gas mixture of helium (He) and oxygen (O2).Heliox is a medical treatment for patients with difficulty breathing. The mixture generates less resistance than atmospheric air when passing through the airways of the lungs, and thus requires less effort by a patient to breathe in and out of the lungs.Heliox has been used medically since the 1930s, and although the medical community adopted it initially to alleviate symptoms of upper airway obstruction, its range of medical uses has since expanded greatly, mostly because of the low density of the gas.

Mosquitoes are members of a group of almost 3,600 species of small flies within the family Culicidae ( from the Latin culex meaning "gnat" or "midge"). These insects can be found worldwide, with the exception of a few places like Antarctica due to its extremely cold temperatures. Female mosquitoes are responsible for biting humans and animals in order to acquire nutrients from blood to help develop their eggs. Mosquitoes transmit diseases like dengue fever, West Nile virus, malaria, and Zika virus, making them one of the most deadly creatures on Earth.

A brain tumor occurs when abnormal cells form within the brain . There are two main types of tumors : malignant (cancerous) and benign (non-cancerous). Malignant brain tumors tend to grow aggressively and can invade surrounding healthy tissues, while benign tumors grow slowly and typically remain contained within a specific area of the brain. Common symptoms of brain tumors include headaches, seizures, vision or hearing problems, loss of motor skills, cognitive changes, and speech difficulties. These symptoms can vary depending on the location and size of the tumor. Diagnosis usually involves imaging tests such as MRI or CT scans.

William Harrison Riker (September 22, 1920 – June 26, 1993) was an American political scientist who is prominent for applying game theory and mathematics to political science. He helped to establish University of Rochester as a center of behavioral revolution in political science.Early lifeWilliam Harrison Riker was born on September 22, 1920, in Des Moines, Iowa. He had 4 children, 2 sons and 2 daughters with wife Mary Elizabeth. He earned his bachelor's degree in economics at Indiana's DePauw University in 1942 and received his Ph.D at Harvard University in 1948.

Pioneer 10 ( originally designated Pioneer F ) is an American space probe , launched in 1972 and weighing , Pioneer 10 (originally designated Pioneer F) is an American space probe, launched in 1972 and weighing approximately 260 kilograms. This trailblazing spacecraft made history as the first spacecraft to journey through the asteroid belt and conduct a flyby of Jupiter. Its primary mission was to gather valuable data on Jupiter's environment and capture images of the planet and its moons. Pioneer 10 continued sending scientific information back to Earth until the early 21st century.

A nuclear thermal rocket (NTR) is a type of thermal rocket where the heat from a nuclear reaction, often nuclear fission, replaces the chemical energy of the propellants in a chemical rocket. In an NTR, a working fluid, usually liquid hydrogen, is heated to a high temperature in a nuclear reactor and then expands through a rocket nozzle to create thrust. The external nuclear heat source theoretically allows a higher effective exhaust velocity and is expected to double or triple payload capacity compared to chemical propellants that store energy internally.NTRs have been proposed as a spacecraft propulsion technology, with the earliest ground tests occurring in 1955.

Medina, officially Al Madinah Al Munawwarah  and also commonly simplified as Madīnah or Madinah , is the second-holiest city in Islam and the capital of the Medina Province of Saudi Arabia. , the estimated population of the city is 1,488,782, making it the fourth-most populous city in the country. Located at the core of the Medina Province in the western reaches of the country, the city is distributed over , of which  constitutes the city's urban area, while the rest is occupied by the Hejaz Mountains, empty valleys, agricultural spaces and older dormant volcanoes.Medina is generally considered to be the "cradle of Islamic culture and civilization".

Commander Keen is a series of side-scrolling platform video games developed primarily by id Software. The series consists of six main episodes, a "lost" episode, and a final game; all but the final game were originally released for MS-DOS in 1990 and 1991, while the 2001 Commander Keen was released for the Game Boy Color. The series follows the eponymous Commander Keen, the secret identity of the eight-year-old genius Billy Blaze, as he defends the Earth and the galaxy from alien threats with his homemade spaceship, rayguns, and pogo stick.

Triskaidekaphobia ( ,  ; ) is fear or avoidance of the number . It is also a reason for the fear of Friday the 13th, called paraskevidekatriaphobia  or friggatriskaidekaphobia .The term was used as early as in 1910 by Isador Coriat in Abnormal Psychology.OriginsNorse mythologyAccording to folklore historian Donald Dossey, the unlucky nature of the number "13" originated with a Norse myth about 12 gods having a dinner party in Valhalla. The trickster god Loki, who was not invited, arrived as the 13th guest, and arranged for Höðr to shoot Balder with a mistletoe-tipped arrow.

The Buran program (, , "Snowstorm", "Blizzard"), also known as the "VKK Space Orbiter programme" , was a Soviet and later Russian reusable spacecraft project that began in 1974 at the Central Aerohydrodynamic Institute in Moscow and was formally suspended in 1993. In addition to being the designation for the whole Soviet/Russian reusable spacecraft project, Buran was also the name given to Orbiter K1, which completed one uncrewed spaceflight in 1988 and was the only Soviet reusable spacecraft to be launched into space. The Buran-class orbiters used the expendable Energia rocket as a launch vehicle.

The World Federation of Trade Unions (WFTU) is an international federation of trade unions. WFTU was established in 1945 to replace the International Federation of Trade Unions.HistoryRiseIts mission was to bring together trade unions across the world in a single international organization, much like the United Nations. After a number of Western trade unions left it in 1949, as a result of disputes over support for the Marshall Plan, to form the International Confederation of Free Trade Unions, the WFTU was made up primarily of unions affiliated with or allegedly sympathetic to communist parties.

This is a list of monarchs who ruled over East Francia , and the Kingdom of Germany ( Regnum Teutonicum ) during the early Medieval period and throughout the Middle Ages. These rulers were known as kings and, later, Holy Roman Emperors. Beginning with the establishment of East Francia in 843 as part of the Treaty of Verdun, the early monarchs, such as Ludwig II, were primarily tasked with uniting various Germanic tribes and fending off external threats. Over time, the kingdom transformed and became known as the Holy Roman Empire, featuring notable leaders such as Otto I, Frederick I Barbarossa, and Charles IV.

Fighting Fantasy is a series of single-player role-playing gamebooks created by Steve Jackson and Ian Livingstone . The first volume in the series, titled The Warlock of Firetop Mountain, was published in 1982 and gained widespread popularity among readers and gamers alike. The books combine elements of choose-your-own-adventure stories with a tabletop role-playing game, allowing the reader to take on the persona of a fictional adventurer, make choices, and participate in battles using simple statistics, dice, and imagination. Over the years, Fighting Fantasy has spawned more than 60 different titles, introducing multiple worlds and diverse themes that continue to engage new generations of fantasy and adventure enthusiasts.

The Porsche 914 or VW-Porsche 914 is a mid-engined sports car designed, manufactured and marketed collaboratively by Volkswagen and Porsche from 1969 until 1976. It was only available as a targa-topped two-seat roadster powered by either a flat-4 or flat-6 engine.HistoryPre-development By the late 1960s, both Volkswagen and Porsche were in need of new models; Porsche was looking for a replacement for their entry-level 912, and Volkswagen wanted a new range-topping sports coupé to replace the Volkswagen Type 34 Karmann Ghia coupé. At the time the majority of Volkswagen's development work was handled by Porsche as part of an agreement that dated back to Porsche's founding.

Pope Leo V was the bishop of Rome and nominal ruler of the Papal States from July 903 to his tragic deposition in September 903. Though his reign was exceptionally brief, lasting a mere two months, his impact as Pope continued to be remembered in the complex history of the medieval Church. Known for his fervent adherence to Christian doctrine, he focused on ecclesiastical organization and fostering piety in Rome. Pope Leo V's reign, however, met a cruel end when he was overthrown by the ambitious Cardinal Christopher. Unfortunately, his successor brutally imprisoned Pope Leo, eventually leading to his mysterious death in 904 under shadowy circumstances.

The Bussard ramjet is a theoretical method of spacecraft propulsion proposed in 1960 by the physicist Robert W. Bussard, popularized by Poul Anderson's novel Tau Zero, Larry Niven in his Known Space series of books, Vernor Vinge in his Zones of Thought series, and referred to by Carl Sagan in the television series and book Cosmos.Bussard proposed a ramjet variant of a fusion rocket capable of reasonable interstellar travel, using enormous electromagnetic fields (ranging from kilometers to many thousands of kilometers in diameter) as a ram scoop to collect and compress hydrogen from the interstellar medium.

The Palmer Raids were a series of raids conducted in November 1919 and January 1920 by the United States Department of Justice, led by Attorney General A. Mitchell Palmer. They aimed to arrest and deport radical leftists, especially anarchists and members of the Communist Party, due to growing fears about the potential influence of communism and anarchism on American society. The Red Scare, fueled by Russian Revolution and labor strikes in the United States, led to an atmosphere of heightened political hysteria. As a result, more than 500 foreign citizens were deported, and countless others were arrested without just cause, in blatant violation of civil liberties.

Belarusians , also known formerly as Byelorussians ( from the Byelorussian SSR ) , Belarussians or Belorusians , are an East Slavic ethnic group primarily residing in Belarus, a landlocked country in Eastern Europe. The majority of Belarusians share a unique cultural heritage, as well as common ancestors and shared religious traditions, which historically evolved from a mix of Christianity and local pagan beliefs. There is also a considerable Belarusian diaspora in various countries across the world, including Russia, Ukraine, Poland, Lithuania, Latvia, and even further afield to the United States, Canada, and Australia.

The Martian Chronicles is a science fiction fix-up novel , published in 1950 , by American writer Ray Bradbury that chronicles the colonization of Mars by humans fleeing from a troubled and eventually atomically devastated Earth, and the conflict between the settlers and the native Martians. The book consists of a series of short stories, originally published in the late 1940s, which are woven together into a cohesive narrative. Each chapter presents various facets of human nature and our shared history, offering thought-provoking insights into our reliance on technology, cultural imperialism, racism, and our inclination to self-destruct.

Lumbar disc disease is the drying out of the spongy interior matrix of an intervertebral disc in the spine . Over time, lumbar disc disease leads to disc degeneration, causing the affected disc to lose its shock-absorbing capabilities and possibly even collapsing. This can result in several painful conditions such as herniated or bulging discs, spinal stenosis, and sciatica. Age, obesity, poor posture, and repetitive stress are among the factors that increase the risk of developing this degenerative disorder. Symptoms may vary, but often include chronic lower back pain, radiating pain down the legs, and loss of flexibility.

Year 1025 (MXXV) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  December 15 – Byzantine Emperor Basil II ("Bulgar Slayer") dies in Constantinople after a 50-year reign. Never married, he is succeeded by his brother and co-emperor Constantine VIII who becomes sole ruler of the Byzantine Empire. Constantine calls the Sicilian invasion off. Catapan Basil Boioannes diverts the Byzantine expeditionary force already assembled on Calabria to join the siege of Capua. Europe  April 18 – Bolesław I the Brave is crowned in Gniezno as the first king of Poland.

Powaqqatsi (or Powaqqatsi: Life in Transformation) is a 1988 American non-narrative film directed by Godfrey Reggio and the sequel to Reggio's experimental 1982 film, Koyaanisqatsi. It is the second film in the Qatsi trilogy.Powaqqatsi is a Hopi neologism coined by Reggio meaning "parasitic way of life" or "life in transition". While Koyaanisqatsi focused on modern life in industrial countries, Powaqqatsi, which similarly has no dialogue, focuses more on the conflict in Third World countries between traditional ways of life and the new ways of life introduced with industrialization.

In mathematics, a Möbius strip, band, or loop ( , ; ), also spelled Mobius or Moebius, is a surface with only one side (when embedded in three-dimensional Euclidean space) and only one boundary curve. The Möbius strip is the simplest non-orientable surface. It can be realized as a ruled surface. Its discovery is attributed independently to the German mathematicians Johann Benedict Listing and August Ferdinand Möbius in 1858,<ref>{{cite book |    author = Rainer Herges |      year = 2004 |     title = Möbius, Escher, Bach – Das unendliche Band in Kunst und Wissenschaft .

Fermat 's principle , also known as the principle of least time , is the link between ray optics and wave optics. It states that the path taken by light between two points is the one that takes the least time. This principle is named after Pierre de Fermat, a French mathematician, who formulated it in 1662. The concept has various applications in optics, such as reflection, refraction, and total internal reflection. In ray optics, light travels in straight lines, whereas wave optics describes light as wave-like propagations.

Parasports are sports played by people with a disability , including physical and intellectual disabilities . Some parasports are forms of existing able-bodied sports, modified to allow participation by individuals with various abilities. Examples of parasports include wheelchair basketball, blind soccer, and Special Olympics events. The development of parasports is crucial for creating equal opportunities and enhancing the social inclusion of people with disabilities. Participation in these sports activities can empower and enable athletes to showcase their talents, skills, and resilience while also increasing public awareness and promoting a more inclusive society. In recent years, the international attention and support for parasports have significantly increased.

Tamar the Great (, lit. "King Tamar") ( 1160 – 18 January 1213) reigned as the Queen of Georgia from 1184 to 1213, presiding over the apex of the Georgian Golden Age. A member of the Bagrationi dynasty, her position as the first woman to rule Georgia in her own right was emphasized by the title mepe ("king"), afforded to Tamar in the medieval Georgian sources.Tamar was proclaimed heir and co-ruler by her reigning father George III in 1178, but she faced significant opposition from the aristocracy upon her ascension to full ruling powers after George's death.

The M109 is an American 155 mm turreted self-propelled howitzer, first introduced in the early 1960s to replace the M44. It has been upgraded a number of times, most recently to the M109A7. The M109 family is the most common Western indirect-fire support weapon of maneuver brigades of armored and mechanized infantry divisions.The M109 has a crew of four: the section chief/commander, the driver, the gunner, and the ammunition handler/loader. The chief or gunner aims the cannon left or right (deflection) and up and down (quadrant).The British Army replaced its M109s with the AS-90.

Fidelio , originally titled ( Leonore , or The Triumph of Marital Love ) , Op . 72 , is a German opera in two acts composed by Ludwig van Beethoven. It is his only opera and one of his most celebrated works. The opera, with a libretto by Joseph Sonnleithner based on the French story Léonore, ou L’amour conjugal by Jean-Nicolas Bouilly, premiered at the Theater an der Wien in Vienna on November 20, 1805. Fidelio follows the story of the loyal and brave Leonore, who disguises herself as a man named Fidelio to rescue her imprisoned husband Florestan from political oppression.

Year 1030 (MXXX) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Emperor Romanos III Argyros decides to retaliate upon the incursions of the Muslims on the eastern frontier. He leads a Byzantine expeditionary force (20,000 men) to secure Antioch. The Mirdasid emir Shibl al-Dawla Nasr of Aleppo sues for peace, but Romanos refuses to negotiate and leads his army against Aleppo, against the advice of his generals. The Byzantine army encamps near Azaz, where they are encircled by the Mirdasids' Bedouin troops, who cut off the Byzantines from food and water.

Nansen passports, originally and officially stateless persons passports, were internationally recognized refugee travel documents from 1922 to 1938, first issued by the League of Nations to stateless refugees. They quickly became known as "Nansen passports" for their promoter, the Norwegian statesman and polar explorer Fridtjof Nansen.HistoryThe end of World War I saw significant turmoil, leading to a refugee crisis. Numerous governments were toppled, and national borders were re-drawn, often along generally ethnic lines. Civil war broke out in some countries. Many people left their homes because of war or persecution or fear thereof.

Josiah Willard Gibbs (; February 11, 1839 – April 28, 1903) was an American scientist who made significant theoretical contributions to physics, chemistry, and mathematics. His work on the applications of thermodynamics was instrumental in transforming physical chemistry into a rigorous inductive science. Together with James Clerk Maxwell and Ludwig Boltzmann, he created statistical mechanics (a term that he coined), explaining the laws of thermodynamics as consequences of the statistical properties of ensembles of the possible states of a physical system composed of many particles. Gibbs also worked on the application of Maxwell's equations to problems in physical optics.

Year 986 ( CMLXXXVI ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. It was a year marked by various significant events across different regions, particularly in European politics and medieval warfare. The city of Dubrovnik, which is now part of modern-day Croatia, officially became an autonomous political entity under Byzantine influence. Moreover, King Lothaire IV of France signed the Treaty of Senlis to clarify his dominions in the Holy Roman Empire, paving the way for territorial agreements and ensuring peaceful governance among various realms.

Tazio Giorgio Nuvolari ( ; 16 November 1892 – 11 August 1953 ) was an Italian racing driver . He first gained attention in motorcycle racing, winning the 1924 European Championship, and then quickly established himself as a dominant force in automobile racing. Nuvolari participated in over 360 car races, claiming numerous victories, including the prestigious Mille Miglia and the Le Mans 24 Hours. Nicknamed "The Flying Mantuan," he is considered one of the greatest pre-war Grand Prix drivers, showing unparalleled skill, fearlessness, and mechanical prowess behind the wheel.

The Boston transportation system includes roadway , subway , regional rail , air , and sea options for passenger and freight transport. Among these options, the Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority (MBTA) operates the subway and regional rail network, which provides reliable, efficient public transit throughout Greater Boston. Additionally, the city's extensive network of highways and roadways offer various routes for vehicles and buses, aiding daily commutes and business travel. Logan International Airport is the major air travel hub of Boston, offering numerous flights across the country and around the globe.

Depleted uranium (DU; also referred to in the past as Q-metal, depletalloy or D-38) is uranium with a lower content of the fissile isotope  than natural uranium. Natural uranium contains about  , while the DU used by the U.S. Department of Defense contains   or less. The less radioactive and non-fissile  constitutes the main component of depleted uranium. Uses of DU take advantage of its very high density of   ( denser than lead).Civilian uses include counterweights in aircraft, radiation shielding in medical radiation therapy and industrial radiography equipment, and containers for transporting radioactive materials.

Melissa Sue Anderson ( born September 26 , 1962 ) is an American-Canadian actress . She began her career as a child actress in the 1970s, gaining widespread recognition for her portrayal of Mary Ingalls on the popular NBC series "Little House on the Prairie" which ran from 1974 to 1981. In addition to her successful television work, she also starred in several films such as "Happy Birthday to Me" (1981) and "Dead Men Don't Die" (1990). Melissa became a Canadian citizen in 2007.

See also History of UnitarianismA number of notable people have considered themselves Unitarians , Universalists , and following the merger of both denominations in 1961, Unitarian Universalists. Some prominent figures include John Adams, Thomas Jefferson, Louisa May Alcott, Ralph Waldo Emerson, and Susan B. Anthony. This religious movement has its roots in Christianity but has evolved over time to include a more inclusive and diverse approach to spirituality and social justice. The core principles of Unitarian Universalism embrace the importance of individual conscience, freedom of belief, reason, tolerance, and the inherent worth and dignity of every person.

In the Ancient Greek religion , Hestia ( ; , `` hearth '' or `` fireside '' ) is the virgin goddess of the hearth, architecture, and domestic life. One of the twelve Olympian deities, she was the daughter of Cronus and Rhea, and the eldest sister of Zeus, Poseidon, and Hades. As the embodiment of a well-kept and functioning household, she was held in high esteem and venerated in every home. Offerings were made to Hestia before any other god, with the fire on the family hearth representing her presence.

A melody ( from Greek μελῳδία , melōidía , `` singing , chanting '' ) , also tune , voice , or line, refers to a sequence of musical tones that create a distinct, memorable, and expressive composition. Melodies serve as the backbone for many musical forms, including songs and instrumental pieces. They often feature repetitive rhythms, harmonies, and varied pitch to invoke an emotional response or thematic connection within the listener. The melody, typically shaped by individual notes that conform to a specific scale, can be accompanied by supporting harmonies, forming a well-balanced and intriguing musical piece that captivates the audience.

Strasbourg ( , , ; ; , ) is the prefecture and largest city of the Grand Est region of France, as well as the official seat of the European Parliament. Located near the border with Germany, Strasbourg is an important hub for transnational politics and diplomacy, in addition to being a significant cultural and economic center. The city's historic city center, Grande Île, is listed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site, attracting visitors with its distinctive architecture and famous landmarks like the Strasbourg Cathedral and the half-timbered houses of La Petite France.

Hilbert 's paradox of the Grand Hotel ( colloquial : Infinite Hotel Paradox or Hilbert 's Hotel ) is a thought experiment which illustrates a counterintuitive property of infinite sets. Proposed by mathematician David Hilbert in the 1920s, the paradox envisions a hypothetical hotel with infinitely many rooms, all of which are occupied. Despite its seemingly full occupancy, the hotel is always able to accommodate new guests without displacing any current occupants. To do this, each guest shifts to the room number double their current room number, thus freeing up all odd-numbered rooms.

East Malaysia , also known as Sabah , Sarawak and Labuan or Malaysian Borneo , is the part of Malaysia located on the island of Borneo. It consists of two regions, Sabah and Sarawak, as well as the Federal Territory of Labuan. With a combined land area of over 200,000 square kilometers, East Malaysia shares borders with Brunei and Indonesia. It offers diverse landscapes, from pristine beaches and coral reefs to lush rainforests, and it's home to unique flora and fauna, including orangutans and the largest flower in the world, the Rafflesia.

Magma  is the molten or semi-molten natural material from which all igneous rocks are formed. Magma is found beneath the surface of the Earth, and evidence of magmatism has also been discovered on other terrestrial planets and some natural satellites. Besides molten rock, magma may also contain suspended crystals and gas bubbles.Magma is produced by melting of the mantle or the crust in various tectonic settings, which on Earth include subduction zones, continental rift zones, mid-ocean ridges and hotspots. Mantle and crustal melts migrate upwards through the crust where they are thought to be stored in magma chambers or trans-crustal crystal-rich mush zones.

Norman Quentin Cook (born Quentin Leo Cook; 31st July 1963), also known by his stage name Fatboy Slim, is an English musician, DJ and record producer who helped to popularise the big beat genre in the 1990s. In the 1980s, Cook was the bassist for the Hull-based indie rock band the Housemartins, who achieved a UK number-one single with their a cappella cover of "Caravan of Love". After the Housemartins split, Cook formed the electronic band Beats International in Brighton, who produced the number-one single "Dub Be Good to Me".

Pas-de-Calais ( , `` strait of Calais '' ; ; also ) is a department in northern France named after the Strait of Calais, the narrowest point between the English Channel and the North Sea. Located within the region of Hauts-de-France, it shares borders with Belgium to the north, the French department of Nord to the east, and the picturesque coastline along the English Channel to the west. The department comprises two culturally distinct territories: the traditional and flat marshlands in the west, where agriculture thrives, and the densely forested and rolling hills of the east, rich in mining and industrial heritage.

A jubilee is a particular anniversary of an event, usually denoting the 25th, 40th, 50th, 60th, and the 70th anniversary. Of biblical origin, the term is often now used to denote the celebrations associated with the reign of a monarch after a milestone number of years have passed.Religious usageThe Jubilee ( yovel) year (every 50th year) and the Sabbatical year (every seventh year) are Biblical commandments concerning ownership of land and slaves. The laws concerning the Sabbatical year are still observed by many religious Jews in the State of Israel, while the Jubilee has not been observed for many centuries.

Relative density, or specific gravity, is the ratio of the density (mass of a unit volume) of a substance to the density of a given reference material. Specific gravity for liquids is nearly always measured with respect to water at its densest (at ); for gases, the reference is air at room temperature . The term "relative density" is often preferred in scientific usage. If a substance's relative density is less than 1 then it is less dense than the reference; if greater than 1 then it is denser than the reference.

The Novikov self-consistency principle, also known as the Novikov self-consistency conjecture and Larry Niven's law of conservation of history, is a principle developed by Russian physicist Igor Dmitriyevich Novikov in the mid-1980s. Novikov intended it to solve the problem of paradoxes in time travel, which is theoretically permitted in certain solutions of general relativity that contain what are known as closed timelike curves. The principle asserts that if an event exists that would cause a paradox or any "change" to the past whatsoever, then the probability of that event is zero.

The MGM-31A Pershing was the missile used in the Pershing 1 and Pershing 1a field artillery missile systems . It was developed by the United States during the late 1950s and early 1960s as a solid-fueled, two-stage medium-range ballistic missile (MRBM). With a maximum range of approximately 740 miles, the MGM-31A was designed to carry a single, nuclear warhead weighing up to 400 kilotons. The Pershing missiles were used by the U.S. Army and NATO forces as part of their Cold War deterrence strategy against potential attacks from the Soviet Union and Warsaw Pact countries.

Eugène Adrien Roland Georges Garros ( ; 6 October 1888 – 5 October 1918 ) was a French pioneering aviator and fighter pilot during World War I. Born in Paris, Garros showed great interest in aviation from a young age and began his flying career in 1909. Known for his exceptional flying skills, he became one of the first pilots to make a non-stop flight across the Mediterranean in 1913. Garros gained notoriety for his unique invention of a synchronization device, which enabled machine guns to fire through an aircraft's propeller without causing damage, greatly changing air combat strategies.

The San Diego Zoo Safari Park, originally named the San Diego Wild Animal Park until 2010, is an 1,800 acre (730 ha) zoo in the San Pasqual Valley area of San Diego, California, near Escondido. It is one of the largest tourist attractions in San Diego County. The park houses a large array of wild and endangered animals including species from the continents of Africa, Asia, Europe, North and South America, and Australia. The park is in a semi-arid environment, and one of its most notable features is the Africa Tram, which explores the expansive African exhibits.

The covalent radius, rcov, is a measure of the size of an atom that forms part of one covalent bond. It is usually measured either in picometres (pm) or angstroms (Å), with 1 Å = 100 pm.In principle, the sum of the two covalent radii should equal the covalent bond length between two atoms, R(AB) = r(A) + r(B). Moreover, different radii can be introduced for single, double and triple bonds (r1, r2 and r3 below), in a purely operational sense.

Pizza Hut is an American multinational restaurant chain and international franchise founded in 1958 in Wichita, Kansas by Dan and Frank Carney. They serve their signature pan pizza and other dishes including pasta, breadsticks and desserts.The chain has 17,639 restaurants worldwide as of 2020,making it the world's largest pizza chain by number of locations.It is a subsidiary of Yum! Brands, Inc., one of the world's largest restaurant companies.HistoryPizza Hut was founded on June 15, 1958, by two brothers, Dan and Frank Carney, both Wichita State students, as a single location in Wichita, Kansas.

Willow Rosenberg is a fictional character created for the fantasy television series Buffy the Vampire Slayer ( 1997–2003 ) . She was portrayed by Alyson Hannigan throughout the show's entire run. Willow started as a shy and nerdy high school student, known for her brilliance in academics and computer skills. As a close friend of the titular character, Buffy Summers, Willow slowly developed her skills in witchcraft and transformed into a confident and powerful witch. Over the course of the show, her storylines highlighted friendship, the responsible use of power, and exploring her sexuality.

Pope Gregory I ( ; – 12 March 604 ) , commonly known as Saint Gregory the Great , was the Bishop of Rome from September 590 until his death in 604. He played a key role in defining and strengthening the papacy and made significant contributions to liturgical music, specifically Gregorian chant. Additionally, he wrote notable theological and pastoral works and carried out numerous missionary projects to spread Christianity across Europe. Renowned for his wisdom and devotion, Pope Gregory I displayed immense leadership through diplomatic missions, poverty alleviation, and reorganizing the administration of church lands.

Tru64 UNIX is a discontinued 64-bit UNIX operating system for the Alpha instruction set architecture (ISA), currently owned by Hewlett-Packard (HP). Previously, Tru64 UNIX was a product of Compaq, and before that, Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC), where it was known as Digital UNIX (originally DEC OSF/1 AXP).As its original name suggests, Tru64 UNIX is based on the OSF/1 operating system. DEC's previous UNIX product was known as Ultrix and was based on BSD.It is unusual among commercial UNIX implementations, as it is built on top of the Mach kernel developed at Carnegie Mellon University.

Giovanni Paisiello ( or Paesiello ; 9 May 1740 – 5 June 1816 ) was an Italian composer of the Classical era, specializing in opera, vocal, and instrumental music. Born in Taranto, he began his career as a choirboy in a local church, showing great promise in music at a young age. Paisiello later studied at the prestigious Conservatorio di S. Onofrio in Naples under esteemed instructors, paving the way for an illustrious career. Throughout his life, Paisiello wrote numerous operas, piano works, and sacred music, gaining the admiration and patronage of European royalty, including Catherine the Great of Russia.

Malayalam ( ; , ) is a Dravidian language spoken in the Indian state of Kerala and the union territories of Lakshadweep and Puducherry by around 44 million native speakers globally. Being the official language of Kerala, Malayalam boasts its diverse dialects that can vary geographically and based on different communities. It derives a large proportion of its vocabulary from Sanskrit, with significant influence from Tamil, Arabic, and English. Written in the unique Malayalam script, which has 54 alphasyllabary letters, the language holds a rich tradition of literature encompassing various genres like poetry, drama, prose, and stories.

Chrysippus of Soli (; , ;  ) was a Greek Stoic philosopher. He was a native of Soli, Cilicia, but moved to Athens as a young man, where he became a pupil of Cleanthes in the Stoic school. When Cleanthes died, around 230 BC, Chrysippus became the third head of the school. A prolific writer, Chrysippus expanded the fundamental doctrines of Zeno of Citium, the founder of the school, which earned him the title of Second Founder of Stoicism.Chrysippus excelled in logic, the theory of knowledge, ethics, and physics.

Bread is a staple food prepared from a dough of flour ( usually wheat ) and water , usually by baking. Throughout history, bread has been an essential part of many cultures due to its versatility and simple production process. It can be produced in various shapes, sizes, textures, and flavors by adding ingredients such as yeast, sugar, salt, butter, nuts, fruits, or spices. Bread provides essential nutrients such as carbohydrates for energy, fiber for digestion, and proteins for growth and maintenance. Many varieties are also fortified with vitamins and minerals for improved nutrition.

Halebidu (IAST: Haḷēbīḍ, literally "old capital, city, encampment" or "ruined city") is a town located in Hassan District, Karnataka, India. Historically known as Dorasamudra or Dwarasamudra, Halebidu became the regal capital of the Hoysala Empire in the 11th century CE. In the modern era literature it is sometimes referred to as Halebeedu or Halebid as the phonetic equivalent, a local name after it was damaged and deserted after being ransacked and looted twice by the forces of the Delhi Sultanate in the 14th century.Halebidu is home to some of the best examples of Hindu and Jain temples with Hoysala architecture.

Thrust is a reaction force described quantitatively by Newton 's third law . When a system expels or accelerates mass in one direction, an equal and opposite force is exerted on that system, resulting in thrust. This principle is exemplified by propulsion systems such as jet engines, rocket engines, or even a simple propeller. The expelled mass can be a fuel, such as in chemical rockets or compressed gas, such as in air-powered thrusters. Alternatively, an external mass can be accelerated, such as water or air, to create thrust in propulsion systems like ship propellers or airplane jet engines.

In commutative algebra , the prime spectrum ( or simply the spectrum ) of a ring R is the set of all prime ideals of R, denoted as Spec(R). It is an essential tool for understanding the structure of commutative rings and their relationship to algebraic geometry. Through the process of localizing and taking prime ideals into account, the prime spectrum reveals a geometric structure embedded in the ring. The elements of Spec(R) represent geometrical points or closed points in the algebraic varieties related to the ring, thereby providing a bridge between commutative algebra and algebraic geometry.

Year 926 ( CMXXVI ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. During this time, major historical events shaped the course of various societies around the world. In England, the young King Æthelstan worked to unify his kingdom after defeating the Vikings in the Battle of Brunanburh. In Constantinople, the Byzantine Emperor Romanos I led a major war against the Arabs that expanded the empire's borders, while cultural advancements were made in Chinese and Indian civilizations under the reigns of their respective emperors.

The Bell OH-58 Kiowa is a family of single-engine, single-rotor, military helicopters used for observation, utility, and direct fire support. Bell Helicopter manufactured the OH-58 for the United States Army based on its Model 206A JetRanger helicopter. The OH-58 was in continuous U.S. Army service from 1969 to 2017, when it was replaced in these roles by the Boeing AH-64 Apache and Eurocopter UH-72 Lakota.The latest model, the OH-58D Kiowa Warrior, is primarily operated in an armed reconnaissance role in support of ground troops. The OH-58 has been exported to Austria, Canada, Croatia, the Dominican Republic, Taiwan, Saudi Arabia, and Greece.

Mary Anning (21 May 1799 – 9 March 1847) was an English fossil collector, dealer, and palaeontologist who became known around the world for finds she made in Jurassic marine fossil beds in the cliffs along the English Channel at Lyme Regis in the county of Dorset in Southwest England. Anning's findings contributed to changes in scientific thinking about prehistoric life and the history of the Earth.Anning searched for fossils in the area's Blue Lias and Charmouth Mudstone cliffs, particularly during the winter months when landslides exposed new fossils that had to be collected quickly before they were lost to the sea.

The San Diego Zoo Safari Park , originally named the San Diego Wild Animal Park until 2010 , is an 800-acre wildlife sanctuary located in Escondido, California, and operated by the San Diego Zoo. Home to over 2,600 animals from over 300 species and showcasing extensive botanical collections, it provides visitors with an immersive and interactive experience by simulating a realistic African safari. Its major habitats include African Plains, Asian Savanna, Gorilla Forest, and Lion Camp. In addition to showcasing and preserving wildlife, the Safari Park plays a significant role in various global conservation initiatives, including endangered species breeding programs, wildlife rehabilitation, and habitat restoration projects.

Year 926 (CMXXVI) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Spring – The Italian nobles turn against King Rudolph II of Burgundy and request that Hugh of Provence, the effective ruler of Lower Burgundy, be elected as king of Italy. Rudolph's father-in-law Duke Burchard II of Swabia is ambushed and killed near Novara, by the henchmen of Archbishop Lambert of Milan. Rudolph, disillusioned by the news, returns to Burgundy to protect himself. Hugh has himself crowned King of Italy.

A drought is an event of prolonged shortages in the water supply, whether atmospheric (below-average precipitation), surface water or ground water. A drought can last for months or years, or may be declared after as few as 15 days. It can have a substantial impact on the ecosystem and agriculture of the affected region and harm to the local economy. Annual dry seasons in the tropics significantly increase the chances of a drought developing and subsequent bush fires. Periods of heat can significantly worsen drought conditions by hastening evaporation of water vapour.Drought is a recurring feature of the climate in most parts of the world.

Edward Higgins White II ( November 14 , 1930 – January 27 , 1967 ) was an American aeronautical engineer , U.S. Air Force officer, test pilot, and NASA astronaut. Born in San Antonio, Texas, he earned his Bachelor of Science degree in Mechanical Engineering from West Point in 1952, and a Master's degree in Aeronautical Engineering from the University of Michigan in 1959. White became an accomplished test pilot and was selected to join NASA in 1962. He is best known as the first American to walk in space during the Gemini 4 mission in 1965, a significant milestone for the US space program.

This list of Anuran families shows all extant families of Anura. Anura is an order of animals in the class Amphibia that includes frogs and toads. More than 5,000 species are described in the order. The living anurans are typically divided into three suborders: Archaeobatrachia, Mesobatrachia, and Neobatrachia. This classification is based on such morphological features as the number of vertebrae, the structure of the pectoral girdle, and the morphology of tadpoles.TaxonomyThe archaeobatrachians are the most primitive of frogs. These frogs have morphological characteristics which are found mostly in extinct frogs, and are absent in most of the modern frog species.

The Palmer Raids were a series of raids conducted in November 1919 and January 1920 by the United States Department of Justice under the administration of President Woodrow Wilson to capture and arrest suspected socialists, mostly Italian immigrants and Eastern European immigrants and especially anarchists and communists, and deport them from the United States. The raids particularly targeted Italian immigrants and Eastern European Jewish immigrants with alleged leftist ties, with particular focus on Italian anarchists and immigrant leftist labor activists. The raids and arrests occurred under the leadership of Attorney General A. Mitchell Palmer, with 3,000 arrested.

In linguistics , an adjective ( abbreviated ) is a word that modifies a noun or noun phrase or describes its referent's properties or attributes. Adjectives are often used to enhance and give more specific meaning to the nouns they accompany, allowing for more vivid and concise communication. There are different types of adjectives, including descriptive, possessive, demonstrative, interrogative, and numeral. They provide a richer understanding of a particular object or event. For instance, descriptive adjectives describe physical or abstract qualities, while possessive adjectives indicate ownership or possession.

Sparta ( Doric Greek : Σπάρτα , Spártā ; Attic Greek : Σπάρτη , Spártē ) was a prominent city-state in ancient Greece, situated on the banks of the River Eurotas in Laconia, in the southeastern part of the Peloponnese peninsula. It emerged as a powerful political and military force around the 10th century BC, largely due to its effective military and social system, focused on discipline, loyalty, and strength. The Spartans became known for their warrior culture, producing highly skilled and feared soldiers, which gave Sparta considerable influence throughout the Classical Greek period.

Crocodiles ( family Crocodylidae ) or true crocodiles are large semiaquatic reptiles that live throughout the tropics in Africa , Asia, the Americas, and Australia. They belong to the order Crocodilia, which also includes caimans, gharials, and alligators. Crocodiles are known for their strong, powerful jaws and sharp teeth, making them fearsome predators. They primarily reside in freshwater habitats like rivers, lakes, wetlands, and sometimes in brackish waters. Crocodiles are carnivorous, with their diet primarily consisting of fish, birds, and small mammals.

The Australian Secret Intelligence Service  (ASIS) is the foreign intelligence agency of Australia, tasked with the covert collection of information overseas through personal contacts and other means of human intelligence. It is part of the Australian Intelligence Community and is also responsible for counter-intelligence and liaising with the intelligence agencies of other countries. ASIS was formed in 1952 but its existence remained secret within much of the government until 1972. ASIS is compared to the American CIA and the British MI6.ASIS is part of the Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade (DFAT) portfolio and has its headquarters in Canberra.

Year 980 ( CMLXXX ) was a leap year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. It marked notable historical events and the emergence of prominent figures that influenced various regions during this period. For instance, Vikings under the leadership of Olav Tryggvason won the battle at Hjorungavag, paving the way for the establishment of the first unified Norwegian state. In Western Europe, Emperor Otto II created the March of Meissen from which present-day Germany eventually developed. Meanwhile, various scientific and artistic pursuits blossomed under the Andalusian ruler Al-Hakam II in Cordoba, showcasing a remarkable spirit of unity among diverse cultures.

Sir Philip Nicholas Outram Pullman  (born 19 October 1946) is an English writer. His books include the fantasy trilogy His Dark Materials and The Good Man Jesus and the Scoundrel Christ, a fictionalised biography of Jesus. In 2008, The Times named Pullman one of the "50 greatest British writers since 1945". In a 2004 BBC poll, he was named the eleventh most influential person in British culture. He was knighted in the 2019 New Year Honours for services to literature.Northern Lights, the first volume in His Dark Materials, won the 1995 Carnegie Medal of the Library Association as the year's outstanding English-language children's book.

Brighella (in Bergamasque dialect: Brighèla) is a comic, masked character from the Italian theatre style Commedia dell'arte. His early costume consisted of loosely fitting, white smock and pants with green trim and was often equipped with a  (also  or , depending on region) or slap stick, or else with a wooden sword. Later he took to wearing a sort of livery with a matching cape. He wore a greenish half-mask (traditionally olive-green) displaying a look of preternatural lust and greed. It is distinguished by a hook nose and thick lips, along with a thick twirled mustache to give him an offensive characteristic.

The subset sum problem (SSP) is a decision problem in computer science. In its most general formulation, there is a multiset  of integers and a target-sum , and the question is to decide whether any subset of the integers sum to precisely . The problem is known to be NP-complete. Moreover, some restricted variants of it are NP-complete too, for example: The variant in which all inputs are positive. The variant in which inputs may be positive or negative, and . For example, given the set , the answer is yes because the subset  sums to zero.

Akasha or Akash ( Sanskrit ) means space or sky or æther in traditional Indian cosmology , depending on the religion or philosophical system. The term has various interpretations in Hinduism, Buddhism, and Jainism, where it plays a critical role in shaping the understanding of the universe and its spiritual dimensions. In Hinduism, Akasha represents the element from which all creation stems, one of the Pancha Mahabhuta, the five elements constituting life. It embodies the eternal omnipresence of divinity and contains the subtle vibrations of mantras and energies of thoughts.

A seed is an embryonic plant enclosed in a protective outer covering . The formation of the seed is part of the process of reproduction in seed plants, the spermatophytes, including the gymnosperms and the angiosperms. Seeds develop following fertilization of the ovule by male sperm cells found in pollen. After fertilization, the resulting zygote undergoes cell division and differentiation to form an embryo, along with a nutrient-storage area (endosperm), all surrounded by the seed coat. Seeds serve various functions such as dispersal to new locations and providing nourishment for the embryonic plant during germination.

ESP most commonly refers to: Extrasensory perception, a paranormal ability Spain (España) - ISO three-letter country code for SpainESP may also refer to:Arts, entertainmentMusic  ESP Guitars, a manufacturer of electric guitars E.S. Posthumus, an independent music group formed in 2000, that produces cinematic style music ESP-Disk, a 1960s free-jazz record label based in New York The Electric Soft Parade, a British band formed in 2001 Eric Singer Project, side project founded in the 1990s by musician Eric Singer ESP, a collaboration between Space Tribe and other artistsSongs, albums  E.S.P.

Giovanni Paisiello (or Paesiello; 9 May 1740 – 5 June 1816) was an Italian composer of the Classical era, and was the most popular opera composer of the late 1700s. His operatic style influenced Mozart and Rossini, and his music was championed by Haydn and Beethoven.LifePaisiello was born in Taranto in the Apulia region and educated by the Jesuits there. He became known for his beautiful singing voice and in 1754 was sent to the Conservatorio di S. Onofrio at Naples, where he studied under Francesco Durante, and eventually became assistant master.

was a Japanese television cooking show produced by Fuji Television . The series , which premiered on October 10 , 1993, ran for over a decade until its final episode on September 19, 2004. Hosted by renowned chef Chen Kenichi, the show featured top chefs and their unique skills as they competed in the creation of tantalizing dishes using unusual ingredients or themes. With its immense popularity in Japan, the show not only influenced the growth of Japanese cooking shows but also made a significant impact on international culinary culture, inspiring many spin-offs, such as the American series Iron Chef.

D'Urville Island , Te Reo Māori name ( 'red heavens look to the south ' ) , is an island in New Zealand, located in the Marlborough Sounds at the northeastern tip of the South Island. Named after the French explorer Jules Dumont d'Urville, the island has a rich Māori history, dating back to the 13th century when tribes such as the Ngāti Kuia, Ngāti Apa, and Rangitane settled in the area. Surrounded by stunning native forests and sheltered bays, D'Urville Island is a popular destination for visitors who seek relaxation, solitude, or an off-the-beaten-track adventure.

The pancreas is an organ of the digestive system and endocrine system of vertebrates. In humans, it is located in the abdomen behind the stomach and functions as a gland. The pancreas is a mixed or heterocrine gland, i.e. it has both an endocrine and a digestive exocrine function. 99% of the pancreas is exocrine and 1% is endocrine. As an endocrine gland, it functions mostly to regulate blood sugar levels, secreting the hormones insulin, glucagon, somatostatin, and pancreatic polypeptide. As a part of the digestive system, it functions as an exocrine gland secreting pancreatic juice into the duodenum through the pancreatic duct.

The Space Shuttle program was the fourth human spaceflight program carried out by the U.S. National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA). The program was active from 1981 to 2011, involving 135 successful launches over its three-decade tenure. It began with the aim of reducing space exploration costs by using a reusable spacecraft capable of carrying humans, equipment, and materials to space. In addition to missions in Earth's orbit and the launch of important observatories, the Space Shuttle program was vital in the assembly and operation of the International Space Station (ISS).

Martin Heidegger (; ; 26 September 188926 May 1976) was a German philosopher who is best known for contributions to phenomenology, hermeneutics, and existentialism. He is among  the most important and influential philosophers of the 20th century.In Heidegger's fundamental text Being and Time (1927), "Dasein" is introduced as a term for the type of being that humans possess. Dasein has been translated as "being there". Heidegger believes that Dasein already has a "pre-ontological" and non-abstract understanding that shapes how it lives. This mode of being he terms "being-in-the-world".

Sir Robert Alexander Watson Watt  (13 April 1892 – 5 December 1973) was a British pioneer of radio direction finding and radar technology.Watt began his career in radio physics with a job at the Met Office, where he began looking for accurate ways to track thunderstorms using the radio signals given off by lightning. This led to the 1920s development of a system later known as high-frequency direction finding (HFDF or "huff-duff"). Although well publicized at the time, the system's enormous military potential was not developed until the late 1930s.

In mathematics and physics , Laplace 's equation is a second-order partial differential equation named after Pierre-Simon Laplace , who first studied its properties. It is the simplest elliptic partial differential equation and plays a significant role in many areas of science, including fluid dynamics, electrostatics, heat conduction, and tidal analysis. The equation is given by the sum of second-order derivatives of a scalar potential function with respect to space variables, and it equals zero. Solutions of Laplace's equation, called harmonic functions, exhibit numerous interesting properties, such as being smooth and having the mean value property.

Blake Edwards (born William Blake Crump; July 26, 1922 – December 15, 2010) was an American actor, film director, producer and screenwriter.Edwards began his career in the 1940s as an actor, but he soon began writing screenplays and radio scripts before turning to producing and directing in television and films. His best-known films include Breakfast at Tiffany's, Days of Wine and Roses, 10, Victor/Victoria, and the hugely successful Pink Panther film series with British actor Peter Sellers. Often thought of as primarily a director of comedies, he also directed several drama, musical, and detective films.

Hilbert's paradox of the Grand Hotel  (colloquial: Infinite Hotel Paradox or Hilbert's Hotel) is a thought experiment which illustrates a counterintuitive property of infinite sets. It is demonstrated that a fully occupied hotel with infinitely many rooms may still accommodate additional guests, even infinitely many of them, and this process may be repeated infinitely often. The idea was introduced by David Hilbert in a 1924 lecture "Über das Unendliche", reprinted in , and was popularized through George Gamow's 1947 book One Two Three... Infinity.The paradoxConsider a hypothetical hotel with a countably infinite number of rooms, all of which are occupied.

Gossypium  is a genus of flowering plants in the tribe Gossypieae of the mallow family, Malvaceae, from which cotton is harvested. It is native to tropical and subtropical regions of the Old and New Worlds. There are about 50 Gossypium species, making it the largest genus in the tribe Gossypieae, and new species continue to be discovered. The name of the genus is derived from the Arabic word goz, which refers to a soft substance. Cotton is the primary natural fibre used by modern humans, amounting to about 80% of world natural fibre production.

Palm OS ( also known as Garnet OS ) is a discontinued mobile operating system initially developed by Palm , Inc., in 1996. Designed primarily for personal digital assistants (PDAs), it soon gained widespread popularity, leading to the release of different versions and applications catering to diverse user needs. While it enjoyed great success with over 50 million users globally, increased competition, primarily from iOS and Android, significantly reduced its market share over time. Eventually, Palm announced the transition from Garnet OS to WebOS in 2009, signaling the end of the platform.

Mycenae ( ;  or , Mykē̂nai or Mykḗnē) is an archaeological site near Mykines in Argolis, north-eastern Peloponnese, Greece. It is located about  south-west of Athens;  north of Argos; and  south of Corinth. The site is  inland from the Saronic Gulf and built upon a hill rising  above sea level.In the second millennium BC, Mycenae was one of the major centres of Greek civilization, a military stronghold which dominated much of southern Greece, Crete, the Cyclades and parts of southwest Anatolia. The period of Greek history from about 1600 BC to about 1100 BC is called Mycenaean in reference to Mycenae.

Giuseppe Saverio Raffaele Mercadante (baptised 17 September 179517 December 1870) was an Italian composer, particularly of operas. While Mercadante may not have retained the international celebrity of Gaetano Donizetti or Gioachino Rossini beyond his own lifetime, he composed as prolific a number of works as either; and his development of operatic structures, melodic styles and orchestration contributed significantly to the foundations upon which Giuseppe Verdi built his dramatic technique.BiographyEarly yearsMercadante was born illegitimate in Altamura, near Bari in Apulia; his precise date of birth has not been recorded, but he was baptised on 17 September 1795.

Triskaidekaphobia ( , ; ) is fear or avoidance of the number . It is also a reason for the fear of Friday the 13th, called paraskevidekatriaphobia (from Greek: Paraskevi, meaning "Friday") or friggatriskaidekaphobia (after Frigga, the Norse goddess for whom "Friday" is named in English). This superstition has ancient origins, rooted in biblical times when the Last Supper had 13 people attending, leading to Christ's crucifixion on a Friday. While some merely experience anxiety surrounding this number, others with triskaidekaphobia experience intense fear that severely impacts their lives.

Pope Leo XI (; 2 June 153527 April 1605), born Alessandro Ottaviano de' Medici, was head of the Catholic Church and ruler of the Papal States from 1 April 1605 to his death. His pontificate is one of the briefest in history, having lasted under a month. He was from the prominent House of Medici originating from Florence. Medici's mother opposed his entering the priesthood and sought to prevent it by having him given secular honours, but after her death he eventually was ordained a priest in 1567.

Adenine ( symbol A or Ade ) is a nucleobase ( a purine derivative ) . It is one of the five nucleobases that form the building blocks of DNA and RNA, the others being guanine, cytosine, thymine (found in DNA only), and uracil (found in RNA only). Adenine plays a crucial role in various biochemical processes in the cell, such as the synthesis of adenosine triphosphate (ATP), which functions as the cell's main energy currency, as well as nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NAD) and flavin adenine dinucleotide (FAD), important coenzymes involved in metabolism.

John D. Carmack II (born August 20, 1970) is an American computer programmer and video game developer. He co-founded the video game company id Software and was the lead programmer of its 1990s games Commander Keen, Wolfenstein 3D, Doom, Quake, and their sequels. Carmack made innovations in 3D computer graphics, such as his Carmack's Reverse algorithm for shadow volumes. In 2013, he resigned from id to work full-time at Oculus VR, where he served as CTO and later Consulting CTO in 2019.BiographyEarly lifeCarmack was born in Shawnee Mission, Kansas, the son of local television news reporter Stan Carmack.

Year 984 (CMLXXXIV) was a leap year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Spring – German boy-king Otto III (4-years old) is seized by the deposed Henry II (the Wrangler), duke of Bavaria, who has recovered his duchy and claims the regency as a member of the Ottonian Dynasty. But Henry is forced to hand over Otto to his mother, empress consort Theophanu. King Ramiro III loses his throne to Bermudo II (the rival king of Galicia), who also becomes ruler of the entire Kingdom of León (modern-day Spain).

Mystery religions , mystery cults , sacred mysteries or simply mysteries , were religious schools of the Greco-Roman world for which participation was reserved to initiates. Rooted in various traditions and rituals, these religions sought to provide followers with a deep, personal understanding and connection with the divine. The initiation into these secret cults typically involved highly symbolic ceremonies, believed to grant direct access to divine wisdom, insight, and blessings. Some well-known mystery religions include the Eleusinian Mysteries, dedicated to the goddesses Demeter and Persephone, and the Mithraic Mysteries, which revolved around the Persian god Mithras.

(; "The Master-Singers of Nuremberg"), WWV 96, is a music drama, or opera, in three acts, by Richard Wagner. It is the longest opera commonly performed, taking nearly four and a half hours, not counting two breaks, and is traditionally not cut. With Hans von Bülow conducting it was first performed on 21 June 1868 at the National Theater in Munich, today home of Bavarian State Opera.The story is set in Nuremberg in the mid-16th century. At the time, Nuremberg was a free imperial city and one of the centers of the Renaissance in Northern Europe.

Fermat's principle, also known as the principle of least time, is the link between ray optics and wave optics. In its original "strong" form, Fermat's principle states that the path taken by a ray between two given points is the path that can be traveled in the least time. In order to be true in all cases, this statement must be weakened by replacing the "least" time with a time that is "stationary" with respect to variations of the path — so that a deviation in the path causes, at most, a second-order change in the traversal time.

Thermonuclear fusion is the process of atoms combining or “ fusing ” together with huge amounts of heat . There are various approaches to achieve this, such as magnetic confinement and inertial confinement. The primary goal is to sustainably reach and maintain the conditions needed for fusion to occur, generating large amounts of energy while producing very little pollution. Successful thermonuclear fusion would provide an essentially limitless and clean energy source, as its main fuel - hydrogen - is abundant in water on Earth. Furthermore, the by-products of fusion are significantly less radioactive than current nuclear fission reactions, reducing environmental risks and nuclear waste issues.

Year 980 (CMLXXX) was a leap year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Peace is concluded between Emperor Otto II (the Red) and King Lothair III (or Lothair IV) at Margut, ending the Franco-German war of 978–980. Lothair renounces his claim on Lower Lorraine, while Otto promises to recognize Lothair's son Louis V as the rightful heir of the West Frankish Kingdom. June 11 – Vladimir I (the Great), grand prince of Kiev, consolidates the Kievan realm from modern Ukraine to the Baltic Sea.

The fisherman's knot is a bend (a knot for joining two lines) with a symmetrical structure consisting of two overhand knots, each tied around the standing part of the other. Other names for the fisherman's knot include: angler's knot, English knot, halibut knot, waterman's knot.Though the fisherman's knot is associated with fishing, it can slip when tied in nylon monofilament and other slippery lines; however, if more holding strength is required, the overhand knots can be made with more turns, as in the double fisherman's knot, and so on.

Dresden ( , ; Upper Saxon : Dräsdn ; ) is the capital city of the German state of Saxony and a cultural and economic hub in eastern Germany. It is located near the border with the Czech Republic and has a rich history, dating back more than 1,200 years. Today, Dresden is home to over half a million residents and offers a diverse range of attractions for tourists, including baroque architecture, notable museums, and impressive gardens. Dresden is also known for its thriving technology and research industries, with strong concentrations in semiconductor manufacturing, software development, and innovative science projects.

was the 69th emperor of Japan , according to the traditional order of succession.Go-Suzaku 's reign spanned the years from 1001 to 1016. Go-Suzaku, whose personal name was Atsuhira, was a son of Emperor Ichijo and his reign saw the increasing influence of the powerful Fujiwara clan over the Imperial Court. His era was marked by stability and a revival in Chinese literature and culture. Important events in his reign included the establishment of official kanji for Japanese provinces, increased building projects such as temples, and artistic growth within Japan, including the prominence of painters and calligraphers.

Eagle is the common name for many large birds of prey of the family Accipitridae . Eagles belong to several groups of genera, which are not closely related. These majestic creatures can be found all around the world, with the exception of Antarctica. With their powerful wings, sharp beaks, and incredible vision, eagles have established themselves as apex predators in various ecosystems. There are over 60 different species of eagles, and they can be broadly categorized into four groups: the fish eagles, booted eagles, snake eagles, and the Harpy eagles.

Year 878 ( DCCCLXXVIII ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. In the year 878, the geopolitical landscape was marked by significant events, both peaceful and turbulent. Key occurrences included the continued rise of the Great Frankish Empire under the reign of King Charles II the Bald. The expansion of Viking settlement throughout the British Isles brought many skirmishes along with cultural and technological advancements. The beginning stages of a prosperous Islamic Golden Age were characterized by a flourishing culture, scientific achievements, and architectural innovations throughout much of the known world at that time.

Tamar the Great ( , lit . `` King Tamar '' ) ( 1160 – 18 January 1213 ) reigned as the Queen of Georgia from 1184 to 1213, presiding over the apex of the Georgian Golden Age. She was the first woman to rule Georgia in her own right and has become an iconic figure in Georgian history. A member of the Bagrationi dynasty, her reign was marked by significant military victories and flourishing culture. Tamar continued the ambitious policies of her father, George III, by consolidating power domestically and expanding the Georgian kingdom's influence in the South Caucasus and beyond.

Juan Moreno y Herrera–Jiménez (born 30 July 1948), known as Jean Reno , is a French actor of Andalusian Spanish origin. He has worked in American, French, English, Japanese, Spanish and Italian movie productions; Reno appeared in films such as Crimson Rivers, Godzilla, The Da Vinci Code, Mission: Impossible, The Pink Panther, Ronin, Les Visiteurs, Wasabi, The Big Blue, Hector and the Search for Happiness and Léon: The Professional.Early lifeReno was born Juan Moreno y Herrera-Jiménez in Casablanca, Morocco. His parents were Spanish, natives of Sanlúcar de Barrameda and Jerez de la Frontera in Andalucia.

Fighting Fantasy is a series of single-player role-playing gamebooks created by Steve Jackson and Ian Livingstone. The first volume in the series was published in paperback by Puffin in 1982.The series distinguished itself by mixing Choose Your Own Adventure-style storytelling with a dice-based role-playing element included within the books themselves. The caption on many of the covers claimed each title was an adventure "in which YOU are the hero!" The majority of the titles followed a fantasy theme, although science fiction, post-apocalyptic, superhero, and modern horror gamebooks were also published.

Stephanie Lynn Nicks (born May 26, 1948) is an American singer, songwriter, and producer known for her work with the band Fleetwood Mac and as a solo artist.After starting her career as a duo with her then-boyfriend Lindsey Buckingham, releasing the album Buckingham Nicks to little success, Nicks joined Fleetwood Mac in 1975, helping the band to become one of the best-selling music acts of all time with over 120 million records sold worldwide. Rumours, the band's second album with Nicks, became one of the best-selling albums of all time, being certified 20× platinum in the US.

Lindsey Adams Buckingham ( born October 3 , 1949 ) is an American singer , musician , songwriter , and producer, best known as the lead guitarist and one of the vocalists of the British-American rock band Fleetwood Mac. He was introduced to Stevie Nicks, who eventually joined the band with him, forming an iconic duo during Fleetwood Mac's heyday in the 1970s and 80s. Their intricate guitar work and distinctive vocals, combined with Buckingham's prolific songwriting abilities, led the group to release classic albums like "Rumours" and "Tusk."

The fisherman 's knot is a bend ( a knot for joining two lines ) with a symmetrical structure consisting of two overhand knots, each tied around the standing part of the other. It is also known as the angler's knot, or the English knot, and is a popular choice among anglers, as it securely joins lines of different diameters and materials. The knot can be easily tied in wet or slippery conditions, making it an ideal option for various water sports activities, including fishing, sailing, and even rescue operations.

Pope Leo IV (790 – 17 July 855) was the bishop of Rome and ruler of the Papal States from 10 April 847 to his death. He is remembered for repairing Roman churches that had been damaged during the Arab raid against Rome, and for building the Leonine Wall around Vatican Hill to protect the city. Pope Leo organized a league of Italian cities who fought and won the sea Battle of Ostia against the Saracens.Early careerA Roman by birth, Leo received his early education at Rome in the monastery of St. Martin, near St. Peter's.

North America 's first transcontinental railroad ( known originally as the `` Pacific Railroad '' and later as the `` Overland Route") was completed in 1869, revolutionizing transportation and trade in the region. Spanning nearly 2,000 miles, the railroad connected the existing Eastern networks in Council Bluffs, Iowa with San Francisco, California, and the burgeoning settlements on the Pacific coast. This engineering marvel was primarily built by Central Pacific and Union Pacific Railroad companies, greatly advancing Western expansion by promoting ease of mobility and enabling the rapid exchange of goods and ideas.

Parasports are sports played by people with a disability, including physical and intellectual disabilities. Some parasports are forms of adapted physical activities from existing able-bodied sports, while others have been specifically created for persons with a disability and do not have an able-bodied equivalent. Disability exists in four categories: physical, mental, permanent and temporary. At a competitive level, disability sport classifications are applied to allow people of varying abilities to face similar opposition.EtymologyThe term "parasports" arose as a portmanteau of the words paraplegic and sports. Though the sport has since included athletes of disabilities other than paraplegia, the term persists as a catch-all.

In linguistics, an adjective (abbreviated ) is a word that modifies a noun or noun phrase or describes its referent. Its semantic role is to change information given by the noun.Traditionally, adjectives were considered one of the main parts of speech of the English language, although historically they were classed together with nouns. Nowadays, certain words that usually had been classified as adjectives, including the, this, my, etc., typically are classed separately, as determiners.Some examples: That's an interesting idea. (attributive) That idea is interesting. (predicative)  The good, the bad, and the ugly.

In mathematics , the Dirac delta distribution ( distribution ) , also known as the unit impulse symbol , is a generalized function, often used to represent a very narrow or short impulse in different fields, like physics and engineering. Introduced by the physicist Paul Dirac, this distribution plays a crucial role in various mathematical transformations, such as Fourier and Laplace. It is defined to have an integral of one, indicating a concentrated effect around a specific point or instant. Additionally, it simplifies analytical calculations with a continuous spectrum of physical quantities, assisting scientists and engineers in solving various problems in diverse domains.
