Pope Leo VIII ( 915 – 1 March 965) was a Roman prelate who claimed the Holy See from 963 until 964 in opposition to John XII and Benedict V and again from 23 June 964 to his death. Today he is considered by the Catholic Church to have been an antipope during the first period and the legitimate pope during the second. An appointee of Holy Roman Emperor Otto I, Leo VIII's pontificate occurred after the period known as the Saeculum obscurum.Early lifeBorn in Rome in the region around the Clivus Argentarius, Leo came from an illustrious noble family.

Mary Anning ( 21 May 1799 – 9 March 1847 ) was an English fossil collector , dealer , and paleontologist who became known around the world for her significant finds in the Jurassic marine fossil beds in the cliffs along the English Channel at Lyme Regis. Despite her limited formal education and social status, her work in fossil discovery and research played a significant role in shaping our understanding of prehistoric life. Her major discoveries, such as the first correctly identified ichthyosaur skeleton and a complete plesiosaur skeleton, provided substantial contributions to the scientific field and strongly influenced the nineteenth-century debates on Earth's history and extinction theories.

The University of California, Los Angeles (UCLA) is a public land-grant research university in Los Angeles, California. UCLA’s academic roots were established in 1882 as a teachers college then known as the southern branch of the California State Normal School (now San José State University). This school was absorbed with the official founding of UCLA as the Southern Branch of the University of California in 1919, making it the second-oldest of the 10-campus University of California system (after UC Berkeley).UCLA offers 337 undergraduate and graduate degree programs in a wide range of disciplines, enrolling about 31,600 undergraduate and 14,300 graduate and professional students.

Gender is the range of characteristics pertaining to femininity and masculinity and differentiating between them. Depending on the context, this may include sex-based social structures (i.e. gender roles) and gender identity. Most cultures use a gender binary, having two genders (boys/men and girls/women); those who exist outside these groups may fall under the umbrella term non-binary. Some societies have specific genders besides "man" and "woman", such as the hijras of South Asia; these are often referred to as third genders (and fourth genders, etc.).

Pietro Mascagni (7 December 1863 – 2 August 1945) was an Italian composer primarily known for his operas. His 1890 masterpiece Cavalleria rusticana caused one of the greatest sensations in opera history and single-handedly ushered in the Verismo movement in Italian dramatic music. While it was often held that Mascagni, like Ruggiero Leoncavallo, was a "one-opera man" who could never repeat his first success, L'amico Fritz and Iris have remained in the repertoire in Europe (especially Italy) since their premieres.Mascagni wrote fifteen operas, an operetta, several orchestral and vocal works, and also songs and piano music.

A gold standard is a monetary system in which the standard economic unit of account is based on a fixed quantity of gold. The gold standard was the basis for the international monetary system from the 1870s to the early 1920s, and from the late 1920s to 1932 as well as from 1944 until 1971 when the United States unilaterally terminated convertibility of the US dollar to gold foreign central banks, effectively ending the Bretton Woods system. Many states still hold substantial gold reserves.Historically, the silver standard and bimetallism have been more common than the gold standard.

La traviata ( ; The Fallen Woman ) is an opera in three acts by Giuseppe Verdi set to an Italian libretto by Francesco Maria Piave. Based on Alexandre Dumas's La Dame aux Camélias, the tragic story revolves around the love and betrayal of a fallen woman named Violetta, a famed Parisian courtesan who battles with societal judgement and the weight of past mistakes. Although not an initial critical success due to casting issues during its premiere in 1853, the opera's touching portrayal of passion, redemption, and doomed love has helped solidify La traviata's popularity.

Risk is a strategy board game of diplomacy, conflict and conquest for two to six players. The standard version is played on a board depicting a political map of the world, divided into forty-two territories, which are grouped into six continents. Turns rotate among players who control armies of playing pieces with which they attempt to capture territories from other players, with results determined by dice rolls. Players may form and dissolve alliances during the course of the game. The goal of the game is to occupy every territory on the board and, in doing so, eliminate the other players.

The Sikorsky UH-60 Black Hawk is a four-blade , twin-engine , medium-lift utility helicopter manufactured by Sikorsky Aircraft . Sikorsky submitted the S-70 design for the United States Army's Utility Tactical Transport Aircraft System (UTTAS) competition in the early 1970s. The Black Hawk was ultimately selected as the winner and became operational in 1979. Since then, it has become a mainstay of numerous military and governmental organizations across the world due to its reliability and versatility. This helicopter can fulfill a variety of roles such as troop transport, air assault, search and rescue, and cargo carrying, making it an indispensable asset to any operation.

Tristan Tzara ( ; ; born Samuel or Samy Rosenstock , also known as S. Samyro ; – 25 December 1963) was a Romanian and French avant-garde poet, essayist, and performance artist, best known for being one of the central figures of the Dada movement. Active throughout the early 20th century, Tzara sought to challenge societal norms and promote new modes of expression. He made significant contributions to contemporary art, collaborating with various artists and writers, and co-founded influential literary reviews. His unique voice inspired countless other creatives and ultimately established Tristan Tzara as a pioneering force within European art and literature scenes.

Barbecue or barbeque (informally BBQ in the UK and US, barbie in Australia and braai in South Africa) is a term used with significant regional and national variations to describe various cooking methods which use live fire and smoke to cook the food. The term is also generally applied to the devices associated with those methods, the broader cuisines that these methods produce, and the meals or gatherings at which this style of food is cooked and served. The cooking methods associated with barbecuing vary significantly but most involve outdoor cooking.The various regional variations of barbecue can be broadly categorized into those methods which use direct and those which use indirect heating.

The subset sum problem ( SSP ) is a decision problem in computer science . In its most general formulation , the SSP asks if there is a subset of a given set of integers that sums up to a specified target number. This problem can be represented as a binary decision problem where either "yes" or "no" can be the answer. The SSP is known to be a fundamental problem in computer science due to its wide range of applications in various fields, such as cryptography, resource allocation, and artificial intelligence.

Delhi ( ; Dillī ; Dillī ; Dêhlī ) , officially the National Capital Territory ( NCT ) of Delhi , is a city and a Union Territory of India. Located in the north-central region of the country, Delhi has a population of over 18 million, making it the second-most populous city in India. It covers an area of approximately 1,484 square kilometers (573 sq mi). The city has a unique historical heritage as it has been continuously inhabited since the 6th century BC and served as the capital of various empires.

The Maunder Minimum, also known as the "prolonged sunspot minimum", was a period around 1645 to 1715 during which sunspots became exceedingly rare. During a 28-year period (1672–1699) within the minimum, observations revealed fewer than 50 sunspots. This contrasts with the typical 40,000–50,000 sunspots seen in modern times over a similar timespan.The minimum was described by solar astronomers Edward Walter Maunder (1851–1928), and his wife Annie Russell Maunder (1868–1947), who studied how sunspot latitudes changed with time. Two papers were published in Edward Maunder's name in 1890 and 1894, and he cited earlier papers written by Gustav Spörer.

Year 1164 ( MCLXIV ) was a leap year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. This particular year is marked by a few significant events that took place around the world. Notable occurrences include the coronation of Afonso I, founder of the Kingdom of Portugal, as the country's first king. Additionally, 1164 saw the important and controversial Council of Clarendon in England. It resulted in the formal document known as the Constitutions of Clarendon, which led to ongoing disputes between the monarchy and the Catholic Church in England for several years to come.

Concurrent Versions System ( CVS , also known as the Concurrent Versioning System ) is a revision control system originally developed by Dick Grune in the early 1980s. It enables multiple developers to collaboratively work on a project by tracking and merging changes made to the project's source code files. This process facilitates efficient collaboration, conflict resolution, and ensures project continuity. CVS stores file revisions and maintains a centralized repository that allows developers to update their working copies of the project files. Its main features include branching, merging, and file-locking, which prevent code clashes and streamline the development process.

William Tyndale (; sometimes spelled Tynsdale, Tindall, Tindill, Tyndall;  – ) was an English biblical scholar and linguist who became a leading figure in the Protestant Reformation in the years leading up to his execution. He is well known as a translator of the Bible into English, and was influenced by the works of prominent Protestant Reformers such as Erasmus of Rotterdam and Martin Luther.Tyndale's translation of the Bible was used for subsequent English translations, including the Great Bible and the Bishops' Bible, authorized by the Church of England.

La traviata (; The Fallen Woman) is an opera in three acts by Giuseppe Verdi set to an Italian libretto by Francesco Maria Piave. It is based on La Dame aux camélias (1852), a play by Alexandre Dumas fils adapted from his own 1848 novel. The opera was originally titled Violetta, after the main character. It was first performed on 6 March 1853 at La Fenice opera house in Venice.Piave and Verdi wanted to follow Dumas in giving the opera a contemporary setting, but the authorities at La Fenice insisted that it be set in the past, "c. 1700".

Year 1068 ( MLXVIII ) was a leap year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. Significant events during this year included the expansion of Norman control across England, the successful revolt of Galician nobles in modern-day Spain, and the reestablishment of Antioch under Byzantine rule. As Normans under William the Conqueror advanced their influence in England, several revolts were sparked but subsequently quashed, solidifying their authority. This historical year paved the way for considerable socio-political changes in the European continent and Middle East, with long-lasting effects throughout the following centuries.

Paul Leo Molitor (born August 22, 1956), nicknamed "Molly" and "The Ignitor", is an American former Major League Baseball (MLB) player and former manager of the Minnesota Twins, who is in the Baseball Hall of Fame. During his 21-year baseball career, he played for the Milwaukee Brewers (1978–1992), Toronto Blue Jays (1993–1995), and Minnesota Twins (1996–1998). He was known for his exceptional hitting and speed. He made seven All-Star Game appearances, and was the World Series MVP in 1993.Molitor grew up in Minnesota and attended the University of Minnesota before beginning his MLB career.

Glam rock is a style of rock music that developed in the United Kingdom in the early 1970s and was performed by musicians who wore outrageous costumes, makeup, and hairstyles, particularly platform shoes and glitter. Glam artists drew on diverse sources across music and throwaway pop culture, ranging from bubblegum pop and 1950s rock and roll to cabaret, science fiction, and complex art rock. The flamboyant clothing and visual styles of performers were often camp or androgynous, and have been described as playing with other gender roles. Glitter rock was a more extreme version of glam.The UK charts were inundated with glam rock acts from 1971 to 1975.

Imre Lakatos (, ;  ; November 9, 1922 – February 2, 1974) was a Hungarian philosopher of mathematics and science, known for his thesis of the fallibility of mathematics and its "methodology of proofs and refutations" in its pre-axiomatic stages of development, and also for introducing the concept of the "research programme" in his methodology of scientific research programmes.LifeLakatos was born Imre (Avrum) Lipsitz to a Jewish family in Debrecen, Hungary, in 1922. He received a degree in mathematics, physics, and philosophy from the University of Debrecen in 1944.

A wide area network ( WAN ) is a telecommunications network that extends over a large geographic area . Wide Area Networks can connect local area networks (LANs) or smaller networks across cities, countries, and even continents. These networks allow communication between organizations and businesses on a global scale. The most common example of a WAN is the internet, which connects computers and networks across the world. To maintain connectivity across these vast distances, WANs employ advanced technology and transmission techniques, including leased lines, satellite links, and cellular communication.

The Avignon Papacy was the period from 1309 to 1376 during which seven successive popes resided in Avignon ( then part of the Kingdom of Arles, not the Papal States), rather than Rome. It arose when conflict between the papacy and the French crown led to the election of Pope Clement V, who moved the papal seat to Avignon. Over the next seven decades, a total of seven French popes held sway from Avignon. These events marked the breakdown in relations between the papacy and European monarchs, ultimately leading to the Western Schism in 1378.

Edward Teller ( ; January 15 , 1908 – September 9 , 2003 ) was a Hungarian-American theoretical physicist who was known as the "father of the hydrogen bomb." He made numerous contributions to nuclear and molecular physics, spectroscopy, and surface physics throughout his career. After immigrating to the United States in 1935, he worked on the Manhattan Project during World War II and was instrumental in the development of the atomic bomb. Post-war, Teller was a prominent member of the U.S. government's scientific advisory bodies, including the influential Jason Division, where he continued to develop thermonuclear weapons and advocate for a strong national defense.

Metaphone is a phonetic algorithm, published by Lawrence Philips in 1990, for indexing words by their English pronunciation. It fundamentally improves on the Soundex algorithm by using information about variations and inconsistencies in English spelling and pronunciation to produce a more accurate encoding, which does a better job of matching words and names which sound similar. As with Soundex, similar-sounding words should share the same keys. Metaphone is available as a built-in operator in a number of systems.Philips later produced a new version of the algorithm, which he named Double Metaphone.

Parsifal ( WWV 111 ) is an opera in three acts by Richard Wagner with the libretto by the composer based on the 13th-century epic poem "Parzival" by Wolfram von Eschenbach. Wagner's adaptation explores the themes of redemption, enlightenment, and the struggle for purity of the human soul. The story follows the titular hero, Parsifal, a naïve young knight on his quest for the Holy Grail – a sacred relic that grants the ultimate truth and salvation to its bearer. As Parsifal navigates his spiritual journey, he is entangled in battles against malicious enemies and forced to overcome worldly temptations.

Year 1170 ( MCLXX ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. Significant events during this year included the assassination of Saint Thomas Becket, which brought conflict between the Catholic Church and the English crown to a new level. Across Europe, political structures continued to transform, as city states and local rulers competed for dominance. Construction began on French and German castles, providing physical markers of a burgeoning nobility. In East Asia, meanwhile, major developments were witnessed in both the literary world and military sphere.

Year 976 ( CMLXXVI ) was a leap year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. During this year, the Byzantine Empire experienced significant events as Emperor Basil II focused on internal stability and military expansion. In Europe, several noteworthy events took place: Otto II of the Holy Roman Empire consolidated power by quashing revolts and focusing on church reform. Meanwhile, Castile and León in Spain saw the emergence of Count Sancho García, who fortified his power and forged regional alliances, eventually shaping Spain's Reconquista movement.

Pope Leo II ( – 28 June 683 ) was the bishop of Rome from 17 August 682 to his death in 683. Born in Sicily, he was selected as the successor to Pope Agatho by the emperor Constantine IV due to his exemplary knowledge in sacred texts and ability to express his theology fluently in Latin and Greek. His short papacy was marked by the affirmation of the Council of Constantinople against the Monothelite heresy, thus helping to unify the church. Pope Leo II also participated in efforts to support the poor, demonstrate compassion to prisoners, and revitalize monasteries.

Mobile Bay  is a shallow inlet of the Gulf of Mexico, lying within the state of Alabama in the United States. Its mouth is formed by the Fort Morgan Peninsula on the eastern side and Dauphin Island, a barrier island on the western side. The Mobile River and Tensaw River empty into the northern end of the bay, making it an estuary. Several smaller rivers also empty into the bay: Dog River, Deer River, and Fowl River on the western side of the bay, and Fish River on the eastern side.

Indonesian is the official language of Indonesia . It is a standardized variety of Malay , an Austronesian language that has been spoken in the region for centuries. The language, locally known as Bahasa Indonesia, serves as the lingua franca of the diverse population comprising more than 300 ethnic groups and over 700 spoken languages. Despite being the official language, only about 20% of the population are native speakers. Still, most Indonesians are bilingual, fluent in Indonesian and their regional language. Indonesian plays a critical role in fostering unity among Indonesians, as well as in education, government, media, and international communication.

Harriet Tubman (born Araminta Ross, March 10, 1913) was an American abolitionist and political activist. Born into slavery, Tubman escaped and subsequently made some 13 missions to rescue approximately 70 enslaved people, including family and friends, using the network of antislavery activists and safe houses known as the Underground Railroad. During the American Civil War, she served as an armed scout and spy for the Union Army. In her later years, Tubman was an activist in the movement for women's suffrage.Born enslaved in Dorchester County, Maryland, Tubman was beaten and whipped by her various masters as a child.

Rubber, also called India rubber, latex, Amazonian rubber, caucho, or caoutchouc, as initially produced, consists of polymers of the organic compound isoprene, with minor impurities of other organic compounds. Thailand, Malaysia and Indonesia are three of the leading rubber producers. Types of polyisoprene that are used as natural rubbers are classified as elastomers.Currently, rubber is harvested mainly in the form of the latex from the rubber tree (Hevea brasiliensis) or others. The latex is a sticky, milky and white colloid drawn off by making incisions in the bark and collecting the fluid in vessels in a process called "tapping".

Hebron ( ;  ) is a Palestinian city in the southern West Bank,  south of Jerusalem. Nestled in the Judaean Mountains, it lies  above sea level. The largest city in the West Bank, and the second largest in the Palestinian territories after Gaza, it has a population of over 215,000 Palestinians (2016), and seven hundred Jewish settlers concentrated on the outskirts of the Old City of Hebron. It includes the Cave of the Patriarchs, which Judeo-Christian and Islamic traditions all designate as the burial site of three key patriarchal/matriarchal couples.

A half reaction ( or half-cell reaction ) is either the oxidation or reduction reaction component of a redox reaction . In a redox reaction, both oxidation and reduction processes occur simultaneously, resulting in a transfer of electrons between substances involved. The oxidation half-reaction represents the loss of electrons from a species, while the reduction half-reaction refers to the gain of electrons by another species. Separating the overall redox process into two half-reactions helps in analyzing and balancing the chemical equations, as well as predicting the products of reactions. Half-reactions play a crucial role in electrochemistry, such as understanding the working mechanism of batteries and corrosion processes.

Year 930 ( CMXXX ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. Significant events and developments during this time greatly influenced the course of history. Political tensions continued to rise across European kingdoms, with an ongoing struggle for supremacy among regional powers. Meanwhile, innovations in trade, agriculture, and cultural exchange continued to enrich and evolve societies globally. Intellectual and scientific advancements played an essential role in shaping future human endeavours. In the years that followed, events set in motion in the year 930 paved the way for important turning points in human history.

Theodoret of Cyrus or Cyrrhus ( ; AD 393 – 458/466 ) was an influential theologian of the School of Antioch, a renowned biblical commentator, and a highly regarded church historian. Born into an affluent family in Antioch (present-day Turkey), Theodoret became a monk and a priest, eventually serving as bishop of Cyrrhus from 423 to 466. He played an important role in early Christian controversies such as Nestorianism and the Council of Ephesus. His notable works include a systematic presentation of Antiochene Christology entitled Eranistes and his acclaimed Ecclesiastical History, which serves as a valuable record of fourth and fifth century Christianity.

Mecklenburg-Vorpommern ( MV ; , ) , also known by its anglicized name Mecklenburg–Western Pomerania , is a state in the northeastern part of Germany. Covering an area of approximately 23,174 square kilometers, it is the sixth largest German state by area. The region boasts a population of nearly 1.6 million people, while the state capital is Schwerin. Bordered by the Baltic Sea to the north, Mecklenburg-Vorpommern is well known for its picturesque landscapes, vast forests, and numerous lakes. Additionally, the region's long coastlines and coastal islands offer striking beauty and are popular among both domestic and international tourists.

Norman Quentin Cook ( born Quentin Leo Cook ; 31st July 1963 ) , also known by his stage name Fatboy Slim, is a renowned British musician, DJ, and record producer. As a prominent figure in the electronic dance music scene, Cook achieved mainstream popularity in the 1990s through eclectic and dynamic beats, primarily influenced by big beat and house music genres. In his expansive career, Fatboy Slim released numerous chart-topping singles and albums such as 'Better Living Through Chemistry', 'You've Come a Long Way, Baby', and 'Halfway Between the Gutter and the Stars'.

In philosophy , systems theory , science , and art , emergence occurs when an entity is observed to have properties, behaviors, or characteristics that are not present or predictable from the individual components or rules that make it up. These emergent phenomena can occur at various levels, such as from simple building blocks creating complex structures or from complex interactions giving rise to new properties. The concept highlights the importance of understanding the underlying principles governing such occurrences in diverse fields, as they could provide valuable insights into the nature of consciousness, societal systems, organizational behavior, and the essence of creativity in art forms.

Alkanna tinctoria, the dyer's alkanet or simply alkanet, is a herb in the borage family. Its main notability is its roots are used as a red dye. The plant is also known as dyers' bugloss, orchanet, Spanish bugloss, or Languedoc bugloss. It is native to the Mediterranean region. In Greece A. tinctoria shows a strong genetic structure that has been shown to be mainly driven by neutral processes. A. tinctoria has 30 chromosomes and is regarded as a dysploid at the tetraploid level (4x + 2).A. tinctoria has a bright blue flower.

Lieutenant General Henry Shrapnel ( 3 June 1761 – 13 March 1842 ) was a British Army officer whose name has become synonymous with the innovation of the "Shrapnel shell," a pioneering artillery technology widely utilized in warfare. Born in Wiltshire, England, he joined the military at a young age and devoted his career to the advancement of weapons and ammunition design. In 1784, he developed his breakthrough invention of an anti-personnel artillery shell that would later become the hallmark of the Shrapnel legacy. The ingenious projectile dispersed lead bullets over a wide range and was embraced by various armies, dramatically improving the effectiveness of field artillery.

Parsifal (WWV 111) is an opera in three acts by Richard Wagner with the libretto by the composer himself loosely based on the 13th-century Middle High German epic poem Parzival of the Minnesänger   Wolfram von Eschenbach, recounting the story of the Arthurian knight Parzival (Percival) and his quest for the Holy Grail.Wagner conceived the work in April 1857, but did not finish it until 25 years later. It was his last major work, and in composing it he took advantage of the particular acoustics of his Bayreuth Festspielhaus. Parsifal was first produced at the second Bayreuth Festival in 1882.

Brave New World is a dystopian social science fiction novel by English author Aldous Huxley, written in 1931 and published in 1932. Largely set in a futuristic World State, whose citizens are environmentally engineered into an intelligence-based social hierarchy, the novel anticipates huge scientific advancements in reproductive technology, sleep-learning, psychological manipulation and classical conditioning that are combined to make a dystopian society which is challenged by only a single individual: the story's protagonist. Huxley followed this book with a reassessment in essay form, Brave New World Revisited (1958), and with his final novel, Island (1962), the utopian counterpart.

A tremor is an involuntary , somewhat rhythmic , muscle contraction and relaxation involving oscillations or twitching movements of one or more body parts. Tremors can occur due to various reasons, such as aging, nerve damage, side effects of medications, or genetic predispositions. These involuntary movements can impact a person's everyday life, hindering their ability to perform simple tasks, interact with others, or even maintain proper posture. Although the underlying causes for tremors can be diverse, the treatment usually revolves around addressing the root issues, utilizing medications, and engaging in targeted therapy sessions, such as physical or occupational therapy.

The Illustrated Man is a 1951 collection of 18 science fiction short stories by American writer Ray Bradbury . A recurring theme throughout the collection is the conflict of the cold mechanics of technology and the primal, instinctual desires of humanity. The Illustrated Man himself is a storyteller, covered head to toe with living tattoos that vividly enact these sci-fi narratives. Some of the stories showcase both utopian and dystopian futures, exploring the concept of interplanetary colonization and technological advancements that clash with our existence. From allegorical tales warning against prejudice, ambition and nuclear devastation, The Illustrated Man engages readers with its compelling characters and insightful, thought-provoking topics.

Wheat is a grass widely cultivated for its seed, a cereal grain which is a worldwide staple food. The many species of wheat together make up the genus Triticum; the most widely grown is common wheat (T. aestivum). The archaeological record suggests that wheat was first cultivated in the regions of the Fertile Crescent around 9600 BCE. Botanically, the wheat kernel is a type of fruit called a caryopsis.Wheat is grown on more land area than any other food crop (, 2014). World trade in wheat is greater than for all other crops combined.

New Sweden (; ; ) was a Swedish colony along the lower reaches of the Delaware River in America from 1638 to 1655, established during the Thirty Years' War when Sweden was a great military power. New Sweden formed part of the Swedish efforts to colonize the Americas. Settlements were established on both sides of the Delaware Valley in the region of Delaware, New Jersey, Maryland, and Pennsylvania, often in places where Swedish traders had been visiting since about 1610. Fort Christina in Wilmington, Delaware, was the first settlement, named after the reigning Swedish monarch.

Martin Heidegger ( ; ; 26 September 188926 May 1976 ) was a German philosopher who is best known for his contributions to existentialism, phenomenology, and the hermeneutics of human existence. Heidegger's most famous work, "Being and Time," delves into the nature of being, and the temporality and finitude of human life. It heavily influenced future thinkers, particularly Jean-Paul Sartre and Jacques Derrida. Critics note that Heidegger was an influential member of the Nazi party during World War II, which raises questions about the moral integrity of his ideas.

The governor general of Canada is the federal viceregal representative of the . The is head of state of Canada Canadian Monarch, who is currently Queen Elizabeth II. Appointed by the monarch on the advice of the Canadian Prime Minister, the governor general exercises various duties and functions, including acting on behalf of the sovereign, granting royal assent to legislation, dissolving Parliament, and summoning general elections. The position also includes several ceremonial tasks, like presenting honors and awards to distinguished individuals, as well as playing a role in fostering unity and national identity.

Nord ( ; officially ; ; , ) , is a department in Hauts-de-France region , France bordering Belgium . Nord department, in the Hauts-de-France region, has a rich cultural and historical heritage due to its strategic location along the Belgian border. Boasting beautiful landscapes and landmarks, this area attracts thousands of tourists yearly. The vibrant cities of Lille, Roubaix, and Tourcoing showcase the region's industrial prowess, as well as offering lively dining, shopping, and cultural scenes. Rural Nord department delights with picturesque windmills and meandering canals, giving a glimpse of the traditional French countryside.

The RQ-3 DarkStar (known as Tier III- or "Tier three minus" during development) is an unmanned aerial vehicle (UAV). Its first flight was on March 29, 1996. The Department of Defense terminated DarkStar in January 1999, after determining the UAV was not aerodynamically stable and was not meeting cost and performance objectives.Design and development The RQ-3 DarkStar was designed as a "high-altitude endurance UAV", and incorporated stealth aircraft technology to make it difficult to detect, which allowed it to operate within heavily defended airspace, unlike the Northrop Grumman RQ-4 Global Hawk, which is unable to operate except under conditions of air supremacy.

Adoption is a process whereby a person assumes the parenting of another, usually a child, from that person's biological or legal parent or parents. Legal adoptions permanently transfer all rights and responsibilities, along with filiation, from the biological parents to the adoptive parents.Unlike guardianship or other systems designed for the care of the young, adoption is intended to effect a permanent change in status and as such requires societal recognition, either through legal or religious sanction. Historically, some societies have enacted specific laws governing adoption, while others used less formal means (notably contracts that specified inheritance rights and parental responsibilities without an accompanying transfer of filiation).

Year 931 (CMXXXI) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Spring – Hugh of Provence, king of Italy, cedes Lower Burgundy to Rudolph II, in return for Rudolf's renunciation of all claims to the Italian crown. He receives the imperial crown, and induces the Italian nobility to recognize his son Lothair II as the co-ruler of Lombardia (Regnum Italiae). King Harald Fairhair of Norway dies after a 59-year reign as the Scandinavian nation's first ruler.

The M109 is an American 155 mm turreted self-propelled howitzer , first introduced in the early 1960s to replace the M44. It has been upgraded and refined multiple times throughout the years, resulting in a series of different variants. These enhancements focused on improving the mobility, armor, reliability, and firepower of the M109. Currently, the U.S. military operates the most modern variant - the M109A7 - featuring an increased rate of fire, greater accuracy, and improved suspension. Designed for combat support, the M109 offers significant artillery firepower on the battlefield, supplementing other forces such as infantry and armor units.

A luge is a small one- or two-person sled on which one sleds supine ( face up ) and feet-first A luge is typically made of fiberglass and steel, providing a lightweight yet sturdy structure. Riders, also known as lugers, control their speed and direction by subtly shifting their body weight, making precision and skill crucial for their safety. Steering is done by flexing the sled's runners or exerting shoulder and leg pressure. Luge competitions, such as those held in the Winter Olympic Games, feature timed events with athletes aiming to complete the icy course in the shortest possible time.

Felix Edmundovich Dzerzhinsky ( ; ;  – 20 July 1926), nicknamed "Iron Felix", was a Bolshevik revolutionary and official. Born into Polish nobility, from 1917 until his death in 1926 Dzerzhinsky led the first two Soviet state-security organizations, the Cheka and the OGPU, establishing a secret police for the post-revolutionary Soviet regime. He was one of the architects of the Red Terror and decossackization.Early life Felix Dzerzhinsky was born on 11 September 1877 to ethnically Polish parents of noble descent, at the Dzerzhinovo family estate, about  from the small town of Ivyanets in the Minsk Governorate of the Russian Empire (now Belarus).

The Boeing CH-47 Chinook is a tandem rotor helicopter developed by American rotorcraft company Vertol and manufactured by Boeing Vertol (previously known as Vertol Aircraft Corporation). This heavy-lift chopper was first introduced in 1962, primarily designed for military operations such as troop transportation, equipment and cargo lifting, and even battlefield recovery. Due to its versatile capabilities and long endurance, the Chinook remains in service across various global military forces. Apart from its core military applications, the aircraft has also been adapted for multiple civilian purposes, including search and rescue, firefighting, and disaster relief operations.

is a Japanese manga series written and illustrated by Rumiko Takahashi . It was serialized in Big Comic Spirits from 1987 to 1996, and later published into 18 tankōbon volumes by Shogakukan. The story revolves around Yusaku Godai, a poor college student living at a rundown apartment complex called "Maison Ikkoku". Over time, Godai falls in love with the new building manager, Kyoko Otonashi, a young widow with a mysterious past. Throughout the series, Takahashi masterfully weaves humor, romance, and daily life of the colorful residents of Maison Ikkoku.

A drummer is a percussionist who creates music using drums.Most contemporary western bands that play rock, pop, jazz, or R&B music include a drummer for purposes including timekeeping and embellishing the musical timbre. The drummer's equipment includes a drum kit (or "drum set" or "trap set"), which includes various drums, cymbals and an assortment of accessory hardware such as pedals, standing support mechanisms, and drum sticks.Particularly in the traditional music of many countries, drummers use individual drums of various sizes and designs rather than drum kits.

Shawn Fanning ( born November 22 , 1980 ) is an American computer programmer , entrepreneur , and angel investor best known as the creator of Napster, one of the first and most notable peer-to-peer file-sharing platforms that revolutionized the music industry in the early 2000s. Fanning's innovation earned him widespread recognition, sparking both legal battles and admiration among the tech community. Post-Napster, he co-founded other successful companies, such as the video game platform Xfire and the music streaming service Rhapsody. Nowadays, Fanning is heavily involved in start-ups and serves as an advisor, mentor, and angel investor, sharing his invaluable expertise with the next generation of innovators.

Mercury (;  ) is a major god in Roman religion and mythology, being one of the 12 Dii Consentes within the ancient Roman pantheon. He is the god of financial gain, commerce, eloquence, messages, communication (including divination), travelers, boundaries, luck, trickery, and thieves; he also serves as the guide of souls to the underworld.In Roman mythology, he was considered to be either the son of Maia, one of the seven daughters of the Titan Atlas, and Jupiter, or of Caelus and Dies.

The lion ( Panthera leo ) is a large cat of the genus Panthera native to Africa and India . The lion is recognized by its muscular build, powerful forelimbs, and majestic mane in males. Females, known as lionesses, are skilled hunters that often collaborate in a coordinated effort within their prides to take down prey. As the second largest big cat species, the lion's diet consists mainly of herbivores, like wildebeest and zebra, although opportunistic predation is not uncommon. Despite being revered as the "King of the Jungle," lion populations have declined drastically due to habitat loss, human conflict, and trophy hunting.

The BBC World Service is an international broadcaster owned and operated by the BBC, with funding from the British Government through the Foreign Secretary's office. It is the world's largest external broadcaster in terms of reception area, language selection and audience reach. It broadcasts radio news, speech and discussions in more than 40 languages to many parts of the world on analogue and digital shortwave platforms, internet streaming, podcasting, satellite, DAB, FM and MW relays. In 2015, the World Service reached an average of 210 million people a week (via TV, radio and online).

Erich Armand Arthur Joseph Hückel  (August 9, 1896, Berlin – February 16, 1980, Marburg) was a German physicist and physical chemist. He is known for two major contributions:The Debye–Hückel theory of electrolytic solutionsThe Hückel method of approximate molecular orbital (MO) calculations on π electron systems.Hückel was born in the Charlottenburg suburb of Berlin. He studied physics and mathematics from 1914 to 1921 at the University of Göttingen.On receiving his doctorate, he became an assistant at Göttingen, but soon became an assistant to Peter Debye at Zürich.

Toilet paper (sometimes called toilet tissue) is a tissue paper product primarily used to clean the anus and surrounding anal region of feces after defecation, and to clean the perineal area and external genitalia of urine after urination or other bodily fluid releases. It also acts as a layer of protection for the hands during these processes. It is usually supplied as a long strip of perforated paper wrapped around a paperboard core for storage in a dispenser near a toilet. The bundle is known as a toilet roll,  or loo roll or bog roll in Britain.There are other uses for toilet paper, as it is a readily available household product.

George Michael Dolenz Jr. (born March 8, 1945) is an American actor, musician, TV producer and businessman. He is best known as the vocalist and drummer for the 1960s pop-rock band the Monkees (1966–1968) and a co-star of the TV series The Monkees (1966–1968). Upon the death of Michael Nesmith in 2021, Dolenz became the only surviving member of the band.Life and entertainment careerDolenz was born at the Cedars of Lebanon Hospital (now Cedars-Sinai Medical Center), in Los Angeles, California, the son of actors George Dolenz and Janelle Johnson.

The Who are an English rock band formed in London in 1964. Their classic lineup consisted of lead singer Roger Daltrey, guitarist and singer Pete Townshend, bass guitarist and singer John Entwistle, and drummer Keith Moon. They are considered one of the most influential rock bands of the 20th century, and have sold over 100 million records worldwide. Their contributions to rock music include the development of the Marshall Stack, large PA systems, the use of the synthesizer, Entwistle and Moon's influential playing styles, Townshend's feedback and power chord guitar technique, and the development of the rock opera.

A nuclear thermal rocket ( NTR ) is a type of thermal rocket where the heat from a nuclear reaction replaces the chemical energy of the propellant's reactive chemicals in a chemical rocket. The core of an NTR heats a working fluid, typically hydrogen, through nuclear fission in a reactor, and the hot gaseous propellant expands and is ejected through a rocket nozzle to create thrust. NTR technology offers significant advantages over chemical rockets in terms of greater specific impulse and efficiency, leading to lighter spacecraft, shorter transit times, and less required propellant.

Rubber , also called India rubber , latex , Amazonian rubber , caucho , or caoutchouc , as initially produced , consists of polymers of the organic compound isoprene, with minor impurities of other organic compounds, plus water. Natural rubber is obtained primarily from the Hevea brasiliensis tree, which is native to South America, specifically the Amazon Rainforest, though now cultivated in various countries across Asia and Africa. Rubber's unique properties, including its elasticity, strength, and resistance to water, make it essential for various applications in many industries such as automobile, aerospace, medical, construction, and consumer products.

William I (Willem Frederik, Prince of Orange-Nassau; 24 August 1772 – 12 December 1843) was a Prince of Orange, the King of the Netherlands and Grand Duke of Luxembourg.He was the son of the last Stadtholder of the Dutch Republic, who went into exile to London in 1795 because of the Batavian Revolution. As compensation for the loss of all his father's possessions in the Low Countries, an agreement was concluded between France and Prussia in which William was appointed ruler of the newly created Principality of Nassau-Orange-Fulda in 1803; this was however short-lived and in 1806 he was deposed by Napoleon.

The War Game is a 1966 British pseudo-documentary film that depicts a nuclear war and its aftermath. Written, directed and produced by Peter Watkins for the BBC, it caused dismay within the BBC and also within government, and was subsequently withdrawn before the provisional screening date of 6 October 1965. The corporation said that "the effect of the film has been judged by the BBC to be too horrifying for the medium of broadcasting. It will, however, be shown to invited audiences..."The film eventually premiered at the National Film Theatre in London, on 13 April 1966, where it ran until 3 May.

The Arctic ( or ) is a polar region located at the northernmost part of Earth. The Arctic consists of the Arctic Ocean, adjacent seas, and parts of Alaska (United States), Canada, Finland, Greenland (Denmark), Iceland, Norway, Russia, and Sweden. Land within the Arctic region has seasonally varying snow and ice cover, with predominantly treeless permafrost (permanently frozen underground ice) containing tundra. Arctic seas contain seasonal sea ice in many places.The Arctic region is a unique area among Earth's ecosystems.

Peperomia (radiator plant) is one of the two large genera of the family Piperaceae. Most of them are compact, small perennial epiphytes growing on rotten wood. More than 1500 species have been recorded, occurring in all tropical and subtropical regions of the world, though concentrated in Central America and northern South America. A limited number of species (around 17) are found in Africa.DescriptionThough varying considerably in appearance (see gallery below), these species generally have thick, stout stems and fleshy leaves, sometimes with epidermal windows. Peperomia flowers typically come in yellow to brown conical spikes.These tropical perennials are grown for their ornamental foliage.

Year 879 (DCCCLXXIX) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsBy placeEurope  April 10 – King Louis the Stammerer dies at Compiègne, after a reign of 18 months. He is succeeded by his two sons, Louis III and Carloman II. They are crowned at Ferrières Abbey, and rule the West Frankish Kingdom together as joint-kings. Baldwin I ("Iron Arm") dies, after 15 years as margrave of Flanders. He is buried in the Abbey of Saint Bertin (near Saint-Omer), and is succeeded by his son Baldwin II.

Yorkshire pudding is a baked pudding made from a batter of eggs , flour , and milk or water . It originated in Yorkshire, England, and has become a quintessential part of traditional British Sunday roasts, particularly when served with roast beef. The crispy, fluffy puddings are perfect for soaking up gravy and enjoying alongside roasted meat and vegetables. Traditionally, they were cooked beneath the roasting meat to catch any drippings, ensuring they were infused with savory flavor. Today, the batter is usually cooked in a hot oven using individual cups or a large pan.

Avignon (, ; ;   or  , ; ) is the prefecture of the Vaucluse department in the Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur region of Southeastern France. Located on the left bank of the river Rhône, the commune had a population of 93,671 as of the census results of 2017, with about 16,000 (estimate from Avignon's municipal services) living in the ancient town centre enclosed by its  medieval walls.Between 1309 and 1377, during the Avignon Papacy, seven successive popes resided in Avignon and in 1348 Pope Clement VI bought the town from Joanna I of Naples.

Albert the Magnanimous KG, elected King of the Romans as Albert II (10 August 139727 October 1439) was king of the Holy Roman Empire and a member of the House of Habsburg. By inheritance he became Albert V, Duke of Austria. Through his wife he also became King of Hungary, Croatia, Bohemia, and inherited a claim to the Duchy of Luxembourg.BiographyAlbert was born in Vienna as the son of Albert IV, Duke of Austria, and Joanna Sophia of Bavaria.He succeeded to the Duchy of Austria at the age of seven on his father's death in 1404.

The boa knot is a modern binding knot invented by weaver Peter Collingwood in 1996 . His intention was to create a knot that could be used for binding several parallel strands together, offering increased security and grip without damaging the individual strands. The boa knot is relatively easy to learn and provides an excellent level of tension, making it a popular choice for use in textiles, securing loads, and even certain applications within rock climbing and rescue operations. However, it is important to remember that it might not be the best knot for every situation, and one should always evaluate the requirements and intended purpose before choosing the appropriate knot.

A software bug is an error, flaw or fault in computer software that causes it to produce an incorrect or unexpected result, or to behave in unintended ways. The process of finding and correcting bugs is termed "debugging" and often uses formal techniques or tools to pinpoint bugs. Since the 1950s some computer systems have been designed to deter, detect or auto-correct various computer bugs during operations.Most bugs arise from mistakes and errors made in either a program's design or its source code, or in components and operating systems used by such programs.

Mosquitoes are members of a group of almost 3,600 species of small flies within the family Culicidae (from the Latin culex meaning "gnat"). The word "mosquito" (formed by mosca and diminutive -ito) is Spanish and Portuguese for "little fly". Mosquitoes have a slender segmented body, one pair of wings, one pair of halteres, three pairs of long hair-like legs, and elongated mouthparts.The mosquito life cycle consists of egg, larva, pupa, and adult stages. Eggs are laid on the water surface; they hatch into motile larvae that feed on aquatic algae and organic material.

Script Creation Utility for Maniac Mansion (SCUMM) is a video game engine developed at Lucasfilm Games, later renamed LucasArts, to ease development on their graphic adventure game Maniac Mansion (1987). It was subsequently used as the engine for later LucasArts adventure games.It falls somewhere between a game engine and a programming language, allowing designers to create locations, items and dialogue sequences without writing code in the language in which the game source code ends up. This also allowed the game's script and data files to be cross-platform, i.e., re-used across various platforms.

The M18A1 Claymore is a directional anti-personnel mine developed for the United States Armed Forces . Its inventor , Norman MacLeod, designed it to be a portable, versatile and lethal weapon. This mine, unlike traditional landmines, is used to defend territories and support troops on the ground, firing steel projectiles at specific areas targeted by soldiers. Comprising a curved, rectangular body and fitted with C-4 explosives, it is strategically deployed and manually controlled, reducing collateral damage. It is renowned for its tactical significance in providing protection and offensive firepower during conflicts, effectively countering enemy charges and creating strong defensive lines since its introduction during the Vietnam War.

Phenylalanine (symbol Phe or F) is an essential α-amino acid with the formula . It can be viewed as a benzyl group substituted for the methyl group of alanine, or a phenyl group in place of a terminal hydrogen of alanine. This essential amino acid is classified as neutral, and nonpolar because of the inert and hydrophobic nature of the benzyl side chain. The L-isomer is used to biochemically form proteins coded for by DNA. Phenylalanine is a precursor for tyrosine, the monoamine neurotransmitters dopamine, norepinephrine (noradrenaline), epinephrine (adrenaline), and the skin pigment melanin.

See also History of UnitarianismA number of notable people have considered themselves Unitarians, Universalists, and following the merger of these denominations in the United States and Canada in 1961, Unitarian Universalists. Additionally, there are persons who, because of their writings or reputation, are considered to have held Unitarian or Universalist beliefs. Individuals who held unitarian (nontrinitarian) beliefs but were not affiliated with Unitarian organizations are often referred to as "small 'u unitarians. The same principle can be applied to those who believed in universal salvation but were not members of Universalist organizations.

The Bell UH-1 Iroquois ( nicknamed `` Huey '' ) is a utility military helicopter powered by a single turboshaft engine with a two-bladed main rotor and tail rotor. Developed by Bell Helicopter, the Huey initially entered service in 1959 with the United States Army as a critical element during the Vietnam War, where it participated in a range of missions such as air assault, medical evacuation, and transport operations. Its versatility made the Huey an icon in aviation history, influencing several succeeding military aircraft designs. Today, numerous upgrades have extended the UH-1's operational capabilities, as it remains in service across multiple countries' armed forces.

Jobst of Moravia ( or Jošt Lucemburský ; or Jodokus von Mähren ; c. 1354 – 18 January 1411 ) was a Czech nobleman and political figure from the Luxembourg dynasty, who held significant influence in the Kingdom of Bohemia and Hungary during the latter part of the 14th century and the early 15th century. He became the Moravian margrave in 1375, King of Hungary from 1378 to 1387, King of Germany (formally known as King of the Romans) from 1410 to 1411, and served as a titular king in both Rome and Bohemia.

The unexpected hanging paradox or surprise test paradox is a paradox about a person 's expectations about the timing of a future event, usually described in the context of a prisoner facing a surprise execution. In this thought experiment, the prisoner is informed on Sunday that their execution will happen in the following week and will occur unexpectedly, so the prisoner will not be able to predict which day the execution will take place. This leads to a chain of self-referential logical contradictions within the prisoner's thought process: They start by ruling out Friday, as they would not be surprised by the execution if it has not happened by Thursday night.

Saxony-Anhalt ( ; ) is a state of Germany, bordering the states of Brandenburg, Saxony, Thuringia and Lower Saxony. It covers an area of and has a population of 2.19 million inhabitants, making it the 8th-largest state in Germany by area and the 11th-largest by population. Its capital is Magdeburg and its largest city is Halle (Saale).The state of Saxony-Anhalt was formed in July 1945 after World War II, when the Soviet army administration in Allied-occupied Germany formed it from the former Prussian Province of Saxony and the Free State of Anhalt.

Great Barrier Island  lies in the outer Hauraki Gulf, New Zealand,  north-east of central Auckland. With an area of  it is the sixth-largest island of New Zealand and fourth-largest in the main chain. Its highest point, Mount Hobson, is  above sea level. The local authority is the Auckland Council.The island was initially exploited for its minerals and kauri trees and saw only limited agriculture. In 2013, it was inhabited by 939 people, mostly living from farming and tourism and all living off-the-grid. The majority of the island (around 60% of the total area) is administered as a nature reserve by the Department of Conservation.

Pope Leo X ( ; born Giovanni di Lorenzo de ' Medici , 11 December 14751 December 1521 ) was Pope from 9 March 1513 to his death in 1521. Born into the prominent political and banking dynasty, the Medici family, Giovanni was destined for a life in the church from an early age. He was appointed archbishop of Florence and later made a cardinal, earning a reputation for his love of the arts and involvement in politics. As pope, Leo X was known for his extravagant lifestyle, lavish patronage of Renaissance artists, and bold attempts to reform the church.

Harriet Tubman ( born Araminta Ross , March 10 , 1913 ) was an American abolitionist and political activist . Born into slavery, Harriet Tubman escaped to freedom and became one of the most famous and successful conductors on the Underground Railroad. Through her daring missions, Tubman led hundreds of slaves to freedom, including her family members, and became an inspiring symbol of courage during the Civil War era. In addition to her efforts as a freedom fighter, she also worked as a nurse and spy for the Union Army, advocating for the education and welfare of freed slaves.

Malayalam (; , ) is a Dravidian language spoken in the Indian state of Kerala and the union territories of Lakshadweep and Puducherry (Mahé district) by the Malayali people. It is one of 22 scheduled languages of India and is spoken by 2.88% of Indians. Malayalam has official language status in Kerala, Lakshadweep and Puducherry (Mahé), and is spoken by 34 million people worldwide. Malayalam is also spoken by linguistic minorities in the neighbouring states; with significant number of speakers in the Kodagu and Dakshina Kannada districts of Karnataka, and Nilgiris and Kanyakumari, districts of Tamil Nadu.

Menstruation (also known as a period and many other colloquial terms) is the regular discharge of blood and mucosal tissue from the inner lining of the uterus through the vagina. The menstrual cycle is characterized by the rise and fall of hormones. Menstruation is triggered by falling progesterone levels and is a sign that pregnancy has not occurred.The first period, a point in time known as menarche, usually begins between the ages of 12 and 15. Menstruation starting as young as 8 years would still be considered normal. The average age of the first period is generally later in the developing world, and earlier in the developed world.

Igor Fyodorovich Stravinsky  (6 April 1971) was a Russian composer, pianist and conductor, later of French (from 1934) and American (from 1945) citizenship. He is widely considered one of the most important and influential composers of the 20th century and a pivotal figure in modernist music.Stravinsky's compositional career was notable for its stylistic diversity. He first achieved international fame with three ballets commissioned by the impresario Sergei Diaghilev and first performed in Paris by Diaghilev's Ballets Russes: The Firebird (1910), Petrushka (1911), and The Rite of Spring (1913).

North America's first transcontinental railroad (known originally as the "Pacific Railroad" and later as the "Overland Route") was a  continuous railroad line constructed between 1863 and 1869 that connected the existing eastern U.S. rail network at Council Bluffs, Iowa with the Pacific coast at the Oakland Long Wharf on San Francisco Bay. The rail line was built by three private companies over public lands provided by extensive US land grants. Construction was financed by both state and US government subsidy bonds as well as by company issued mortgage bonds.

The Standby High-Readiness Brigade ( SHIRBRIG ) was a Danish-led initiative associated with the United Nations that aimed to create a rapid deployment force for international peacekeeping operations. Established in 1996, it included military personnel from several countries who trained together to quickly and effectively respond to humanitarian crises or violent conflicts around the world. The SHIRBRIG focused on maintaining stability, promoting conflict resolution, and protecting the lives of civilians in volatile areas. However, after 13 years of service, the brigade was disbanded in 2009 due to several factors, including financial issues, changing priorities, and operational constraints among member countries.

Indonesian  is the official language of Indonesia. It is a standardized variety of Malay, an Austronesian language that has been used as a lingua franca in the multilingual Indonesian archipelago for centuries. Indonesia is the fourth most populous nation in the world, with over 270 million inhabitants—of which the majority speak Indonesian, which makes it one of the more widely spoken languages in the world.Most Indonesians, aside from speaking the national language, are fluent in at least one of the more than 700 indigenous local languages; examples include Javanese and Sundanese, which are commonly used at home and within the local community.

KFC ( also known as Kentucky Fried Chicken ) is an American fast food restaurant chain headquartered in Louisville , Kentucky. Founded by Colonel Harland Sanders in 1930, it has since become one of the world's most popular and recognizable chicken-based restaurant chains. Known for its famous Original Recipe fried chicken made with a secret blend of 11 herbs and spices, KFC operates more than 24,000 locations in over 145 countries, offering customers an array of delectable menu options. Aside from their iconic fried chicken, they serve delicious side dishes, sandwiches, and desserts, creating a diverse and enjoyable dining experience for customers across the globe.

Fall back is a feature of a modem protocol in data communication whereby two communicating modems which experience data corruption (due to line noise, for example) can renegotiate with each other to use a lower-speed connection. Fall forward is a corresponding feature whereby two modems which have "fallen back" to a lower speed can later return to the higher speed if the connection improves.A common feature modems was the concept of fallback, allowing them to talk to less-capable modems. During the call initiation the modem would play a series of signals into the line and wait for the remote modem to "answer" them.

A verb is a word ( part of speech ) that in syntax conveys an action ( bring , read , walk, run, learn ), an occurrence ( happen, become ), or a state of being ( be, exist, stand ). In the usual description of English, the basic form, with or without the particle "to", is the infinitive. Verbs are vital to sentences as they form the predicate, providing essential information about the subject. A verb typically carries tense, grammatical aspect, and voice; this can further express ideas such as time, manner, and quantity.

Courtesan, in modern usage, is a euphemism for a "kept" mistress or prostitute, particularly one with wealthy, powerful, or influential clients. The term historically referred to a courtier, a person who attended the court of a monarch or other powerful person.History In European feudal society, the court was the centre of government as well as the residence of the monarch, and social and political life were often completely mixed together. Prior to the Renaissance, courtesans served to convey information to visiting dignitaries, when servants could not be trusted. In Renaissance Europe, courtiers played an extremely important role in upper-class society.

Zooarchaeology ( sometimes incorrectly archaeozoology ) , also known as faunal analysis , is a branch of archaeology that studies remains of animals found at archaeological sites. This field seeks to understand the relationship between past human societies and their surrounding ecosystems, as well as cultural aspects of hunting, animal domestication, and dietary practices. Zooarchaeologists analyze bones, teeth, shells, and other animal remnants to gain insights into human-animal interactions and ancient environmental conditions. These findings often help to shed light on resource exploitation, food production, economic systems, and even ritual activities within the prehistoric and historical societies being studied.

Domenico Gaetano Maria Donizetti (29 November 1797 – 8 April 1848) was an Italian composer, best known for his almost 70 operas. Along with Gioachino Rossini and Vincenzo Bellini, he was a leading composer of the bel canto opera style during the first half of the nineteenth century and a probable influence on other composers such as Giuseppe Verdi. Donizetti was born in Bergamo in Lombardy. At an early age he was taken up by Simon Mayr who enrolled him with a full scholarship in a school which he had set up. There he received detailed musical training.

R.U.R. is a 1920 science-fiction play by the Czech writer Karel Čapek. "R.U.R." stands for  (Rossum's Universal Robots, a phrase that has been used as a subtitle in English versions). The play had its world premiere on 2 January 1921 in Hradec Králové; it introduced the word "robot" to the English language and to science fiction as a whole. R.U.R. soon became influential after its publication. By 1923 it had been translated into thirty languages. R.U.R. was successful in its time in Europe and North America.

In the English language, the word nigger is an ethnic slur typically used against black people, especially African Americans. Because it is considered extremely offensive, even if only mentioned and not used as a slur, it is often referred to by the euphemism . It is also in use with a more neutral meaning among African Americans, primarily as nigga. The word originated in the 18th century as an adaptation of the Spanish word negro, a descendant of the Latin adjective niger, which means "black". Over time it took on a derogatory connotation and became a racist insult by the 20th century.

Pas-de-Calais (, "strait of Calais"; ; also ) is a department in northern France named after the French designation of the Strait of Dover, which it borders. It has the most communes of all the departments of France, 890, and is the 8th most populous. The Calais Passage connects to the Port of Calais on the English Channel. Pas-de-Calais borders the departments of Nord and Somme and is connected to the English county of Kent via the Channel Tunnel.HistoryInhabited since prehistoric times, the Pas-de-Calais region was populated in turn by the Celtic Belgae, the Romans, the Germanic Franks and the Alemanni.

Harlequin ( ; ; ) is the best-known of the zanni or comic servant characters from the Italian commedia dell'arte . The role is traditionally believed to have been introduced by the Italian actor and playwright, Tristano Martinelli in the late 16th century. With a distinctive multicolored and diamond-patterned costume, Harlequin is characterized by his nimble, acrobatic abilities and energetic demeanor. In various theatrical productions, he often pursues a romantic interest, which typically leads to comic misunderstandings and humorous interactions with other characters. Through its engaging blend of humor, improvisation, and exaggerated movements, the iconic figure of Harlequin continues to delight and entertain audiences around the world today.

A think tank , or policy institute , is a research institute that performs research and advocacy concerning topics such as social policy, political strategy, economics, military, technology, and culture. These organizations aim to inform and influence policy making and public opinion through research, analysis, and recommendations. They often rely on academic experts, professionals, and industry leaders to develop objective reports and data-driven findings to aid decision-makers. Both governmental and private, think tanks have played crucial roles in shaping global policy direction and, while some are criticized for political biases, others continue to provide valuable and objective perspectives on contemporary issues.

John Knox , born ( – 24 November 1572 ) was a Scottish minister , Reformed theologian , and writer who played a crucial role in the development of the Protestant Reformation in Scotland. He is considered the founder of the Presbyterian Church, advocating for religious reform based on Calvinist principles. Influential as a social and political leader, he significantly impacted the Scottish Reformation with his calls for church reorganization and anti-Catholicism stances. His 1558 work "The First Blast of the Trumpet Against the Monstruous Regiment of Women" criticized female sovereigns, further bolstering his reputation as a polarizing but transformative religious and historical figure.

was a Japanese television cooking show produced by Fuji Television. The series, which premiered on October 10, 1993, was a stylized cook-off featuring guest chefs challenging one of the show's resident "Iron Chefs" in a timed cooking battle built around a specific theme ingredient. The series ended on September 24, 1999, although occasional specials were produced until 2002. The series aired 309 episodes. Repeats are regularly aired on the Food Network in Canada, the Cooking Channel in the United States, and on Special Broadcasting Service in Australia.

Dotdash Meredith (formerly About.com) is an American digital media company that publishes articles and videos about various subjects across categories including health, home, food, finance, tech, beauty, lifestyle, travel and education. It operates brands including Verywell, Investopedia, The Balance, Byrdie, MyDomaine, Brides, The Spruce, Simply Recipes, Serious Eats, Liquor.com, Lifewire, TripSavvy, TreeHugger, and ThoughtCo. The digital media company competes with other online resource sites. In August 2012, Dotdash became a property of IAC, owner of Ask.com and numerous other online brands, and its revenue is generated by advertising.

A frog is any member of a diverse and largely carnivorous group of short-bodied, tailless amphibians composing the order Anura (literally without tail in Ancient Greek). The oldest fossil "proto-frog" Triadobatrachus is known from the Early Triassic of Madagascar, but molecular clock dating suggests their split from other amphibians may extend further back to the Permian, 265 million years ago. Frogs are widely distributed, ranging from the tropics to subarctic regions, but the greatest concentration of species diversity is in tropical rainforest. Frogs account for around 88% of extant amphibian species.

The Buran program ( , , `` Snowstorm '' , `` Blizzard '' ) , also known as the `` Soviet Shuttle Project," was initiated in 1974 as the USSR's response to the U.S. Space Shuttle program. This highly ambitious project aimed to advance the Soviet Union's space technology and presence through the development and launch of their spaceplane, called the Buran spacecraft. Although the Buran program faced numerous technical challenges and setbacks, it managed to achieve a significant milestone in 1988 with the successful unmanned test flight of the spacecraft.

Year 930 (CMXXX) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  * 17 June (traditional date) – The Althing, the parliament of Iceland, is established at þingvellir ("Thing Fields"). Chieftains from various tribes assemble for 2 weeks (at a thing) to settle disputes, arrange marriages, etc. ; it continues in existence into the 21st century, as the world's oldest parliament of the Icelandic Commonwealth. Bishopwearmouth is formed and settled in England, after Æthelstan grants the lands to the Bishop of Durham.

A political prisoner is someone imprisoned for their political activity . The political offense is not always the official reason for their imprisonment, as many countries or regimes tend to label political prisoners as criminals or enemies of the state. Such prisoners may include human rights activists, opposition figures, critics of a regime, or those who express dissenting opinions or engage in peaceful protests. In authoritarian countries, these individuals are often subject to unjust treatment, trumped-up charges, and human rights violations as they stand for values and freedoms contrary to the government's narrative.

Pope Leo II ( – 28 June 683) was the bishop of Rome from 17 August 682 to his death. He is one of the popes of the Byzantine Papacy. Described by a contemporary biographer as both just and learned, he is commemorated as a saint in the Roman Martyrology on 28 June (3 July, pre-1970 calendar).Early careerLeo was a Sicilian by birth, the son of a man named Paul. He may have ended up being among the many Sicilian clergymen in Rome due to the attacks of the Caliphate on Sicily in the mid-7th century.

Magma is the molten or semi-molten natural material from which all igneous rocks are formed . Magma is found beneath the Earth's surface, primarily in the upper mantle and lower crust, where temperatures are high enough to cause rock to melt. When magma is pushed or forced to the Earth's surface, it can cause a volcanic eruption. During these eruptions, magma (also referred to as lava when outside of the earth's crust) cools down, hardens, and becomes igneous rock. Intrusive igneous rocks, like granite, are formed below the surface while extrusive igneous rocks, like basalt, are created above it.

A bong (also known as a water pipe) is a filtration device generally used for smoking cannabis, tobacco, or other herbal substances. In the bong shown in the photo, the gas flows from the lower port on the left to the upper port on the right.In construction and function, a bong is similar to a hookah, except smaller and especially more portable. A bong may be constructed from any air- and water-tight vessel by adding a bowl and stem apparatus (or slide) which guides air downward to below water level whence it bubbles upward ("bubbler") during use.

Cell division is the process by which a parent cell divides into two or more daughter cells . Cell division usually occurs as a part of a larger cell cycle, which consists of growth, replication of genetic material, and subsequent separation of the cellular contents into distinct new cells. This process plays a vital role in growth, tissue repair, and reproduction in multicellular organisms. There are two types of cell division: mitosis and meiosis. Mitosis results in two identical daughter cells, each with the same number of chromosomes as the parent cell.

The Jagiellonian University (Polish: Uniwersytet Jagielloński (UJ)) is a public research university in Kraków, Poland. Founded in 1364 by King Casimir III the Great, it is the oldest university in Poland and the 13th oldest university in continuous operation in the world. It is often regarded as Poland's most prestigious academic institution. The university has been viewed as a guardian of Polish culture, particularly for continuing operations during the partitions of Poland and the two World Wars, as well as a significant contributor to the intellectual heritage of Europe.The campus of the Jagiellonian University is centrally located within the city of Kraków.

The heart is a muscular organ in most animals, which pumps blood through the blood vessels of the circulatory system. The pumped blood carries oxygen and nutrients to the body, while carrying metabolic waste such as carbon dioxide to the lungs. In humans, the heart is approximately the size of a closed fist and is located between the lungs, in the middle compartment of the chest.In humans, other mammals, and birds, the heart is divided into four chambers: upper left and right atria and lower left and right ventricles.

The governor general of Canada  is the federal viceregal representative of the . The  is head of state of Canada and the 14 other Commonwealth realms, but  resides in  oldest and most populous realm, the United Kingdom. The , on the advice of  Canadian prime minister, appoints a governor general to carry on the Government of Canada in the 's name, performing most of her constitutional and ceremonial duties. The commission is for an indefinite period—known as serving at  Majesty's pleasure—though five years is the usual length of time. Since 1959, it has also been traditional to alternate between anglophone and francophone officeholders—although many recent governors general have been bilingual.

In combinatorics and in experimental design , a Latin square is an n × n array filled with n different symbols, each occurring exactly once in each row and exactly once in each column. Latin squares have been extensively studied and applied for various purposes in mathematics, statistics, and computer science. They play an important role in designing balanced experiments, solving error-correcting code problems, generating cryptographic systems, and constructing combinatorial puzzles like Sudoku. In addition to its practical applications, the analysis of Latin squares has led to numerous interesting mathematical properties and relationships.

Millets  are a group of highly variable small-seeded grasses, widely grown around the world as cereal crops or grains for fodder and human food. Most species generally referred to as millets belong to the tribe Paniceae, but some millets also belong to various other taxa.Millets are important crops in the semiarid tropics of Asia and Africa (especially in India, Mali, Nigeria, and Niger), with 97% of millet production in developing countries. The crop is favored due to its productivity and short growing season under dry, high-temperature conditions.Millets are indigenous to many parts of the world.

David is a masterpiece of Renaissance sculpture, created in marble between 1501 and 1504 by the Italian artist Michelangelo. David is a  marble statue of the Biblical figure David, a favoured subject in the art of Florence.David was originally commissioned as one of a series of statues of prophets to be positioned along the roofline of the east end of Florence Cathedral, but was instead placed in a public square, outside the Palazzo Vecchio, the seat of civic government in Florence, in the Piazza della Signoria, where it was unveiled on 8 September 1504.

A resistojet is a method of spacecraft propulsion (electric propulsion) that provides thrust by heating a, typically non-reactive, fluid. Heating is usually achieved by sending electricity through a resistor consisting of a hot incandescent filament, with the expanded gas expelled through a conventional nozzle.Resistojets have been flown in space since 1965 on board military Vela satellites. However, they only became used in commercial applications in 1980 with the launch of the first satellites in the INTELSAT-V program. Many GEO spacecraft, and all 95 Iridium, used Aerojet MR-501/MR-502 series resistojet engines.

In music performance and notation , legato ( ; Italian for `` tied together '' ; French lié ; German gebunden) is a technique that connects separate notes or phrases smoothly, without gaps or spaces. By doing so, it imparts a sense of fluidity, continuity, and coherence in the performance, and thus significantly enhances the musicality and emotional expression of a piece. Musicians achieve this effect through various means, such as minimizing the time interval between successive notes or by blending articulation techniques like finger legato on string instruments and wind instruments, or the sustain pedal on piano.

Arabidopsis ( rockcress ) is a genus in the family Brassicaceae . They are small flowering plants related to cabbage and mustard.
