Native to Eurasia and Africa, these plants have adapted to a wide range of environments and have significant ecological importance. Arabidopsis thaliana, a species in this genus, has gained popularity as a model organism for studying plant biology due to its simple genetics, fast growth cycle, and compact size. Research on Arabidopsis has contributed significantly to understanding fundamental processes like gene function, plant development, and response to environmental factors. Consequently, this knowledge can be utilized for improving agricultural practices and crop performance.

Year 950 ( CML ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. Significant events during this year included the final phase of Viking invasions and cultural diffusion between Scandinavia, Europe, and the British Isles, leading to increased trade and migration. In addition, King Harald Bluetooth of Denmark extended his rule to parts of Norway and Sweden, thereby laying the groundwork for the establishment of the Kalmar Union in 1397. Also, Cordoba Caliphate expanded and contributed to technological advances in mathematics, astronomy, and literature.

The Etruscan civilization of ancient Italy covered a territory , at its greatest extent , of roughly what is now Tuscany, western Umbria, and northern Lazio. Flourishing from the 9th century BC to the 1st century AD, the Etruscans played a significant role in shaping early Roman art, culture, and society. With distinct advancements in metalworking, agriculture, and maritime trade, they were renowned for their impressive artwork and intricate tomb architecture. Despite their profound influence, much of the Etruscan civilization's records have been lost or not fully deciphered, leaving an air of mystery to one of the greatest civilizations in ancient Italy.

Year 877 (DCCCLXXVII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Summer – King Charles II ("the Bald") sets out for Italy, accompanied by his wife Richilde and a number of his chief vassals. He gives orders for an expedition, but Duke Boso (his brother-in-law) refuses to join the army. At the same time Carloman, son of Louis the German, has crossed the Alps into eastern Lombardy at the head of a Frankish army.

A white cane is a device used by many people who are blind or visually impaired. A white cane primarily allows its user to scan their surroundings for obstacles or orientation marks, but is also helpful for onlookers in identifying the user as blind or visually impaired and taking appropriate care. The latter is the reason for the cane's white colour, which in many jurisdictions is mandatory.Variants Long cane: Designed primarily as a mobility tool used to detect objects in the path of a user. Cane length depends upon the height of a user, and traditionally extends from the floor to the user's sternum.

A wide area network (WAN) is a telecommunications network that extends over a large geographic area. Wide area networks are often established with leased telecommunication circuits.Businesses, as well as schools and government entities, use wide area networks to relay data to staff, students, clients, buyers and suppliers from various locations around the world. In essence, this mode of telecommunication allows a business to effectively carry out its daily function regardless of location. The Internet may be considered a WAN.Design optionsThe textbook definition of a WAN is a computer network spanning regions, countries, or even the world.

Carnival is a Western Christian festive season that occurs before the liturgical season of Lent . The main events typically occur during February or early March, during a period known as Shrovetide. The celebration is marked by feasting, parades, masquerade balls, and various other activities that display vibrant colors, dazzling costumes, and lively music. One of the main goals of Carnival is to indulge in enjoyment and feasting before the more solemn and austere period of Lent begins. This often includes indulging in rich foods and alcohol, attending social gatherings, and participating in local customs and traditions.

Columbina ( in Italian Colombina , meaning `` little dove '' ; in French and English Colombine ) is a stock character in the Commedia dell'Arte, a theatrical art form originating in 16th-century Italy. She is typically portrayed as a witty and cunning servant or the wife, lover, or companion of Harlequin. Columbina is usually dressed in simple attire, donning a petticoat and tight-fitting corset, reflecting her lower-class status, and carries a small bat, known as a "battocchio", which she uses to swat away those who irk her.

Poznań University of Technology , PUT ( Polish name : Politechnika Poznańska ) is a university in Poznań , Poland Poznań University of Technology, PUT (Polish name: Politechnika Poznańska) is a university in Poznań, Poland. Established in 1919, it is one of the oldest and most prestigious technical universities in Poland. With a strong focus on research and innovation, the institution is recognized for its diverse study programs, emphasizing science, engineering, technology, and applied arts. Currently, PUT offers various undergraduate, graduate and PhD programs through its nine faculties.

Dementia manifests as a set of related symptoms, which usually surface when the brain is damaged by injury or disease. The symptoms involve progressive impairments in memory, thinking, and behavior, which negatively impact a person's ability to function and carry out everyday activities. Aside from memory impairment and a disruption in thought patterns, the most common symptoms include emotional problems, difficulties with language, and decreased motivation. The symptoms may be described as occurring in a continuum over several stages. Consciousness is not affected. Dementia ultimately has a significant effect on the individual, caregivers, and relationships in general.

A white cane is a device used by many people who are blind or visually impaired . A white cane primarily serves two purposes: it helps the person navigate their environment and avoid obstacles, and it signals to others that the individual is visually impaired, prompting them to provide assistance when necessary. There are different types of white canes, including the traditional rigid cane, the folding cane, and the support cane. They are made from various lightweight materials such as aluminum, graphite, or fiberglass. Additionally, the white color ensures high visibility to make others aware of the user's visual impairment.

Wool is the textile fibre obtained from sheep and other animals, including cashmere and mohair from goats, qiviut from muskoxen, hide and fur clothing from bison, angora from rabbits, and other types of wool from camelids.Wool consists of protein together with a small percentage of lipids. In this regard it is chemically quite distinct from cotton, which is mainly cellulose.CharacteristicsWool is produced by follicles which are small cells located in the skin. These follicles are located in the upper layer of the skin called the epidermis and push down into the second skin layer called the dermis as the wool fibers grow.

Hex is a two player abstract strategy board game in which players attempt to connect opposite sides of a hexagonal grid through a continuous path of their own pieces. Invented in the 1940s by Danish mathematician and engineer Piet Hein and independently by American mathematician John Nash, Hex combines elements of both bridge-building and territorial conquest. Each player has an allocated color, typically black and white, and takes turns placing their colored piece on the board. The goal is to create an unbroken chain of your own pieces connecting your designated pair of opposite edges while simultaneously blocking your opponent from achieving the same.

Loris is the common name for the strepsirrhine mammals of the subfamily Lorinae ( sometimes spelled Lorisinae ) in the family Loridae. Loris species can be found in the tropical rainforests and woodland areas across South Asia and Southeast Asia, primarily in countries like Sri Lanka, India, Bangladesh, Indonesia, and Borneo. They are well-known for their large round eyes, making them efficient night hunters. These unique nocturnal primates are arboreal creatures, meaning they spend most of their time in trees, and feed primarily on insects, fruits, and vegetation.

A tremor is an involuntary, somewhat rhythmic, muscle contraction and relaxation involving oscillations or twitching movements of one or more body parts. It is the most common of all involuntary movements and can affect the hands, arms, eyes, face, head, vocal folds, trunk, and legs. Most tremors occur in the hands. In some people, a tremor is a symptom of another neurological disorder. A very common tremor is the teeth chattering, usually induced by cold temperatures or by fear.TypesTremor is most commonly classified by clinical features and cause or origin.

A county is a geographical region of a country used for administrative or other purposes in certain modern nations. The term is derived from the Old French   denoting a jurisdiction under the sovereignty of a count (earl) or a viscount. Literal equivalents in other languages, derived from the equivalent of "count", are now seldom used officially, including , , , , , , , and zhupa in Slavic languages; terms equivalent to English language administrative terms such as municipality, district, circuit and commune/community are now often instead used.When the Normans conquered England, they brought the term with them.

A frog is any member of a diverse and largely carnivorous group of short-bodied , tailless amphibians composing the order Anura. Found on every continent except Antarctica, frogs exhibit various adaptations depending on their environment. Their powerful hind legs, typically adapted for leaping or swimming, help them traverse both land and water terrains. Frog species differ in size, with the largest (Goliath frog) measuring up to 32 centimeters and the smallest (P. amauensis) only 7.7 millimeters. Their dietary preferences include insects, worms, and even smaller frogs.

Bi-curious is a term for a person, usually someone who is a heterosexual, who is curious or open about engaging in sexual activity with a person whose sex differs from that of their usual sexual partners. The term is sometimes used to describe a broad continuum of sexual orientation between heterosexuality and bisexuality. Such continuums include mostly-heterosexual or mostly-homosexual, but these can be self-identified without identifying as bisexual. The terms heteroflexible and homoflexible are mainly applied to bi-curious people, though some authors distinguish heteroflexibility and homoflexibility as lacking the "wish to experiment with sexuality" implied by the bi-curious label.

Civil liberties are guarantees and freedoms that governments commit not to abridge, either by constitution, legislation, or judicial interpretation, without due process. Though the scope of the term differs between countries, civil liberties may include the freedom of conscience, freedom of press, freedom of religion, freedom of expression, freedom of assembly, the right to security and liberty, freedom of speech, the right to privacy, the right to equal treatment under the law and due process, the right to a fair trial, and the right to life.

Bristol  is a city, ceremonial county and unitary authority in England. Situated on the River Avon, it is bordered by the ceremonial counties of Gloucestershire, to the north; and Somerset, to the south. Bristol is the most populous city in South West England.The wider Bristol Built-up Area is the eleventh most populous urban area in the United Kingdom.Iron Age hill forts and Roman villas were built near the confluence of the rivers Frome and Avon, and around the beginning of the 11th century, the settlement was known as Brycgstow (Old English "the place at the bridge").

Toilet humour , or potty or scatological humour ( compare scatology ) , is a type of off-colour humour dealing with defecation, urination, and flatulence. It is considered to be base or vulgar by some individuals, often resulting in laughter or amusement from those who find the humor appealing. Generally, toilet humour appeals more to children and adolescents as they go through bodily and maturity developments. Moreover, comedians such as George Carlin and Kevin Hart have dabbled in toilet humour for the shock value, allowing them to highlight certain taboos or to provoke thoughtful reactions from their audiences.

George Catlett Marshall Jr.  (December 31, 1880 – October 16, 1959) was an American army officer and statesman. He rose through the United States Army to become Chief of Staff under Presidents Franklin D. Roosevelt and Harry S. Truman, then served as Secretary of State and Secretary of Defense under Truman. Winston Churchill lauded Marshall as the "organizer of victory" for his leadership of the Allied victory in World War II. After the war, he spent a frustrating year trying and failing to avoid the impending civil war in China.

Coxsackie A virus (CAV) is a cytolytic Coxsackievirus of the Picornaviridae family, an enterovirus (a group containing the polioviruses, coxsackieviruses, and echoviruses).Viral structure and genome Coxsackie A virus is a subgroup of enterovirus A, which are small, non-enveloped, positive-sense, single-stranded RNA viruses. Its protective, icosahedral capsid has an external portion that contains sixty copies of viral proteins (VP1,-2,-3) and an internal portion surrounding the RNA genome containing sixty copies of VP4 viral proteins. This capsid mediates cell entry and elicits the humoral immune responses.

An anti-tank guided missile (ATGM), anti-tank missile, anti-tank guided weapon (ATGW) or anti-armor guided weapon is  a guided missile primarily designed to hit and destroy heavily armored military vehicles. ATGMs range in size from shoulder-launched weapons, which can be transported by a single soldier, to larger tripod-mounted weapons, which require a squad or team to transport and fire, to vehicle and aircraft mounted missile systems.Earlier man-portable anti-tank weapons like anti-tank rifles and magnetic anti-tank mines, generally had very short range, sometimes on the order of metres or tens of metres.

Tristan Tzara (; ; born Samuel or Samy Rosenstock, also known as S. Samyro;  – 25 December 1963) was a Romanian and French avant-garde poet, essayist and performance artist. Also active as a journalist, playwright, literary and art critic, composer and film director, he was known best for being one of the founders and central figures of the anti-establishment Dada movement. Under the influence of Adrian Maniu, the adolescent Tzara became interested in Symbolism and co-founded the magazine Simbolul with Ion Vinea (with whom he also wrote experimental poetry) and painter Marcel Janco.

Kannada (; ಕನ್ನಡ, ; less commonly known as Kanarese) is a Dravidian language spoken predominantly by the people of Karnataka in the southwestern region of India. The language is also spoken by linguistic minorities in the states of Maharashtra, Andhra Pradesh, Tamil Nadu, Telangana, Kerala and Goa; and also by Kannadigas abroad. The language had roughly 43 million native speakers by 2011. Kannada is also spoken as a second and third language by over 12.9 million non-native speakers in Karnataka, which adds up to 56.9 million speakers.

Lindsey Adams Buckingham (born October 3, 1949) is an American singer, musician, songwriter, and producer, best known as the former lead guitarist and male lead singer of the music group Fleetwood Mac from 1975 to 1987 and 1997 to 2018. In addition to his tenure with Fleetwood Mac, Buckingham has released six solo albums and three live albums. As a member of Fleetwood Mac, he was inducted into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame in 1998. Buckingham was ranked 100th in Rolling Stones 2011 list of "The 100 Greatest Guitarists of All Time".

General Dynamics Electric Boat (GDEB) is a subsidiary of General Dynamics Corporation. It has been the primary builder of submarines for the United States Navy for more than 100 years. The company's main facilities are a shipyard in Groton, Connecticut, a hull-fabrication and outfitting facility in Quonset Point, Rhode Island, and a design and engineering facility in New London, Connecticut.HistoryThe company was founded in 1899 by Isaac Rice as the Electric Boat Company to build John Philip Holland's submersible ship designs, which were developed at Lewis Nixon's Crescent Shipyard in Elizabeth, New Jersey.

In chemistry, an aldehyde  is an organic compound containing a functional group with the structure −C(H)=O. The functional group itself (i.e. without the "R" side chain) is known as an aldehyde or formyl group. Aldehydes are common and play important roles in the technology and biological spheres.Structure and bondingAldehydes feature a carbon center that is connected by a double bond to oxygen and a single bond to hydrogen and single bond to a third substituent, which is carbon or, in the case of formaldehyde, hydrogen. The central carbon is often described as being sp2-hybridized.

The Soma cube is a solid dissection puzzle invented by Danish polymath Piet Hein in 1933 during a lecture on quantum mechanics. The puzzle consists of seven unique pieces made from irregular configurations of unit cubes, which can be assembled to form a 3x3x3 cube. Each piece, called a "Soma piece," has a distinct shape and can be combined in numerous ways to construct different patterns and figures. This deceptively simple yet highly versatile toy is more than just a mathematical challenge – it engages logical thinking, creativity, and spatial intelligence.

Shakespearean tragedy is the designation given to most tragedies written by playwright William Shakespeare . Many of his history plays share the qualifiers of a Shakespearean tragedy, but because they are based on real figures throughout the history of England, they were classified as "histories" in the First Folio. Shakespeare's tragedies typically exhibit a hero who is faced with a significant and eventually tragic personal challenge that they must overcome, often causing great suffering for themselves and those around them. These heroes tend to be royal figures, characterized by their extraordinary charisma and intelligence, qualities that set them apart from others.

Éraic (or eric) was the Irish equivalent of the Welsh galanas and the Anglo-Saxon and Scandinavian weregild, a form of tribute paid in reparation for murder or other major crimes. The term survived into the sixteenth century as , by then relating only to compensation for the killing of an Irishman. In the case of homicide, if the attacker fled, the fine had to be paid by the tribe to which he belonged.In Irish mythology the eraic takes an important place. In the Oidheadh Chloinne Tuireann, the children of Tuirreann owe an eraic to Lugh.

In economics, inflation refers to a general progressive increase in prices of goods and services in an economy. When the general price level rises, each unit of currency buys fewer goods and services; consequently, inflation corresponds to a reduction in the purchasing power of money. The opposite of inflation is deflation, a sustained decrease in the general price level of goods and services. The common measure of inflation is the inflation rate, the annualised percentage change in a general price index.Prices will not all increase at the same rates. Attaching a representative value to a set of prices is an instance of the index number problem.

Thomas Becket , also known as Saint Thomas of Canterbury , Thomas of London and later Thomas à Becket ( 21 December c. 1119 – 29 December 1170), was an English archbishop, a pivotal figure during the reign of King Henry II. Known for his fearless defense of the church, he clashed frequently with the king, who believed in monarchial power over ecclesiastical jurisdiction. Thomas's martyrdom at Canterbury Cathedral—orchestrated by the king's knights—garnered international sympathy for the church, and soon, his burial place became a site of pilgrimage.

The Ante-Nicene Fathers, subtitled "The Writings of the Fathers Down to A.D. 325", is a collection of books in 10 volumes (one volume is indexes) containing English translations of the majority of Early Christian writings. The period covers the beginning of Christianity until the promulgation of the Nicene Creed at the First Council of Nicaea.PublicationThe series was originally published between 1867 and 1873 by the Presbyterian publishing house T. & T. Clark in Edinburgh under the title Ante-Nicene Christian Library (ANCL), as a response to the Oxford movement's Library of the Fathers which was perceived as too strongly identified with the Anglo-Catholic movement.

Year 1164 (MCLXIV) was a leap year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Battle of Renfrew: A Norse-Gaelic army led by Lord Somerled, ruler of the Isles, invades Scotland and is routed by the Scottish forces under the command of Walter fitz Alan and Herbert of Selkirk, bishop of Glasgow. England  January 30 – King Henry II tries to delimit spiritual and royal jurisdictions in the Constitutions of Clarendon, written in large part by his councilor Richard de Luci.

In quantum mechanics , counterfactual definiteness ( CFD ) is the ability to speak `` meaningfully '' of the definiteness of the outcomes of measurements that have not been performed. It suggests that well-defined values of observables exist for quantum systems even if no measurement is made. CFD arises from the assumption of a hidden-variable theory, which states that the values of these unmeasured observables have precise and objective existence independent of observation. However, counterfactual definiteness challenges the standard interpretation of quantum mechanics, which postulates the wave function's collapse upon measurement and holds that physical properties do not have precise values until measured.

Anthony John Hancock (12 May 1924 – 25 June 1968) was an English comedian and actor.High-profile during the 1950s and early 1960s, he had a major success with his BBC series Hancock's Half Hour, first broadcast on radio from 1954, then on television from 1956, in which he soon formed a strong professional and personal bond with comic actor Sid James. Although Hancock's decision to cease working with James, when it became known in early 1960, disappointed many at the time, his last BBC series in 1961 contains some of his best-remembered work (including "The Blood Donor" and "The Radio Ham").

The Collatz conjecture in mathematics asks whether repeating two simple arithmetic operations will eventually transform every positive integer into one. It  concerns sequences of integers in which each term is obtained from the previous term as follows: if the previous term is even, the next term is one half of the previous term. If the previous term is odd, the next term is 3 times the previous term plus 1. The conjecture is that these sequences always reach 1, no matter which positive integer is chosen to start the sequence.The conjecture is named after mathematician Lothar Collatz, who introduced the idea in 1937, two years after receiving his doctorate.

In their most common sense , the terms thought and thinking refer to conscious cognitive processes that can happen independently of external stimuli or situations. Thought encompasses a range of mental activities such as problem-solving, reasoning, understanding, perceiving, evaluating, remembering, and planning. These complex functions allow individuals to process information, form beliefs, make decisions, and develop their personal worldview. Thinking, on the other hand, is the active process in which a person consciously directs and organizes their thoughts to achieve a specific goal or task.

Scooby-Doo is an American animated franchise comprising many animated television series produced from 1969 to the present, as well as their derivative media. Writers Joe Ruby and Ken Spears created the original series, Scooby-Doo, Where Are You!, for Hanna-Barbera Productions in 1969. This Saturday-morning cartoon series featured teenagers Fred Jones, Daphne Blake, Velma Dinkley, and Shaggy Rogers, and their talking Great Dane named Scooby-Doo, who solve mysteries involving supposedly supernatural creatures through a series of antics and missteps.Scooby-Doo was originally broadcast on CBS from 1969 to 1976, when it moved to ABC.

Tilburg  is a city and municipality in the Netherlands, in the southern province of North Brabant. With a population of 222,601 (1 July 2021), it is the second-largest municipality in North Brabant and seventh-largest in the Netherlands.Tilburg University is located in Tilburg, as are Avans University of Applied Sciences and Fontys University of Applied Sciences. Tilburg is known for its ten-day-long funfair, held in July each year. The Monday during the funfair is called "Roze Maandag" (Pink Monday), and is primarily LGBT-oriented.There are three railway stations within the municipality: Tilburg, Tilburg Universiteit and Tilburg Reeshof.

Hazardous waste is waste that has substantial or potential threats to public health or the environment.Characteristic hazardous wastes are materials that are known or tested to exhibit one or more of the following hazardous traits:IgnitabilityReactivityCorrosivityToxicityListed hazardous wastes are materials specifically listed by regulatory authorities as hazardous wastes which are from non-specific sources, specific sources, or discarded chemical products.Hazardous wastes may be found in different physical states such as gaseous, liquids, or solids. A hazardous waste is a special type of waste because it cannot be disposed of by common means like other by-products of our everyday lives.

A sports governing body is a sports organization that has a regulatory or sanctioning function.Sports governing bodies come in various forms and sizes, ranging from large international organizations like the International Olympic Committee (IOC) and the Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA), to smaller, more localized associations such as state or provincial-level sporting associations. These governing bodies oversee different aspects of their respective sports, including rules and regulations, discipline and conduct, qualifications and certifications, competitive structures and calendar coordination, promotion and development of the sport, as well as event hosting and management.

Auger electron spectroscopy ( AES ; pronounced in French ) is a common analytical technique used specifically in the study of surfaces and materials. Developed by Pierre Auger, a French physicist, in the 1920s, this powerful method involves the emission of Auger electrons from a sample that has been exposed to an incident electron beam or ion beam. This technique allows scientists and engineers to investigate and characterize the chemical composition, chemical states, and elemental depth distribution of the near surface of various materials such as metals, insulators, and thin films.

was the 70th emperor of Japan, according to the traditional order of succession.Go-Reizei's reign spanned the years 1045–1068.This 11th century sovereign was named after the 10th century Emperor Reizei and go- (後), translates literally as "later;" and thus, he is sometimes called the "Later Emperor Reizei". The Japanese word "go" has also been translated to mean the "second one;" and in some older sources, this emperor may be identified as "Reizei, the second," or as "Reizei II.

The lungs are the primary organs of the respiratory system in humans and most animals including a few fish , serving a crucial role in the process of gas exchange, oxygen intake, and removal of carbon dioxide. They are a pair of spongy, air-filled organs, located on either side of the chest within the ribcage, and are connected to the trachea and bronchi, which aid in transporting air in and out. Capillaries present within lung tissue facilitate the exchange of gases with the bloodstream. Lungs also help in temperature regulation and maintaining the acid-base balance in the body.

Melissa Sue Anderson (born September 26, 1962) is an American-Canadian actress. She began her career as a child actress after appearing in several commercials in Los Angeles. Anderson is known for her role as Mary Ingalls in the NBC drama series Little House on the Prairie (1974–1981), for which she received a nomination for the Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Drama Series. She is also known for film roles that include Vivian in Midnight Offerings (1981), Ginny in the slasher film Happy Birthday to Me (1981), and Alex in the ABC Afterschool Special, Which Mother Is Mine?

Hildegard Frieda Albertine Knef ( ; 28 December 19251 February 2002 ) was a German actress , voice actress , singer, writer, and filmmaker. Born in Ulm, she gained international recognition after World War II for her breakthrough role in the controversial 1946 film "Murderers Among Us." Throughout her career, Knef worked both in Germany and Hollywood, starring in several films like "The Sinner," "Diplomatic Courier," and "The Snows of Kilimanjaro." Her distinct, sultry voice also led to a successful singing career in which she released multiple albums in Germany.

The Himalayas, or Himalaya (; Sanskrit: ,  "snow",  "dwelling", "abode"), are a mountain range in Asia separating the plains of the Indian subcontinent from the Tibetan Plateau. The range has some of the planet's highest peaks, including the highest, Mount Everest. Over 100 peaks exceeding  in elevation lie in the Himalayas. By contrast, the highest peak outside Asia (Aconcagua, in the Andes) is  tall.The Himalayas abut or cross five countries: Bhutan, India, Nepal, China, and Pakistan.

Mecklenburg-Vorpommern (MV; , ), also known by its anglicized name Mecklenburg–Western Pomerania, is a state in the north-east of Germany. Of the country's sixteen states, Mecklenburg-Vorpommern ranks 14th in population, 6th in area, and 16th in population density. Schwerin is the state capital and Rostock is the largest city. Other major cities include Neubrandenburg, Stralsund, Greifswald, Wismar and Güstrow.The state was established in 1945 after World War II through the merger of the historic regions of Mecklenburg and the Prussian Western Pomerania by the Soviet military administration in Allied-occupied Germany.

Enriched uranium is a type of uranium in which the percent composition of uranium-235 ( written 235U ) has been increased through a process called isotope separation. Natural uranium contains around 0.7% of 235U isotope, whereas enriched uranium typically contains 3-5% of 235U. Enrichment is required as 235U is capable of sustaining nuclear fission, which is a critical aspect of nuclear energy and nuclear weapons development. This process results in the production of a highly reactive isotope which releases a great amount of energy during fission. Enriched uranium is used as fuel in commercial nuclear power plants and as material for nuclear weapons in higher concentrations.

( ; `` The Master-Singers of Nuremberg '' ) , WWV 96 , is a music drama , or opera , in three acts by Richard Wagner. Premiering in 1868, this iconic opera is set in mid-16th century Nuremberg and tells the story of Walther von Stolzing, a knight who aspires to join the prestigious Guild of Master-Singers. Blending love, humor, and dramatic tensions, it beautifully encapsulates themes of artistic innovation and tradition. Wagner's score pays homage to the classic German masters while infusing his distinctive compositional techniques, thus enriching the historical and cultural atmosphere of the opera.

Kannada ( ; ಕನ್ನಡ , ; less commonly known as Kanarese ) is a Dravidian language spoken predominantly by the people of Karnataka in the southwestern region of India. According to recent estimates, there are about 43.7 million speakers, making it the third most spoken Dravidian language and one of India's official languages. The richness of Kannada literature dates back over a thousand years and has won eight Jnanpith awards, one of India's highest literary honors. Kannada's written form, derived from ancient Brahmi, has evolved over centuries into various scripts, including modern Kannada script.

Patrick Jake O'Rourke ( November 14 , 1947 – February 15 , 2022 ) was an American libertarian political satirist , author, and journalist. Known for his sharp wit and humorous writing style, O'Rourke's work spanned several decades and influenced countless other writers and commentators. A regular contributor to publications like National Lampoon and Rolling Stone, he also authored several best-selling books, such as "Parliament of Whores" and "Eat the Rich." Through his satire, O'Rourke effectively questioned and criticized prevailing political ideas and engaged a diverse audience in thought-provoking dialogue.

A luge  is a small one- or two-person sled on which one sleds supine (face up) and feet-first. A luger steers by using the calf muscles to flex the sled's runners or by exerting opposite shoulder pressure to the seat. Racing sleds weigh  for singles and  for doubles. Luge is also the name of an Olympic sport.Lugers can reach speeds of 140 km/h (87 mph). Austrian Manuel Pfister reached a top speed of 154 km/h (96 mph) on a track in Whistler, Canada, prior to the 2010 Winter Olympics.

The AGM-114 Hellfire (AGM stands for air-to-ground missile) is an air-to-surface missile (ASM) first developed for anti-armor use, but later models were developed for precision drone strikes against other target types, and have been used in a number of actions aimed to "destroy high-value targets." It was originally developed under the name Heliborne laser, fire-and-forget missile, which led to the colloquial name "Hellfire" ultimately becoming the missile's formal name. It has multi-mission, multi-target precision-strike ability, and can be launched from multiple air, sea, and ground platforms, including the Predator drone.

Hazardous waste is waste that has substantial or potential threats to public health or the environment.Characteristic hazardous wastes are materials that are known or tested to exhibit one or more of the following hazardous traits: ignitability, reactivity, corrosivity, or toxicity. Examples of hazardous waste include solvents, chemical byproducts, batteries, and contaminated materials. Proper management, handling, storage, and disposal of hazardous waste are essential in order to minimize the risks associated with their harmful properties. Failing to manage these dangerous wastes properly can have devastating consequences, such as water and soil pollution, spread of diseases, and potential damage to ecosystems and human life.

The Australian Secret Intelligence Service ( ASIS ) is the foreign intelligence agency of Australia , tasked with the covert collection and analysis of information and intelligence in support of Australia's national security objectives. ASIS operates under the guidance and oversight of the Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade, as well as the Australian Intelligence Community. ASIS was established in 1952 and its primary role includes protecting the interests and citizens of Australia through covert activities abroad, identifying potential threats to national security, countering terrorism, and fostering diplomatic relations. Working closely with international partners, ASIS plays a crucial role in safeguarding Australia's strategic interests globally.

Alain Marie Pascal Prost ( born 24 February 1955 ) is a French retired racing driver . A four-time Formula One World Champion, he is widely regarded as one of the greatest drivers in the history of motorsports. Born in Lorette, Loire, Prost discovered his love for racing at an early age, later starting his professional career in 1976 with Formula Renault. Throughout the 1980s and early 1990s, Prost fiercely competed against iconic rivals like Ayrton Senna, winning numerous Grands Prix. His success and driving technique earned him the nickname "Le Professeur," owing to his intellectual approach to racing.

Tajiks ( , Tājīk , Tājek ; ) are a Persian-speaking Iranian ethnic group native to Central Asia , living primarily in Tajikistan, Afghanistan, and Uzbekistan. They comprise approximately 84% of the population of Tajikistan and 47% of the population in Badakhshan province of Afghanistan. Additionally, they form significant communities in the regions of Panjakent, Penjikent and the Samarqand area of Uzbekistan. Historically, Tajiks played a key role in the Silk Road trade as craftsmen, merchants, and scholars. Their culture is diverse and includes distinctive traditions, languages, literature, arts, music, and cuisine.

SPARC ( Scalable Processor Architecture ) is a reduced instruction set computing ( RISC ) instruction set architecture originally developed by Sun Microsystems in the mid-1980s. SPARC was designed to improve system performance through simplifying processor design, emphasizing the efficient execution of common instructions, and maximizing system scalability. Since its inception, SPARC has seen multiple generations of enhancements, which have kept it relevant and compatible with contemporary technologies. Some of these upgrades include multicore processing capabilities, improved cache coherency mechanisms, and extended instruction sets that allow for additional advanced computations.

Soil is a mixture of organic matter , minerals , gases , liquids , and organisms that together support life . It is the Earth's living skin and plays a vital role in maintaining the balance of nature, which, in turn, ensures the survival and well-being of living creatures on our planet. Soil functions as a foundation for plants, provides nutrients to grow, purifies water through the natural filtration process, and houses microorganisms essential to decomposition and maintaining healthy ecosystems. Soil also serves as a habitat for a wide range of organisms, thus fostering biodiversity.

Wool is the textile fibre obtained from sheep and other animals , including cashmere and mohair from goats , qiviut from muskoxen, and angora from rabbits. Widely used for clothing, wool has several benefits, such as excellent insulation and moisture-wicking properties, providing warmth without bulkiness. It also has natural flame-retardant abilities and is hypoallergenic, which is suitable for people with sensitive skin. Furthermore, wool is an eco-friendly, renewable resource with a long lifespan, adding to its versatility in various industries. Blending it with synthetic fibres can further enhance its durability and other attributes, thus widening its application across numerous sectors.

Chrysippus of Soli ( ; , ; ) was a Greek Stoic philosopher . He was a native of Soli , Cilicia, and later moved to Athens, where he became the third head of the Stoic school, succeeding Cleanthes. Born around 279 BCE, Chrysippus is considered one of the most influential figures in the development of Stoicism. He made significant contributions to logic, ethics, and physics. His approach emphasized rational thinking and self-discipline, advocating that happiness could be attained through understanding the natural order of the world and aligning oneself with it.

A terrarium ( plural : terraria or terrariums ) is usually a sealable glass container containing soil and plants , and can be opened for maintenance or to access the plants inside. Terraria serve as small, self-contained ecosystems, typically mimicking a natural environment such as a tropical rainforest or desert. They are commonly used for growing and showcasing delicate or exotic plant species that require specific living conditions. The terrariums create a stable microclimate that retains moisture and supports healthy plant growth. In addition to plants, terraria can also occasionally house small animals like insects, snails, or reptiles, depending on the type and size of the enclosure.

A knight 's tour is a sequence of moves of a knight on a chessboard such that the knight visits every square exactly once. The exact origin of this intriguing puzzle remains uncertain; however, its conception dates back to ancient times. Throughout the years, it has presented an interesting challenge to enthusiasts, mathematicians, and chess players alike. Many algorithms have been proposed for both open and closed Knight's Tours, where in the latter case, the knight ends its sequence on a square attacking the original starting position. Euler himself explored this intricate problem, adding an enriching angle to this captivating puzzle.

Pietro Mascagni ( 7 December 1863 – 2 August 1945 ) was an Italian composer primarily known for his operas Pietro Mascagni (7 December 1863 – 2 August 1945) was an Italian composer primarily known for his operas, specifically his groundbreaking piece Cavalleria Rusticana (Rustic Chivalry). A forerunner of the verismo style of opera, Cavalleria Rusticana incorporated true-to-life themes, focusing on common people's passions and turmoil. Though he composed a substantial amount of other works, including more operas and several orchestral and chamber pieces, none quite matched the critical acclaim and lasting popularity of his first success.

The PalmPilot Personal and PalmPilot Professional are the second generation of Palm PDA devices produced by Palm Inc ( then a division of 3Com) in 1997. These innovative devices revolutionized personal digital assistants with their lightweight design and advanced functionalities. Featuring a backlit display and an expandable memory slot, PalmPilot quickly became the market leader for portable electronic organization tools. Moreover, the incorporation of Graffiti handwriting recognition system greatly simplified text input on touch screens, influencing many future mobile devices. However, with the introduction of smartphones, the demand for stand-alone PDAs significantly decreased, eventually leading to a decline in PalmPilot's market prominence.

Glam rock is a style of rock music that developed in the United Kingdom in the early 1970s and was performed by musicians who wore outrageous costumes, makeup, and hairstyles, particularly platform shoes and glitter. Characterized by its flamboyant, theatrical, and androgynous look, glam rock sought to challenge societal norms and embrace the ideas of fun and nonconformity. Artists such as David Bowie, T. Rex, Slade, and Sweet emerged as pioneers of the genre, experimenting with unique soundscapes that melded guitar-driven rock with electronic instruments and pop-infused hooks.

ESP most commonly refers to : Extrasensory perception , a paranormal ability Spain ( España ) - ISO three-letter country code for Spain. Extrasensory perception, also known as ESP, is the mysterious ability to receive information without the use of the five traditional senses (sight, hearing, taste, smell, or touch). It encompasses various psychic phenomena such as telepathy, clairvoyance, and psychokinesis. Despite its popular usage in the realms of parapsychology, supernatural folklore, and popular culture, scientific evidence for ESP has remained scarce and inconclusive.

Kristiansund (, ; historically spelled Christianssund and earlier named Fosna) is a municipality on the western coast of Norway in the Nordmøre district of Møre og Romsdal county. The administrative center of the municipality is the town of Kristiansund (established in 1742), which is the major town for the whole Nordmøre region. Other notable settlements in the municipality include the villages of Kvalvåg, Rensvik, and Nedre Frei.The  municipality is the 333rd largest by area out of the 356 municipalities in Norway. Kristiansund is the 51st most populous municipality in Norway with a population of 24,179.

Willow Rosenberg is a fictional character created for the fantasy television series Buffy the Vampire Slayer (1997–2003). She was developed by Joss Whedon and portrayed throughout the TV series by Alyson Hannigan.Willow plays an integral role within the inner circle of friends—called the Scooby Gang—who support Buffy Summers (Sarah Michelle Gellar), a teenager gifted with superhuman powers to defeat vampires, demons, and other evil in the fictional town of Sunnydale. The series begins as Buffy, Willow, and their friend Xander (Nicholas Brendon) are in 10th grade and Willow is a shy, nerdy girl with little confidence.

Isis ( ; Ēse ; ; Meroitic : Wos [ a ] or Wusa ) was a major goddess in ancient Egyptian religion, revered as the mother goddess, protector of the pharaohs, and healer of the sick. She was worshipped as a devoted wife and mother, known for her self-sacrifice, resourcefulness, and magical prowess. Isis became highly regarded among various Mediterranean cultures due to her cult's expansive influence. During the Greco-Roman period, she was associated with aspects of Hellenistic and Roman deities like Hera, Demeter, Aphrodite, and Venus.

Year 876 (DCCCLXXVI) was a leap year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  At the invitation of Benevento, the newly-restored Byzantine fleet appears in the waters off Otranto. On the orders of Emperor Basil I, the Byzantines sail up the Adriatic Sea and reconquer part of southern Italy. The city of Bari is occupied in the name of the Byzantine Empire. Instead of holding it for his 'ally' Adelchis of Benevento, Basil makes it the capital of the new Byzantine Theme of Longobardia.

The covalent radius , rcov , is a measure of the size of an atom that forms part of one covalent bond. It represents the approximate distance between the nucleus of an atom and the outermost shell of its electrons engaged in bond formation. The value of rcov may vary depending on the type of bonding environment, but typically falls between 30 to 200 picometers. rcov plays an essential role in understanding molecular geometry and predicting the shape of a molecule. The larger the rcov value, the bigger the size of the atom, thus affecting its bond strength and the molecule's stability.

Turbo Pascal is a software development system that includes a compiler and an integrated development environment ( IDE ) for the Pascal programming language, developed by Borland Software Corporation. It was initially released in 1983 and gained widespread popularity in the late 80s and early 90s. Turbo Pascal streamlined the coding process by providing syntax-highlighting, autocomplete features, and advanced debugging capabilities. Its user-friendly nature and competitive pricing allowed programmers to write fast and efficient code, revolutionizing the development landscape. Turbo Pascal's influence on programming and computer science is significant, contributing to the creation of future IDEs and object-oriented programming.

Heliox is a breathing gas mixture of helium ( He ) and oxygen ( O2 ) .Heliox is a medical treatment option that is commonly used for patients with respiratory conditions, such as asthma, bronchitis, and chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD). By incorporating a lighter, less dense gas like helium, heliox enables easier airflow within the respiratory system and allows for more effective gas exchange within the lungs. This improved airway resistance reduction provides immediate relief to patients who are struggling to breathe due to severe airway obstruction or constriction.

The AGM-114 Hellfire ( AGM stands for air-to-ground missile ) is an air-to-surface missile ( ASM ) first developed for anti-armor use by the United States Army in the early 1980s. The Hellfire's versatility has led it to be used extensively on rotary and fixed-wing aircraft, as well as unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs). Featuring semi-active laser guidance or radar frequency seekers, the Hellfire provides precision strikes for various target types, such as tanks, bunkers, and enemy combatants. Today, the Hellfire missile serves as a primary armament for numerous NATO countries and has been integrated into several conflict operations across the globe.

Michael I ( ; 25 October 1921 – 5 December 2017 ) was the last King of Romania , reigning from 20 July 1927 to 8 June 1930 and then again from 6 September 1940 to 30 December 1947. Born into the House of Romania, he was a son of King Carol II and Queen Helen. As a child, Michael was forced to rule following his father's forced abdication, making him one of the youngest monarchs in world history. His second reign came when Carol II fled in the face of an Axis invasion.

Michael I ( ; 25 October 1921 – 5 December 2017) was the last King of Romania, reigning from 20 July 1927 to 8 June 1930 and again from 6 September 1940 until his forced abdication on 30 December 1947.Shortly after Michael's birth, his father, Crown Prince Carol of Romania, had become involved in a controversial relationship with Magda Lupescu. In 1925, Carol was pressured to renounce his rights to the throne and moved to Paris in exile with Lupescu. In 1927, Michael ascended the throne, following the death of his grandfather King Ferdinand I.

In chemistry , an aldehyde is an organic compound containing a functional group with the structure −C ( H ) =O, in which a carbon atom is double-bonded to an oxygen atom and single-bonded to a hydrogen atom. The presence of the aldehyde functional group plays a crucial role in the overall properties, behavior, and reactivity of these molecules. Aldehydes are found in various industrial and biological processes. They are widely used in the synthesis of perfumes, dyes, polymers, solvents, and other organic compounds. Examples of naturally occurring aldehydes include formaldehyde, acetaldehyde, and vanillin (the primary component of vanilla flavor).

Near Earth Asteroid Rendezvous – Shoemaker (NEAR Shoemaker), renamed after its 1996 launch in honor of planetary scientist Eugene Shoemaker, was a robotic space probe designed by the Johns Hopkins University Applied Physics Laboratory for NASA to study the near-Earth asteroid Eros from close orbit over a period of a year. It was the first spacecraft to successfully orbit an asteroid and also land on an asteroid. In February 2000, the mission succeeded in closing in with the asteroid and afterwards orbited it several times. On February 12, 2001, the mission succeeded in touching down on the asteroid.

The Campeonato Nacional de Liga de Primera División , commonly known simply as Primera División in Spain , and as LaLiga internationally, is the top professional football league in Spain. Founded in 1929, it consists of 20 teams competing to be crowned champions. Over the years, powerhouse teams such as FC Barcelona, Real Madrid, and Atlético Madrid have dominated the competition, drawing millions of fans and world-class players. LaLiga not only garners tremendous excitement within Spain but is followed globally, thanks in large part to famous players such as Lionel Messi, Cristiano Ronaldo, and Antoine Griezmann showcasing their talent on this prestigious stage.

Delhi (;  Dillī;  Dillī;  Dêhlī), officially the National Capital Territory (NCT) of Delhi, is a city and a union territory of India containing New Delhi, the capital of India. Straddling the Yamuna river, but primarily its western or right bank, Delhi shares borders with the state of Uttar Pradesh in the east and with the state of Haryana in the remaining directions. The NCT covers an area of . According to the 2011 census, Delhi's city proper population was over 11 million, while the NCT's population was about 16.8 million.

Aden ( ,  ;   Yemeni: ) is a city, and since 2015, the temporary capital of Yemen, near the eastern approach to the Red Sea (the Gulf of Aden), some  east of the strait Bab-el-Mandeb. Its population is approximately 800,000 people. Aden's natural harbour lies in the crater of a dormant volcano, which now forms a peninsula joined to the mainland by a low isthmus. This harbour, Front Bay, was first used by the ancient Kingdom of Awsan between the 7th to 5th centuries BC. The modern harbour is on the other side of the peninsula.

Ravenna ( , , also ; ) is the capital city of the Province of Ravenna , in the Emilia-Romagna region of Northern Italy. It was the capital of the Western Roman Empire from 402 until its fall in 476, as well as the Ostrogothic Kingdom, and later, the Exarchate of Ravenna, a Byzantine enclave in Italy. Ravenna's historic significance has earned it recognition as a UNESCO World Heritage site, home to exquisite Byzantine mosaics and numerous churches, mausoleums, and baptisteries, making it an important center for culture, art, and architecture.

Oak Ridge National Laboratory ( ORNL ) is a U.S. multiprogram science and technology national laboratory sponsored by the U.S. Department of Energy (DOE) and managed by UT-Battelle. It is located in Oak Ridge, Tennessee. Established in 1943, ORNL is one of the largest and most prestigious research facilities in the country, focused on interdisciplinary research in fields such as advanced materials, nuclear science, clean energy technologies, climate change, and supercomputing. As a key DOE facility, it employs over 5,000 experts who work to deliver groundbreaking scientific discoveries and cutting-edge technologies that address crucial issues affecting modern society, the environment, and energy production.

Henry Richard Enfield ( born 30 May 1961 ) is an English comedian , actor , writer , and director . Born in Sussex, England, he first gained widespread recognition through his partnership with Paul Whitehouse on their long-running sketch comedy show, "Harry Enfield and Chums." Throughout his career, Enfield has portrayed a diverse range of comedic characters on both television and film. Additionally, he has also penned multiple comedy scripts, making him a well-rounded comedic genius. Over the years, Enfield's impressive array of work has garnered critical acclaim and several awards, cementing his status as one of the leading figures in British comedy.

Year 1054 (MLIV) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Sultan Tughril leads a large Seljuk army out of Azerbaijan into Armenia, possibly to consolidate his frontier, while providing an incentive to his Turkoman allies in the form of plunder. Tughril divides his army into four columns, ordering three to veer off to the north to raid into central and northern Armenia, while he takes the fourth column towards Lake Van. The Seljuk Turks capture and sack the fortress city of Artchesh, after an 8-day siege.

The European Organization for Nuclear Research , known as CERN (; ; derived from the name ), is a European research organization that operates the largest particle physics laboratory in the world. Established in 1954, the organization is based in a northwest suburb of Geneva on the Franco–Swiss border and has 23 member states. Israel is the only non-European country granted full membership. CERN is an official United Nations Observer.The acronym CERN is also used to refer to the laboratory, which in 2019 had 2,660 scientific, technical, and administrative staff members, and hosted about 12,400 users from institutions in more than 70 countries.

Catalase is a common enzyme found in nearly all living organisms exposed to oxygen ( such as bacteria , plants , and animals). It plays a crucial role in the detoxification and protection against oxidative stress by catalyzing the breakdown of hydrogen peroxide, a potentially harmful compound, into water and oxygen. This essential biological function is especially significant in cellular environments, as high levels of hydrogen peroxide can cause cellular damage and premature aging. Thus, the presence and activity of catalase is critical to ensuring the proper functioning, health, and longevity of various life forms, as well as maintaining the delicate balance within ecosystems.

In the history of cryptography, Typex (alternatively, Type X or TypeX) machines were British cipher machines used from 1937. It was an adaptation of the commercial German Enigma with a number of enhancements that greatly increased its security. The cipher machine (and its many revisions) was used until the mid-1950s when other more modern military encryption systems came into use.DescriptionLike Enigma, Typex was a rotor machine. Typex came in a number of variations, but all contained five rotors, as opposed to three or four in the Enigma.

A monopropellant rocket ( or `` monochemical rocket '' ) is a rocket that uses a single chemical as its propellant for thrust generation. Unlike conventional bipropellant rockets, which require two separate components – fuel and an oxidizer, a monopropellant rocket relies on the decomposition or catalytic reaction of the singular propellant to produce energy. Monopropellant rockets are primarily used for attitude control or maneuvering in space vehicles, and satellites. The most common monopropellant is hydrazine, known for its stability and controllability. The major advantages of monopropellant rockets include their simplicity, reliability, and higher efficiency compared to traditional systems, albeit at a lower overall thrust output.

Year 881 ( DCCCLXXXI ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) of the Julian calendar. During this year, many significant events occurred that had lasting impacts on Europe and the world at large. Political power dynamics continued to shift as kings and emperors rose and fell in various regions, influencing their territories for centuries to come. Inventions, technological advancements, and important literature were being introduced, paving the way for future innovations in various fields. Additionally, natural phenomena like earthquakes and eclipses would bring about intriguing discussions among scholars, leaving traces of history to be unraveled in years to come.

Year 1036 (MXXXVI) was a leap year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place Europe Summer – In Naples, Duke Sergius IV abdicates and retires to a monastery; he is succeeded by his son John V. A Zirid expeditionary force invades Sicily and takes Palermo from the Normans, but fails to fully reconquer the island. England  February 5 – Edward the Confessor's younger brother Alfred Aetheling is blinded and murdered, in an apparent attempt to seize the throne of England from Harold I. Africa  June 13 – Caliph al-Zahir li-i'zaz Din Allah dies after a 16-year reign.
